<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 2ndLd-Writethru   08-11 0907</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0789,0930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Killing in Burma, but Hints at Reconciliation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th pvs, ``We understand ...' to include
report on list of demands. PICKS up 10th pvs, `Premier Tun Tin ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Burmese troops killed at least 15 more people Thursday, a crowd
of thousands had soldiers surrounded in a Rangoon suburb, and the
government gave its first hint that an end to the protests might
bring concessions.
   Coupled with the offer to consider the people's ``legitimate
requests,'' however, was a stern declaration by the armed forces
commander that Burma is threatened by the ``anarchy of the
violence-makers.''
   Rangoon radio said protesters, who demand that President Sein
Lwin be ousted, were preparing firebombs and planning to
``escalate'' violence, but Western diplomats in the Burmese capital
reported no large demonstrations Thursday. Tens of thousands had
been in the streets the previous two days.
   A senior Western diplomat in Rangoon said all gasoline stations
were closed Thursday, apparently as a precaution against arson and
the manufacture of firebombs.
   Broadcasts monitored in Bangkok, Thailand, said 15 people were
killed and 81 wounded in the third day of street confrontations, in
which security forces have opened fire repeatedly to disperse
crowds. According to official figures, 95 people have been killed
and 240 wounded in Burma since violence began Tuesday.
   The radio said Thursday that 10,000 people surrounded an army
unit the day before in the Rangoon suburb of North Okkalapa,
shooting had occurred and reinforcements were sent in. It said
three aircraft dropped leaflets warning that security forces would
shoot unless the crowds dispersed.
   Diplomats reported clashes in the area Thursday. The radio said
without giving details that the only large demonstration in the
country involved 1,000 people in North Okkalapa.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
there were reports of continued demonstrations in the suburbs of
Rangoon and in the major northern city of Mandalay.
   ``We understand central Rangoon appears to be quiet with a heavy
troop presence in that part of the city,'' she said.
   Students have circulated a list of demands to diplomats, The New
York Times reported in its Friday editions. Among the demands were
holding a multiparty referendum, freedom for jailed government
opponents, an end to martial law and a reduction in the cost of
living, the newspaper reported. It said it was unclear whether the
demands had been presented to the government.
   Premier Tun Tin promised on Rangoon radio Thursday night that
authorities ``will seriously consider legitimate requests of the
people ... in accordance with the law.''
   He said planned economic reforms will be implemently urgently to
improve living conditions, but only if the violence ends. Diplomats
say economic crisis and rampant inflation are among the reasons for
the uprising that began after Sein Lwin, a former general, assumed
power two weeks ago in the nation of 38 million people.
   Sau Maung, the armed forces commander, said in the same
broadcast the army would continue its tough response. He said
soldiers were restrained at first, but that changed when
``dishonest elements'' took over the protests. ``The people are now
facing anarchy of the violence-makers,'' he said.
   Diplomats said security forces in North Okkalapa, where the
soldiers were surrounded, were attacked Wednesday by residents
armed with weapons either captured or provided by defectors from
the military.
   They cited unconfirmed reports that at least two truckloads of
soldiers joined the protesters.
   Earlier radio reports said mobs beheaded three policemen
Wednesday in North Okkalapa and South Okkalapa.
   The senior Western diplomat said protesters initially tried to
avoid clashes but became enraged after unprovoked killings Tuesday.
On Wednesday, he said, protesters began confronting soldiers and
``in effect defying them to shoot.''
   He said protesters began piling bricks, trees and stones on
streets Wednesday night to block military vehicles. He said some
firearms may have been captured, but most weapons werek such
makeshift items as spears made of stripped umbrellas.
   ``These were unarmed, peaceful demonstrators, and they still are
mostly, but now they've gotten more violent,'' he said.
   Protesters were said to have taken over Pegu, about 45 miles
northeast of Rangoon, with no response from the army, the diplomat
said.
   Travelers from Rangoon said the city of 3.5 million was at a
virtual standstill, with most shops, offices and markets closed.
They said buildings were pocked by bullets and bloodstains marked
the locations of street fights.
   Martial law was imposed on the capital after a student march
Aug. 3 and an 8 p.m.-4 a.m. curfew took effect Tuesday.
   Mrs. Oakley said in Washington that a new advisory was issued
for Americans, warning them not to travel to Burma. Britain, France
and Japan have issued such warnings and France advised French
tourists in Burma to leave.
   Britain denied on Thursday earlier reports that Burmese troops
clubbed the British military attache with rifle butts during
protest violence in Rangoon. The Foreign Office said Col. Michael
Bremridge was held for about two hours in an identity card mixup,
but ``was treated perfectly reasonably and sensibly.''
   The protests are by far the largest since a coup by Ne Win ended
democracy in Burma in 1962. Sein Lwin became the nation's president
and head of the government party when Ne Win resigned after 26
years in power.
   Protesters accuse Sein Lwin of ruthlessly suppressing student
riots in March and June, when he was an army general, and earlier
harsh measures against dissenters.
</TEXT>
