<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Iacocca     08-11 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Iacocca,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iacocca Says He And Ex-Boss Ford Were `Buddies'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca says he
holds no grudges against Henry Ford II for firing him a decade ago,
preferring to remember the times when they went hunting, went to
parties or ``caroused Europe together.''
   ``My difficulty with Henry Ford was over long before he died
last year,'' the 63-year-old Iacocca wrote in Aug. 29's Fortune
magazine, which was made available Wednesday.
   The grandson of Ford's founder died last September after more
than 40 years at the helm of the nation's second-largest automaker.
   Iacocca, who rose to stardom in the auto industry after creating
the super-popular Mustang, was fired after more than 20 years at
Ford Motor Co. in 1978. He has been at Chrysler since then and is
credited with putting the once-troubled company back on its feet
with the help of $1.2 billion in government-guaranteed loans.
   ``A lot of people told me Henry Ford II did me a favor 10 years
ago by firing me,'' Iacocca wrote. ``They said that if I had stayed
at Ford, I would have been in a comfortable ivory tower. ... By
getting canned in 1978 I got thrown into a situation where I became
a leader.''
   Iacocca had few kind words to say about Henry Ford II in his
first book, ``Iacocca: An Autobiography,'' but in the Fortune
article, he recalled how he and Ford ``hunted together, we went to
parties together, we caroused Europe together.''
   ``I remember the 16 good years, and not the two bad ones in 1977
and 1978.''
</TEXT>
