<DOCNO> AP880811-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EliotAnniversary     08-11 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eliot Anniversary,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jews Disagree About Fund Named For T.S. Eliot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish opinion has been split by a library fund to
mark the 100th birthday of poet T.S. Eliot, who critics say was
notoriously anti-Semitic. Three distinguished Jews are among the
fund's supporters.
   ``T.S. Eliot's writings were undoubtedly anti-Semitic and Jews
will not be alone in having qualms about supporting a fund to mark
his centenary,'' said Hayim Pinner, secretary-general of the Board
of Deputies of British Jews.
   Eliot was born in St. Louis in 1888, became a British subject
and died in Britain in 1965. He won the Nobel Prize for literature
and Britain's coveted Order of Merit.
   He was chairman of the privately run London Library, which has
appealed for $170,000 to establish a trust fund in his name and is
inviting American donations. The fund's purpose is to pay the
subscriptions of students and scholars who otherwise could not
afford to use the library.
   Jews associated with the appeal include Lewis Golden, the
library's honorary treasurer and a member of the appeal committee,
and patrons Sir Isaiah Berlin, the Oxford University philosopher,
and Lord Goodman, a leading London lawyer and arts enthusiast.
   ``The London Library would have done better to honor one of any
number of great British writers and poets untainted by race hatred
at its ugliest,'' Pinner said.
   David Nathan, deputy editor of the weekly Jewish Chronicle,
raised the issue originally. He said he believes Eliot's writings
helped block the escape of some Jews from Nazi Germany.
   ``I think Eliot was responsible in part for creating a climate
of opinion in the 1930s in which American and British politicians
and bureaucrats closed the doors to many people who could have been
rescued from the gas ovens,'' Nathan said in an interview.
   Golden granted that at least one Eliot work contained
``objectionable'' phrases, but said the poet ultimately believed
``our culture is based on the legacy of Greece, Rome and Israel.''
   Nathan said Golden had responded to his complaints by saying
``he wasn't aware of Eliot's anti-Semitism.''
   ``I have the most enormous admiration for Eliot as a poet,''
Nathan said. ``If I thought he was second rate, I wouldn't have
bothered.''
   In its appeal, the library says Eliot is ``one of the greatest
figures of 20th century literature. His influence is worldwide.''
   Critics say Eliot's anti-Semitism is blatant, including the
writing of ``jew'' without a capital J to emphasize inferiority.
   In the 1927 poem ``Burbank with a Baedeker: Bleistein with a
Cigar,'' Eliot wrote: ``The rats are underneath the piles. The jew
is underneath the lot.''
   Eliot said in a lecture in January 1933, as Adolf Hitler was
about to take power in Germany: ``Reasons of race or religion
combine to make any large number of free-thinking Jews undesirable
... and a spirit of excessive tolerance is to be deprecated.''
   Nathan said Eliot dehumanized Jews ``and that allows racism of
all kinds.''
   Golden commented: ``Although one cannot excuse it, the
objectionable poem by Eliot has to be read in the context of the
attitude prevalent in the 1920s and expressed in some quarters in
America and elsewhere, long before the dreadful consequences of the
Nazis' frenzied use of anti-Semitism as a political weapon burst
upon the world.
   ``What could be more indicative of Eliot's ultimate feelings is
contained in his book `Notes Towards a Definition of Culture,'
published in 1948, where he more than once mentions that our
culture is based on the legacy of Greece, Rome and Israel.''
   Michael Hastings, who explored Eliot's strained first marriage
in a 1985 play called ``Tom and Viv,'' said: ``Even after he got
the Nobel Prize, Eliot continued to write dozens of racial
limericks to his friends, referring to kikes and niggers. I don't
think it's excusable for a Nobel laureate to behave in that way.''
   Peter Forbes, editor of Britain's leading poetry magazine,
Poetry Review, said: ``I think the anti-Semitism detracts from
Eliot's status as a major culural figure.
   ``Many people feel uneasy with his status as a cultural guru
because of his anti-Semitism, but nobody ever suspected Eliot of
being a progressive. He was a famous reactionary.''
   Thomas Stearns Eliot, poet, sometime bank clerk, playwright and
publisher, was born in St. Louis on Sept. 26, 1888, and became a
British subject in 1927. His most famous poem was ``The Waste
Land.''
   The centenary will be an international event, including
conferences, lectures, exhibitions and poetry readings in Britain,
the United States, France, Spain and Japan.
</TEXT>
