<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupercomputerKids     08-11 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supercomputer Kids,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-agers Compete for Oh `S-o-o-o Awesome' Supercomputer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the beginning of the summer, the 16
high school computer jocks were in awe of the $1 million
supercomputer like the one ETA Systems Inc. will award to one of
their schools Friday.
   But as their six-week competition doing research projects on the
ETA10-P winds up, some of the students admit they have become a
little blase.
   ``When we first got here, the supercomputer looked s-o-o-o big,
s-o-o-o wonderful, and it really is. Don't get me wrong,'' said
15-year-old Doreen Pettus, who will be a junior this fall at North
Florida Christian High School in Tallahassee.
   ``But the closer you get to it, I mean, it's just crazy because
the kids back home think it's s-o-o-o awesome. And we're here and
we got used to it,'' Miss Pettus said.
   The teen-age competitors, who worked on individual projects but
are being judged in teams representing four high schools, now share
professionals' complaints about the computer's ``slowness'' in
making calculations, she said. The supercomputer has a capacity of
375 million operations per second, according to ETA Systems.
   ``You get a different perspective of things when you've been
here,'' Miss Pettus said.
   The contest was the brainchild of ETA's president, Carl
Ledbetter, who said he hopes it will encourage Americans to focus
more attention on math and science education.
   Entry forms were mailed to all public and private high schools
in the country, although company officials expected no more than 50
schools to apply. They were amazed when 1,475 schools did, he said.
   The Educational Testing Service helped the company winnow the
applications to 99 semifinalists and then the final four high
schools, Ledbetter said.
   In addition to North Florida Christian, the finalists are
Montgomery Blair High School in Silver Spring, Md.; Thomas
Jefferson High School for Science and Technology in Alexandria,
Va.; and James Logan High School in Union City, Calif.
   The ``Superquest'' contest is being judged by an independent
panel of five scientists headed by Kenneth Wilson, who received the
1982 Nobel Prize for his work on computational physics. The winning
school will be announced Friday night at a formal dinner, with the
contestants' parents in attendance.
   Besides the supercomputer, the top school will get two years of
operating costs, which are worth $7,000 to $10,000 a month, and a
company employee to advise them on the machine's use.
   The other schools won't go home empty-handed, though. Each will
receive a $50,000 Control Data Corp. Cyber 910 graphics work
station, and each student is getting $3,000 for participating. ETA
Systems is Control Data's supercomputer division.
   This year's contestants have been a serious group. ``There's a
little game playing but not a lot. I've actually brought games in
to try and relieve the tension,'' said Neil Lincoln, the company's
supercomputer architect.
   Miss Pettus decorated her corner of an ETA Systems workroom in
typical schoolgirl fashion with a high school pennant and a poster,
but her description of her project belied her 15 years.
   ``I think the correct title is `A Life Cycle Factor Simulation
of the Southern Bald Eagle,''' she said.
   She explained that she had obtained data about eagles in Florida
for the last 15 years. Her model was created to try to mimic that
data and produce the same results so she could project what will
happen to the eagles.
   Around the corner, 17-year-old Daniel Mall, a senior at
Montgomery Blair, talked with equal seriousness abut his project.
   ``Basically, the purpose of my program is to design some type of
material surface structure to apply to boat hulls,'' he said. The
objective is to reduce drag.
   Nearby, his 16-year-old teammate, Sven Hiralal Khatri, also a
senior, was intent on his computational program evaluating the
growth of urban regions from Washington, D.C., to Boston with
respect to time.
   Ledbetter acknowledges that the contest, in addition to focusing
attention on science and math education, also is powerful
advertising for the 5-year-old company.
   ``It also happened to be coincidental with the fact that for the
first time in the history of the computer industry, it's possible
to put a supercomputer in a high school,'' he said.
   ``For the first time at ETA, we have developed a supercomputer
that's air-cooled. It's a little tiny thing. You think of them as
being big behemoths,'' he said.
   Ledbetter said he hopes ETA Systems can hire some of this year's
contestants. The only problem, he said, is having to wait until
they've earned their college degrees.
</TEXT>
