<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalStrike     08-11 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Strike,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nurses Narrowly Approve Contract Vote at Public Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nurses at San Francisco General Hospital
and other public facilities narrowly approved a new one-year
contract Wednesday night, averting a health care emergency at city
hospitals.
   About 1,500 nurses at private hospitals remained on strike, but
resumed talks with hospital administrators.
   The 1,600 public nurses represented by Local 790 of the United
Public Employees voted 320-307 for the new pact, said Donna Gerber,
field representative for the union.
   Members of Local 250 and Affiliated Hospitals, a group of
private hospitals, began their first day of formal mediation
Tuesday. About 4,000 nurses and support workers are striking
against eight private hospitals.
   San Francisco General and Laguna Honda, several health care
clinics and one jail faced a strike by Local 790 nurses if the new
municipal contract had not been ratified.
   The nurses' negotiating committee had recommended that the
contract be approved.
   The private hospitals are negotiating with the CNA and Local 250
in a group called Affiliated Hospitals.
   CNA, which has not yet resumed talks, is on strike at
Children's, St. Mary's, Marshal Hale, Mount Zion and St. Francis in
San Francisco and Seton in nearby Daly City. Local 250 is striking
at those, plus Pacific Presbyterian.
   An eighth facility, French Hospital, joined the strike Saturday.
Their talks are being held separately.
   Local 250's dispute centers on health benefits and sick leave.
The nurses are fighting for pay increases.
</TEXT>
