<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainDerailment     08-11 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say No Serious Injuries In Derailment, But Evacuations
Ordered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELM GROVE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About two dozen railroad cars derailed
and piled up along the Soo Line track here Wednesday, forcing about
1,000 people to evacuate homes and businesses, but no one was
seriously hurt, authorities said.
   Residents withinin a half-mile radius of the site were sent to a
nearby church because some tanker cars were carrying hazardous
materials, Waukesha County emergency officials said.
   Brookfield Fire Chief Jim Mehring said initial checks showed no
known leaks in the tanker cars, which carried propane, methanol and
some type of caustic acid. A hazardous materials team was sent to
the scene.
   Police and fire departments from neighboring communities were
assisting in cleanup operations.
   Waukesha County Sheriff Lt. Terry Martorano said he did not
expect residents would be allowed to return until Thursday, after
heavy equipment was brought from Chicago to unstack the cars.
   Authorities said a tanker car apparently lost a wheel gear
causing the the 24-car derailment in the 110-car train.
</TEXT>
