<DOCNO> AP880811-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EPA-Lead     08-11 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA-Lead,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Issues Plan to Reduce Lead in Drinking Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists say a new government
proposal to reduce dangerous lead in drinking water supplies is a
step in the right direction, but one that doesn't go far enough.
   The Environmental Protection Agency announced Wednesday that it
plans to issue rules requiring half the nation's water plants,
about 53,000, to treat water so that it contains less lead. The
metal causes a variety of harmful physical and mental effects.
   EPA administrator Lee A. Thomas said the plan will have ``far
more effect on the drinking water system than any rule we have ever
put up.''
   It also could cost some consumers, those served by small water
treatment plants, up to $367 a year. Most consumers could expect
much smaller increases of between $10 and $30 annually.
   While environmentalists said they support any step that will
reduce lead in drinking supplies, they said EPA's proposal does not
address the problem of lead contamination from the pipes that carry
water from the plant to the consumer's tap.
   Marion Sills of the Environmental Defense Fund, a lobbying
group, said EPA's proposals were a ``good first tier,'' but they
don't provide enough protection. If EPA's solutions fail to
eliminate the lead at the consumer's tap, there is little than can
be done, she said.
   ``The proposal constitutes an abdication of EPA's responsibility
for ensuring that Americans can turn on their faucets and receive
drinking water free from harmful levels of lead,'' said Stephanie
Pollack of the Boston-based Conservation Law Foundation of New
England.
   Concentrations of lead in the blood have been associated with a
variety of health problems. Lead can impair mental ability in
children, cause premature births and delay physical and mental
development of babies. In adults it can interfere with hearing and
increase blood pressure, and, at high levels, cause kidney damage
and anemia.
   Under EPA's plan:
   _Water plant operators would be required to begin a corrosion
control program by treating water with chemicals if water at the
consumer's tap has lead levels greater than 10 parts per billion.
The program also would be required for acidic water.
   Lead often enters water _ particularly acidic or corrosive water
_ after it leaves the treatment plant. Acidity is an indicator of
corrosive water, which causes pipes to leach lead before it reaches
the tap. Thomas said there is a ``dramatic reduction'' in lead if
the acidity of the water is reduced.
   _If the average lead levels are greater than 10 parts per
billion, water suppliers must conduct a public education program,
which would include helping consumers have their water tested.
   Some consumers might have to pay to have lead pipes, which the
U.S. banned two years ago, replaced in their homes. They also may
have to allow water to run from the tap for a time before drinking.
   _Water treatment plants would have to reduce lead to a maximum
contaminant level of 5 parts per billion. Lead in source water
supplies is less of a problem than lead collected in pipes.
   Environmentalists had hoped to see stiffer maximum contaminant
levels on water at the consumer's tap. Currently, the law says the
levels must be no higher than 50 parts per billion.
   But Thomas and other EPA officials said regulating contaminant
levels was too complicated. So the new proposals, if they become
law, will supersede the contaminant level requirement.
   Before the EPA puts the regulations into effect, officials must
advertise them and solicit comment.
   Congress has given the government a deadline of June 1989 to do
something about lead levels. In 1986, Congress amended the Safe
Drinking Water Act to deal with lead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reparations Bjt   08-11 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reparations, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reparations Bill Apologizes for Internment of Japanese-Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law authorizing reparations for
Japanese-Americans interned during World War II helps lift ``an
unjust burden of shame'' borne by 120,000 loyal citizens for four
decades, says a congressman who was among those incarcerated.
   ``Today is a moment of great emotion for me, a day when hopes
and dreams have become reality,'' said Rep. Norman Mineta,
D-Calif., as President Reagan signed the bill Wednesday.
   The bill authorizes tax-free payments of $20,000 to each of the
approximately 60,000 surviving veterans of wartime camps, many of
whom spent three years in internment.
   The Japanese-Americans were rounded up and sent to the camps
under an order issued by President Franklin D. Roosevelt after the
Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor, Hawaii, on Dec. 7, 1941, plunged
the United States into World War II. Many Japanese-Americans
lobbied for the legislation for years. It finally cleared Congress
by a 257-156 vote in the House on Aug. 4.
   Reagan originally objected to some features of the bill, saying
it would be too costly, but he backed the final version which calls
for a fund of $1.2 billion, with appropriations in any one year
limited to $500 million. Legislation providing the actual money
must still be enacted.
   In signing the bill, Reagan said, ``What is most important in
this bill has less to do with property than with honor. For here we
admit a wrong. Here we reaffirm our commitment as a nation to equal
justice under the law.''
   Mineta, who as a child of 10 was taken to an internment camp in
Wyoming, said, ``Today the unjust burden of shame which 120,000
loyal Americans have carried for 46 painful years has at long last
been lifted.''
   Many of the 250 Japanese-Americans who attended the signing
ceremony said it is the principle of the bill, not the money, that
matters.
   Among them were six members of one family _ now scattered in
California, Georgia and Oregon _ who were taken from a farm near
Stockton, Calif., to an internment camp at Rohr, Ark.
   Dr. Walter Emori, now 47 and an arthritis specialist in Medford,
Ore., was 3 when the family was interned.
   ``We see this as a healing process which says the country
recognizes that a wrong was being done and in one small way perhaps
is trying to make amends for this,'' Emori said.
   ``In general, the Japanese-American people who went to camp
recognize that it was an awful, hysterical, grim time in American
history, and although we all feel badly that we had to go and that
we were rounded up and not only had our personal belongings but our
civil liberties taken away from us, it's kind of understandable as
to why this should happen,'' he said.
   Emori noted that his family has prospered since the war, as have
many other Japanese-Americans.
   ``We as a family would like to take this gesture the next step
further and say we'd like to give this back to the country for the
good that came out of the awful,'' he said.
   He said the family plans to use its total payments of $120,000
for such a gesture, possibly to an endowed professorship at Loma
Linda University in California, where his parents worked for years
and where all four of the children went to school. Both of Emori's
sisters have master's degrees in nursing and his brother is in
business in California. His parents live near him in Medford.
   Katherine Nunotani, 70, of San Francisco, who was sent to a camp
in Jerome, Ark., along with her elderly parents when she was 24,
agreed that the money was not important.
   ``I hope nothing like this ever happens to people in the United
States,'' she said. ``The people who deserve to get it (the money),
like my old parents, they're gone.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president always
endorsed the purpose of the bill, even though he balked at the
price tag.
   When asked whether the large number of Japanese-American voters
in California, a crucial state in the coming presidential election,
influenced Reagan's decision to sign the measure, Fitzwater said:
``No. That was not a factor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
