<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FleeingContras     08-11 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fleeing Contras,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Fighters, Civilians Flee; Many Sick, Hungry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 1,000 Contra rebels and
Nicaraguan civilians arrived at the Nicaraguan-Honduran border this
week, many suffering from hunger and disease, according to U.S.
diplomats and rebel leaders.
   State Department cables said U.S. diplomats who visited the
Honduran side of the border Monday reported that the new arrivals
were in ``appalling condition.''
   The documents were made available to The Associated Press as
Congress considers proposals for providing additional aid to the
rebels.
   The Senate, on a 49-47 vote Wednesday evening, approved a
Democratic plan to provide $27 million in humanitarian aid to the
Contras who are opposed to Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government. Senate Republicans, who had sought military as well as
humanitarian assistance, voted against the proposal as a bloc.
   According to the State Department cables, many of the newly
arriving refugees were barefoot because their boots had fallen
apart during the long trek through mountainous country in
Nicaragua, and the clothing of some was in tatters.
   Enrique Bermudez, a member of the rebel directorate, said in a
telephone interview Wednesday from Honduras that of the 1,000
Nicaraguans, 250 were rebel fighters and 750 were civilians.
   The cables said the U.S. Agency for International Development,
which is responsible for managing the humanitarian aid program,
undertook an emergency airlift program to the border area this week
to assist the new arrivals.
   Diplomats attached to the U.S. Embassy in Honduras said in the
cables that a ``human crisis of major proportions may be under
way'' along the Coco River, which separates the two countries.
   Congress approved $17.7 million in humanitarian aid to the
Contras in late March. But because of congressional restrictions
and restraints written into a cease-fire agreement signed by the
Contras and the Sandinistas last March, the bulk of that assistance
has been sent to camps on the Honduran side of the border, rather
than into Nicaragua itself. Thousands of rebels have retreated to
the border area in recent months.
   U.S. diplomats dispatched to the scene ``tell of famished people
tearing into crates of emergency foodstuff,'' one cable said.
   However, the cables gave no indication of how many of those who
arrived at the border were suffering from hunger or disease.
   Contra sources reported numerous cases of mountain leprosy,
malaria and parasitic infection among the latest arrivals. They
said at least 10 members of the group died en route.
   An additional 2,000 Nicaraguans were reported en route to the
border area and may be in ``an even more appalling condition'' than
those who arrived this week, according to one cable.
   Another cable said U.S. assistance facilities may be overwhelmed
if the additional Nicaraguans arrive soon.
   Alfredo Cesar, a member of the Contra political directorate,
said Wednesday that there are about 9,000 rebels in the border area
and about 2,500 deep inside Nicaragua.
   In the telephone interview, Bermudez declined to provide figures
but said that 65 percent of the rebels are along the border and 35
percent in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
