<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ConventionRentals Bjt   08-11 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convention Rentals, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Months' Rent For A One-Month Apartment; $3,000 For A Week In
A House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carol Wilkerson scandalized her mother by
renting her house for $2,500 during the week of the GOP national
convention.
   ``She said, `Republicans? You're renting your house to
REPUBLICANS?'
   ``My mother's a dyed-in-the-wool Democrat from New York,'' said
Mrs. Wilkerson.
   Actually, the house is being rented by a small Washington, D.C.,
communications company for two couples and two single women who
will install and maintain phone lines in the Superdome during the
convention there, Mrs. Wilkerson said.
   The company _ she couldn't recall its name _ is one of many
renting houses or apartments during the convention Aug. 15-18.
   Most apartments are being rented to the news media, leasing
specialists say.
   The CBS and NBC television networks have rented about 30
apartments for their staffs in luxury complexes converted from
warehouses within walking distance of the Superdome, said Brenda
Boettner, leasing director at Downtown Locators.
   Although the apartments are leased for a month, the networks are
paying three months' rent _ $3,240 for one bedroom and $4,590 for
two _ because the company won't accept shorter corporate rentals,
she said.
   Downtown Locators has to rent furniture, buy sheets and dishes
and otherwise make the apartment ready to live in immediately, she
noted.
   ``The biggest task is gathering individual pieces _ flower
pieces, pots and pans, Corelle dishes,'' said Carol Rockhold,
representative for corporate apartments at Tonti Management Corp.
   She said her recent 80-hour weeks often have included 12 hours a
day spent driving to various discount houses to find all of the
little things that go into furnishing a corporate apartment.
   She wouldn't say who was renting from Tonti, other than that
most were electronic support people for the news media, or what
they were paying.
   But she did say she had rented more than 200 apartments in
suburban Metairie for the convention. Most of the tenants came
after the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta ended July 22,
she said.
   Mrs. Wilkerson's tenants are coming Friday.
   She said she used their rent check to get some renovation done
before they arrived.
   ``We had the whole house repainted, replastered, and we're
getting new drapes,'' she said. ``It's great. The house is 100
years old and there's always work to do. But the economy has been
bad in New Orleans and we'd been putting the work off.''
   She said several of her friends also are renting their houses
for the week. One of them, Lydia Montgomery, said the $3,000 she's
getting also will go into the house.
   ``I've got a bedroom that I've been wanting to redo. ... And
there are curtains I've been wanting to have done. And we'll be
able to go out to eat a couple of nights,'' she said.
   Both women are giving their tenants some personal service.
   ``We're going to leave a list of restaurants, and all the
neighbors will come down and introduce themselves.... A friend of
mine makes gumbo, and I'm going to leave them dinner for the first
night. And they're going to go to the neighborhood watering hole
and put their first drink on our tab,'' said Mrs. Wilkerson.
   Mrs. Montgomery, who made $1,500 renting rooms to six couples
during the 1986 Super Bowl, said her children don't care for such
deals.
   ``I have two daughters. Nineteen and 23. They're both mortified
when I do this,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
