<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BusCrash-Congress     08-11 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Congress,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Accuses Agency of Inattention to School Bus Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee chairman whose panel is
probing a disastrous Carrollton, Ky., school bus crash is accusing
a federal safety agency of being too passive on improving the
safety of the vehicles.
   Rep. Thomas A. Luken, D-Ohio, said the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration on Wednesday is paying a ``lack of
attention'' to school bus safety.
   The House Energy and Commerce Committee's transportation
subcommittee, which Luken heads, was examining the May 14 accident
in which 27 bus occupants were killed when the vehicle was hit
head-on by a pickup truck going in the wrong direction.
   All the deaths have been attributed to smoke inhalation, caused
by a fire that engulfed the bus after the collision.
   ``NHTSA has never issued a specific standard for flammability
for school buses,'' Luken said.
   Instead, he said, the agency relies on regulations adopted in
the 1970s.
   ``Other safety agencies, such as the Federal Aviation
Administration, have issued more stringent flammability
standards,'' he said.
   NHTSA Administrator Diane K. Steed told Luken that her agency
has focused on preventing the ejection of passengers from buses in
accidents. The Kentucky crash was the first in which school bus
occupants were killed from a fire, she said.
   ``In view of the much higher risk of impact injury compared to
the risk of fire injury, the agency concluded that it was more
important to preserve the superior impact protection for the
children,'' as long as materials met basic flammability standards,
she said.
   At the same session, Steed estimated that about one-fourth of
the nation's 350,000 school buses were built before the government
issued rules in 1977 stiffening safety standards for the vehicles.
   The bus involved in the Kentucky crash was built three weeks
before the federal safety requirements took effect on April 1,
1977, and did not conform with all of the government standards. The
rules covered buses manufactured after April 1, 1977.
   The requirements covered the use of energy-absorbing materials;
stronger seats, roofs and body joints; more accessible exits; and
improvements to the impact resistance of fuel systems.
   The driver of the pickup truck that smashed into the bus, Larry
Mahoney of Worthville, Ky., has been charged with 27 counts of
murder and with drunken driving.
   James and Karolyn Nunnallee, whose 10-year-old daughter, Patty,
was killed in the crash, told the subcommittee the federal
government has to improve its efforts to control drunken driving.
   ``The federal government has the resources and the capability to
not only assist the states but to force the states to do something
about the drunk driving menace,'' Karolyn Nunnallee said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
