<DOCNO> AP880811-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EmergencySpending     08-11 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Emergency Spending,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Leaders Hope to Finish Emergency Spending Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Scheduling of votes on final bill uncertain, top prospects
uncertain</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate leaders would like to put the
finishing touches on a bill providing emergency infusions of money
to several federal programs whose coffers are running low.
   The Senate voted its approval Wednesday evening for a 1988
supplemental spending measure that would disperse $633 million in
new spending among a handful of agencies, including the Veterans
Administration and the Justice Department.
   That means that a compromise bill has to be worked out because
the House approved a $189 million version of the bill on July 27
that distributed the funds differently.
   Aides from the two chambers began meeting Wednesday, even before
the Senate passed the legislation, to begin ironing out differences
between the two bills. With Congress planning to begin a nearly
four-week summer vacation after business ends today, lawmakers were
hoping that a compromise bill could be fashioned and approved
before going home.
   Both bills were labeled ``dire emergency'' supplemental spending
measures, a legacy of last fall's budget summit agreement between
President Reagan and congressional leaders.
   In agreeing to that pact, the parties agreed that the only extra
spending that would be sought for fiscal 1988 _ which ends Sept. 30
_ would be for ``dire emergencies.'' Normally, supplemental
spending bills become laden with pet projects that lawmakers have
been unable to attach to other measures.
   Some legislators are hoping a second supplemental spending bill,
which already has cleared the House Appropriations Committee, will
be enacted later this year.
   The biggest difference between the bills passed by the House and
Senate was over spending on veterans' programs. The Senate measure
contained $530 million in new and transferred funds to help the
Veterans Administration pay for higher benefits, a growing caseload
and medical treatment, while the House bill had no such money.
   The House bill, on the other hand, had $50 million to keep some
state unemployment programs running and $24 million to help
refugees from the Soviet Union, Eastern Europe, Africa and
Southeast Asia. The Senate removed money for the refugees.
   Both bills contain $49 million for workers who have lost their
jobs because of foreign imports, $43 million for some recipients of
federal black lung benefits and $60 million for the Coast Guard to
keep its air and sea patrols operating.
   The two measures also include aid for the Justice Department to
pay for expenses of last year's uprising by Cuban detainees in
prisons in Atlanta and Oakdale, La., for the Agriculture Department
to pay for some expenses caused by the drought and for the Small
Business Administration to disburse disaster loans.
   The Senate bill could have been approved a week ago, but it was
delayed as Democrats and Republicans tried unsuccessfully to forge
an agreement on aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   The Senate passed its spending bill only after majority
Democrats, on a 57-39 vote, defeated a GOP plan to funnel military
aid to the rebels fighting Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOPCommittee     08-11 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Committee,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Tries To Set Aside Disagreements And Focus On Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans dispensed with a bitter
delegation fight and turned back a request to make the party
structure more open to minorities as they cruised toward next
week's convention with sharpened attacks on the Democrats.
   ``When I look up there and don't see a black face, I get
suspicious,'' Lugenia Gordon, a 67-year-old black Republican from
New York City, told the Republican National Committee on Wednesday.
   ``It seems to me that the Republican Party looks at us like
Limburger cheese _ a little bit of us goes a long way,'' said Ms.
Gordon, who was speaking on behalf of an appeal from a group
calling itself Freedom Republicans that urged the party to include
more minorities in the party structure.
   The RNC rejected the proposal.
   RNC Chairman Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr. sought to focus the party's
attacks on the Democrats, saying they have no right to get upset
over Republican criticism.
   Fahrenkopf cited George Bush's appearance ealier in the week
before the GOP platform committee when the vice president referred
to Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis as ``the stealth candidate''
and said the Massachusetts governor was invisible on the issues.
   ``Dukakis is already crying foul,'' Fahrenkopf said in a speech
to the RNC, which was meeting less than a week before the party's
national convention. ``But how can Dukakis call this negative
campaigning and go unchallenged?
   ``Yes, the vice president's remarks were critical. ... But the
vice president used a memorable rhetorical device to make a point
grounded in fact _ that Dukakis will not discuss the issues,'' he
said.
   Also on Wednesday, the committee settled a bitter six-month
fight in Georgia, where two groups wrestled for control of the
state's 48-member delegation to the national convention.
   In the end, a faction that included supporters of television
evangelist Pat Robertson along with dissident party members won a
majority of the state's delegation, even though all Georgia
delegates are obliged to vote for Bush.
   On the other side were party regulars, who were outraged at a
settlement imposed on them by the national committees and approved
by the national campaigns of Bush and Robertson.
   Georgia GOP Chairman John Stuckey, who was on the losing side,
left for home Wednesday, saying he would not return to claim his
seat as a convention delegate next week and would not rule out the
possibility of resigning his state party post.
   Asked if the Bush campaign had leaned on him to accept an
agreement, Stuckey replied, ``No, they fell on me.''
   Negotiators included Rich Bond, deputy manager of the Bush
campaign, and Mark Nuttle, who had been manager of the Robertson
campaign.
   ``We are striving to get our family together on this and aim our
fire at Michael Dukakis and not at each other,'' Bond said.
   However, Stuckey said he doubted the settlement would achieve
party harmony in Georgia.
   ``If the object of this exercise is to buy peace, it will have
the same effect as Mr. (Neville) Chamberlain ... to buy peace,''
said Stuckey, referring to the former British prime minister's
attempt to negotiate peace with Nazi Germany before World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
