<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Cox     08-11 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Cox,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>William Cox, Author of Western Novels Dies At Age 87</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author William Cox, who specialized in
paperback sagas dramatizing life in the Old West, died at his
typewriter while writing his 81st novel, his widow said. He was 87.
   Cox died at his home here Sunday of congestive heart failure,
said his wife, Casey.
   Cox's last entry on his unfinished novel ``Cemetery Jones and
the Tombstone Wars,'' came Sundayand read: ``He felt a surge of
hitherto unknown ambition. He could be as hard and he sure was
tougher than Old Man Clanton,'' said Mrs. Cox.
   In addition to his 80 novels, Cox wrote about 1,000 short
stories, 100 television scripts and screenplays. His efforts ranged
from newspaper sports stories to popular pulp tales for ``dime
magazines'' in the 1920s and 1930s.
   ``Writing was just one of those things that he did,'' Mrs. Cox
said. `He'd have a plot in his mind for days. Then he'd get in a
fit, go into his study, and just write.''
   Cox wrote screenplays for two films, ``Veils of Bagdad'' and
``Tanganyika'' in the mid-1950s.
   Later, he focused on writing Westerns, including ``The Six
Horsemen,'' ``Chicano Cruz,'' and the ``Cemetery Jones'' series.
   Survivors include his wife, and stepson, Douglas Campbell.
Funeral services will be private.
</TEXT>
