<DOCNO> AP880811-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0113EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp     08-11 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Envoy Says Iraqi Overflights Could Endanger Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's U.N. ambassador complained that
Iraqi warplanes have buzzed Iranian cities and warned that more
such flights could jeopardize a truce to end eight years of war.
   In Tehran on Wednesday, Iran's acting commander-in-chief Hashemi
Rafsanjani said a U.N. inquiry must condemn Iraq as the aggressor
in the Persian Gulf war or the region will face grave consequences.
   Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati met U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar on Wednesday to lodge a protest, saying
Iraqi planes had broken the sound barrier swooping down on several
Iranian cities.
   Perez de Cuellar, who has been trying to negotiate and end to
the conflict, announced Monday that both sides have agreed to an
Aug. 20 cease-fire date with direct talks to begin five days later
in Geneva.
   There have been no reports of fighting since.
   After meeting with the U.N. cheif, Mahallati told reporters that
Iraqi overflights ``can be a dangerous opening.
   ``If it (the overflights) would be continued, I am afraid that
it is an obstacle in the way of the secretary-general carrying out
his task,'' he said.
   Perez de Cuellar said of the alleged overflights:
   ``I am persuaded that if something happened, it was kind of a
mistake, a technical mistake, a misunderstanding.''
   Tehran Radio reported the Iraqi flights over southwestern Iran
on Wednesday. Iraqi media reported no air force activity, and there
was no independent confirmation of any overflights.
   A member of the Iraqi Mission to the United Nations said there
would be no comment on Mahallati's remarks until today. He declined
to give his name.
   In Tehran, Rafsanjani, also the speaker of parliament, said Iran
wants ``justice and punishment of the aggressor who has violated
all principles'' of international law.
   He spoke at an international conference organized by Iran to
discuss ``aggression and defense.''
   The year-old U.N. cease-fire resolution that Iran finally
accepted last month calls on the secretary-general to set up an
impartial body to judge who started the war.
   ``We have accepted the resolution with the hope that on the
committee determining the responsibility of the aggressor, they
(the United Nations) are serious,'' Rafsanjani said. ``We hope
events do not take place that make us think they have told us lies.
   ``If we have such a feeling, this might have grave consequences
for the region.'' He did not elaborate.
   Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after border skirmishes.
   Cyrus Nasseri, head of the Iranian U.N. mission in Geneva, said
Iran wants compensation for aggression in the war but gave no
details. Official Iranian estimates put war damage at $350 billion.
   Also on Wednesday, small groups of U.N. officials arrived in
Tehran and Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, to prepare for hundreds of
military observers who will monitor the cease-fire.
   All 350 observers from 25 countries are expected to be in place
within a week, the officials said.
   The U.N. Security Council met Wednesday in informal
consultations to approve the secretary-general's list of nations
sending cease-fire monitors.
   The nations are: Argentina, Australia, Austria, Bangladesh,
Canada, Denmark, Finland, Ghana, Hungary, Indonesia, India,
Ireland, Italy, Kenya, Malaysia, New Zealand, Nigeria, Norway,
Poland, Senegal, Sweden, Turkey, Yugoslavia, and Zambia.
   Earlier in the day, the United States called on Arab nations and
Japan to donate money to the peacekeeping group.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said: ``We
do intend to urge the (Persian) gulf states, who are the chief
beneficiaries of this settlement, to share in the cost through
voluntary contributions.
   ``We'll be giving the same message to other countries like Japan
and others who have an interest in the gulf,'' he said. Japan
imports nearly all its oil from the gulf region.
   Meanwhile, U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said of the body's
financial problems, ``if we continue at this rate,'' the United
Nations will be bankrupt before October.
   The General Assembly will reconvene in a special session Tuesday
to assess its 159 members for the $74 million that the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group will cost in its first six months.
   The United States expects to be assessed about $23 million of
that amount, said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley in
Washington.
   The United States is the most delinquent contributor to the
U.N.'s regular budget, accounting for $467 million of the $602
million in unpaid assessments.
</TEXT>
