<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LincolnLawFirm     08-11 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lincoln Law Firm,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Furnishings from Chicago's Oldest Law Firm Go on Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chairs that once belonged to the son of Abraham
Lincoln went on sale with other furniture, lawbooks and art in the
liquidation of the city's oldest law firm, founded by Robert Todd
Lincoln and others 116 years ago.
   When the partners of Isham, Lincoln & Beale decided in April to
dissolve the firm as part of a merger, it meant eight floors of
offices would have to be divested of furniture, equipment, lawbooks
and art _ much of it with historic connections.
   Five chairs once owned by founding partner Robert Todd Lincoln,
the son of the 16th president, have been priced at $2,000 to $2,500
apiece, said Bud Schwartz of F.E. Schwartz and Associates, which is
conducting the sale as the law firm's executor.
   Schwartz said the sale, which began Wednesday, was going
``unbelievably well. We've got 12 sales people on the floor, and we
couldn't keep up with it.''
   There's also an ornate desk, reportedly from a Scottish castle,
that once seated Robert Lincoln's partner, Edward Isham, and the
carpet that covered the office floor of a more recent partner, the
late former Gov. Richard Ogilvie.
   ``They're selling everything from the computers and law books to
whole offices,'' said spokeswoman Arlene Shattil. ``The sale will
continue until everything that can be sold is sold, which should be
at least two or three weeks.''
   The sale is by appointment only, and people with appointments
are expected to come early to view a videotape of the items being
sold. Schwartz said the tape was prepared to save the potential
customers a tour of the offices.
   Schwartz declined to discuss reasons for the dissolution except
to say the firm was going through a merger.
</TEXT>
