<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-11 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Employee Union Cites Spending Cuts During Reagan Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic government programs have been cut by
a total of $158.6 billion in terms of services delivered since
President Reagan assumed office, according to a report released
today by a union of government workers.
   Federal aid to state and local governments over the past seven
years is 16.5 percent, or $123.6 billion, below what it would have
been had programs in place in 1981 been maintained at then-current
service levels, said the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees.
   Cumulative government payments to individuals such as college
aid, Social Security and food stamps over the seven years are $35
billion less, or 2.3 percent below, what they would have totaled
had the programs been maintained at 1981 levels, the study
commissioned by AFSCME said.
   The report _ titled ``The Republican Record: A 7-Year Analysis
of State Losses of Federal Funding'' _ said the biggest cut was in
state aid to provide free or reduced-price milk to schoolchildren.
   Federal spending on the milk program has totaled $131 million
over the past seven years, or 86.2 percent below the $950 million
that would have been spent had the program been maintained at is
1981 funding level, the report said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Last Admiral to Fight in World War II Is Retiring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Navy admiral still on active duty to
see combat in World War II is retiring Aug. 31 after more than 55
years of military service.
   President Reagan will honor Rear Adm. John Duncan Bulkeley by
nominating him for promotion to the three-star rank of vice
admiral, the Pentagon said Wednesday. Senate confirmation of that
promotion was virtually assured.
   Bulkeley, a Medal of Honor winner, is known within the Navy as
the officer who safely evacuated Gen. Douglas MacArthur to
Australia in March 1942 after the Japanese invaded the Philippines.
   He received the nation's highest military award for his
squadron's success in damaging or destroying Japanese planes,
warships and merchant ships while he commanded various motor
torpedo boat squadrons in the Pacific theater.
   Bulkeley has spent the last 21 years as head of the Naval Board
of Inspection and Survey, which is responsible for inspecting all
ships and shore facilities for their equipment's readiness.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Call for Dissolution of Panama Canal Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional conservatives are asking fellow
lawmakers to void the treaty that shifts ownership of the Panama
Canal from the United States to the Panamanian government.
   Under the agreement ratified by the Senate in 1979, the United
States would abandon all rights to the Canal Zone and it would
become a part of Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   But a resolution introduced Wednesday contends the treaty is
invalid because the Constitution requires both the House and Senate
to approve the transfer of U.S. property.
   ``We did not participate on the House side,'' said Rep. Philip
Crane, R-Ill. ``It was a flawed treaty in terms of our
constitutional obligations.''
   Republican Sen. Steve Symms of Idaho said Congress also never
ratified changes imposed by Panama and was not signed by that
nation's president.
   Crane said the 39 initial co-sponsors include three Democrats.
``It's really not a partisan question,'' he said. ``It's an
American question, an issue of American interests and security.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Bill To Fight Radon Pollution in Schools,</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Homes
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel has sent to the full
House a $46 million package calling for federal and state action to
combat cancer-causing radon pollution in houses and schools.
   The legislation, which cleared the Energy and Commerce Committee
by a voice vote Wednesday, would set a national goal of making the
air inside buildings as free of radon gas concentrations as the air
outside buildings.
   It would require the Environmental Protection Agency to update
and revise its ``Citizen's Guide to Radon'' to include information
about health risks posed by various indoor levels of the naturally
occurring gas.
   Health experts have warned that the EPA's current listing for
acceptable levels of radon gas is too high, allowing for the
equivalent of smoking half a pack of cigarettes a day. Radon is an
colorless, odorless radioactive gas produced by the decay of
uranium deposits.
</TEXT>
