<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TelevisionAddict     08-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Television Addict,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tree-Cutting `TV Addict' Seeks Rehabilition Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described TV addict charged with
chopping down a neighbor's 83-year-old oak tree to improve his
satellite reception hopes to get the charges erased, but his
neighbor isn't happy about the prospect.
   Arthur Anderson, 59, of Redding, told Danbury Superior Court
Judge Howard Moraghan on Wednesday that he didn't have a criminal
record and wanted to apply for the accelerated rehabilitation
program.
   Under the program, first-time offenders can have charges erased
from their records after they successfully complete probationary
periods.
   ``This isn't the crime of the century,'' Anderson's lawyer,
Jeffrey B. Sienkiewicz, told reporters. Anderson is charged with
second-degree criminal mischief and third-degree criminal trespass.
   The tree owner, Charles Marriner, 62, will be able to address
the judge he rules on Anderson's request.
   Marriner, who is suing Anderson for $37,000 in damages, said he
plans to ``give very serious thought to opposing accelerated
rehabilitation based on the fact that it was the second time he did
it.''
   Marriner said he has received letters from people as far away as
Seattle urging him to pursue prosecution of Anderson.
   ``The common thread of these letters is people are feeling very
threatened and very upset about the aberration of a person's
rights,'' Marriner said.
   In court, Moraghan asked Anderson what he had done.
   ``I cut a tree down,'' Anderson said, his voice barely audible.
   The construction worker told police in June after he cut down
the tree, ``Now I can get the Disney Channel.'' He also said he and
his wife are ``TV addicts.''
   The judge ordered a Sept. 7 court date for Anderson, who could
receive a maximum sentence of one year in prison for second-degree
criminal mischief and six months for third-degree criminal
trespassing if he is tried and convicted.
   State's Attorney Devin Stilson said he believes accelerated
rehabilitation is appropriate for Anderson because the program is
intended for crimes that are not of a serious nature.
</TEXT>
