<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ProstitutionEssays     08-11 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prostitution Essays,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Gives Prostitute A Choice: Essays Or Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For every 200 words Olivia D'Amato
writes about the world's oldest profession, a judge will suspend
one day of her maximum 30-day sentence on a prostitution conviction.
   Ms. D'Amato ``was quite taken aback'' when Municipal Judge
Samuel Serata issued the sentence Tuesday, said her attorney,
Howard Kupperman.
   ``It's unusual, innovative and different. To you and I and other
literate people, it seems easy, but for her it's quite a burden,''
Kupperman said Wednesday.
   ``She could conceivably get the whole sentence suspended, but it
will be quite a challenge.''
   Ms. D'Amato has definite opinions on her profession, he said.
Before she was convicted, she told the judge that prostitution is
the world's oldest profession and that jail sentences would not
stop it, Kupperman said. She told the judge that legalizing
prostitution would probably be the best solution, he said.
   When she left the courtroom, Ms. D'Amato told Kupperman her
first priority would be to get the conviction overturned. She was
charged with soliciting an undercover police officer. Kupperman's
defense centered on the fact that Ms. D'Amato knew the officer and
would never have solicited him.
   Like Ms. D'Amato, Kupperman and City Attorney Mark Grice, who
prosecuted the case, expressed surprise at the sentence.
   ``I think it's fair,'' Grice said. ``By writing an essay, maybe
she would realize the problems in prostitution. He wants to hear
her standpoint on ways the courts can address prostitution.
   ``He was especially concerned about young girls _ girls younger
than 18 _ on the streets here in Atlantic City,'' the prosecutor
said.
   Ms. D'Amato has been arrested for prostitution elsewhere, Grice
said, including New York, California and Washington. She has been
arrested at least three times in Atlantic City, he said.
   She could not be reached for comment Wednesday.
</TEXT>
