<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     08-11 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker Says He Plans To Outbid Canadian Company For PTL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former PTL leader Jim Bakker says he
plans to recapture his television ministry by outbidding a Canadian
company for PTL's assets when the bankruptcy sale closes next month.
   The Canadian company, Samoth Capital Corp., has offered $113
million _ $46 million in cash immediately and the rest over five
years.
   Bakker said the Canadian offer's real value is $77 million after
discounting such things as interest that could be earned if the
money were paid to PTL immediately. He said he plans to outbid that
amount.
   PTL agreed last week to give Samoth Capital's president, Peter
Thomas of Vancouver, until Sept. 16 to decide whether he wants to
go through with the deal. Until then, PTL is free to consider other
offers.
   Thomas was scheduled to begin inspecting the property today,
said PTL trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton.
   Also today, U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Rufus Reynolds was
expected to hear arguments in a dispute between The Charlotte
Observer and Bakker's attorneys.
   Bakker's attorneys are protesting the sale of Bakker's
deposition transcripts to the newspaper by a court reporter, saying
their premature release is unfair to Bakker.
   Bakker was preparing his defense in PTL's $52 million lawsuit
that charges him with grossly mismanaging the ministry and the
Heritage USA theme park at Fort Mill, S.C., he founded but left
last year after acknowledging a sexual encounter with Jessica Hahn.
   Using the transcripts as its source, the Observer published an
article last week that quoted Bakker as saying he believed
thousands of internal PTL documents had been destroyed since he
resigned as president in March 1987. Ministry officials denied that.
   Reynolds appeared to agree to with Bakker and last week issued
an order protecting the release of further transcripts. The
Observer said it plans to protest the order.
   PTL has been in bankruptcy proceedings since June 1987, three
months after Bakker resigned. Bakker has said he wants to buy PTL's
assets, including the Heritage USA Christian retreat and the PTL
satellite TV network, and return as its leader.
   Bakker's attorney, Jim Toms, wouldn't provide details about
Bakker's bid, but promised that ``what money is paid will be paid
at closing, and it will be a number that will be in excess of what
we believe the present value of the Canadian deal to be.''
   They weren't specific about when the offer would be made, saying
they are still making arrangements with unidentified overseas
lenders.
   Asked why anyone would lend Bakker so much money when a federal
grand jury is investigating him for possible criminal wrongdoing,
Bakker replied: ``That's not really a problem with these people.
I'm not expecting to be indicted, anyway.''
   Benton said Wednesday that before PTL will deal with Bakker, he
must deposit a substantial amount of cash or securities to
guarantee that he has the ability to buy the assets.
   The Canadian group has deposited $50,000 and has pledged $4.95
million more as soon as it decides whether to go through with the
purchase. Bakker's offer doesn't provide for any advance deposit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
