<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoyWilliamsParole     08-11 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roy Williams Parole,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Teamsters Chief Wins Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Teamsters President Roy L.
Williams has won a parole from his 10-year prison term as a reward
for testifying for the government in mob trials and because of his
failing health, officials said.
   Williams, who has served three years for his 1982 attempted
bribery conviction, will be paroled Jan. 13, David Dorworth, chief
analyst with the U.S. Parole Commission in Washington, D.C., said
Wednesday.
   Dorworth said Williams' release would not depend upon his
continued testimony for the government in organized-crime trials
but ``is a reward for his cooperation thus far and in consideration
of his poor health.''
   F. Russell Millin, a Kansas City lawyer representing the former
labor leader, said he told Williams about the decision Wednesday
and Williams ``heaved the biggest sigh of relief you can imagine.''
   Williams, 73, who suffers from emphysema and an enlarged heart,
is confined at the U.S. Medical Center for Federal Prisoners in
Springfield.
   Williams served as international Teamsters president from 1981
until he was forced to resign after his conviction for trying to
bribe former U.S. Sen. Howard Cannon of Nevada to influence
trucking deregulation. Cannon was not charged in the case.
   In an attempt to have his sentence reduced, Williams, a
long-time Kansas City labor leader, started cooperating with
federal authorities investigating the mob.
   He testified during one mob trial that he had been under the
control of Nick Civella, the reputed crime boss in Kansas City at
the time, and received payoffs of $1,500 a month from Civella for
seven years until he became president of the Teamsters. He said
Civella, who has died, played a key role in his election to the
union presidency.
   Williams also testified by videotape in the federal court trial
in New York against mob figures accused of fixing his election as
Teamsters president, and that of his successor, the late Jackie
Presser.
   Mob boss Anthony ``Fat Boy'' Salerno and two co-defendants were
acquitted in May of the election-fixing charges, but Salerno and
several co-defendants were convicted of charges that they conspired
to rig bids in the construction industry.
   Wiliams' attorneys have been working for the past year to gain
his release. They contended the risk Williams incurred by
testifying should be sufficient to win parole.
   Millin said he assumed Williams would return to his farm near
Leeton upon his release.
</TEXT>
