<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--EarthquakeWarnings     08-11 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Earthquake Warnings,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Geologic Signals May Precede Earthquakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-hour cycles of contraction and expansion
in the Earth's crust were detected for months before a major
earthquake struck the Japan Sea, scientists reported today.
   Such episodes should be studied for their potential in warning
of quakes, said researcher Alan Linde.
   Linde, with coworkers at the Carnegie Institution of Washington
and researchers in Japan, presents an analysis in the British
journal Nature.
   The three-hour episodes may reflect a buildup of stress that is
released during the quake, Linde said.
   About 100 episodes were recorded in the five months before the
1983 quake, but none have appeared since the aftershocks ended,
Linde said. They may have begun earlier, but the instrument that
recorded them was not in place before that, Linde said.
   The instrument was about 50 miles southeast of the quake's
epicenter, which was off the west coast of Japan. The quake
registered 7.7 on the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
