<HEAD>Doctors At Government Hospitals Stage One-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7,000 doctors at Israel's government-run
hospitals staged a one-day strike today to protest a stalemate in
talks on pay and a plan to deal with a backlog of operations.
   Israel radio said the doctors were not satisfied with the
government's decision to give hospitals nine months to deal with
what it says are 15,000 people awaiting operations.
   The doctors want the program to last longer because they
estimate 45,000 people are on the waiting list.
   The doctors, whose average monthly salary is about $750, also
demand wage increases of up to 20 percent, according to the Finance
Ministry.
   Finance Minister Moshe Nissim condemned the strikers and said
the government had ``reached the limit'' on what it could give.
   ``I think there is a also limit to the doctors' torturing of the
patients,'' he said on Israel radio.
