<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Arias     08-11 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Arias,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three-Time Panamanian President Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arnulfo Arias Madrid, who was ousted three times as
president of Panama, was remembered upon his death at age 86 as a
symbol of democracy in a country dominated by the military.
   Arias died of a heart attack here Wednesday, five days short of
his 87th birthday. He had lived here in self-imposed exile.
   The Panamanian government decreed Monday a day of mourning for
Arias, the patriarch of Panamanian politics.
   The Panamanian flag will be flown at half staff for eight days
starting Monday, Arias' birthday and the day he is to be buried in
Panama City.
   Arias, whose presidential terms were ended by military coups,
arrived here in December. He feared to return to Panama because of
his opposition to Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the nation's de
facto leader.
   ``If he had gone back, the military would have killed him,''
said Roberto Dominguez, Panamanian consul to the United States and
who opposes Noriega.
   Although Arias reportedly suffered from heart trouble, he had
been in good health recently. Arias' wife, Mireya, was with him
when he died at his home, Dominguez said.
   Relatives said Arias' body will be flown to Panama City on
Friday.
   Arias was called by opposition leaders ``a great rebel'' and
``the indisputable leader'' of Panama for the past 57 years. He was
president in 1940-41, 1949-51 and for 11 days in 1968.
   The last coup led to the long domination of the Panamanian
government by the military, first under Gen. Omar Torrijos, who
died in a 1981 plane crash, then under Noriega.
   Arias, head of the Authentic Panamanian Party, narrowly lost the
1984 election to the official party's candidate. His supporters and
others accused the government of fraud. Many also felt the military
stole a 1964 electoral victory from him.
   He continued to speak out against the military, and in 1986 said
it killed opposition leader Dr. Hugo Spadafora, who had accused
Noriega's government of involvement with drugs.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida this year for alleged drug
trafficking.
   Opposition leaders in Panama expressed sorrow over Arias' death.
   Ricardo Arias Calderon, president of the Christian Democratic
Party, said the former president represented ``the figure of a
great rebel'' who had a social conscience and was ``concerned about
those who have less and for those who suffer more.''
   Guillermo Endara, undersecretary of the Authentic Party, said
Arias was ``the indisputable leader'' of Panama for the past 57
years.
   Carlos Ivan Zuniga, president of the Popular Action Party, said,
``There is no doubt that his death is going to constitute a
tremendous uncertainty, leave a vacuum.''
   Born when Panama was still part of Colombia, Arias was educated
in the United States and became active in his new nation's politics
in 1931, when he helped engineer a coup against the president.
   He later served as ambassador to France and England, and in
Europe became enamored of Mussolini's fascism. He returned to
advocate it in Panama, and was elected president in 1940.
   The United States, worried about his connections to the Axis
powers on the eve of World War II, encouraged a military coup
against him. But he returned to power with more moderate views in
1948, and is credited with founding his nation's highly regarded
social security system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0049 </DOCNO>
