<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Beating     08-11 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Beating,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Museum Guards Sentenced for Beating College Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two museum security guards have been sentenced to
prison for illegally detaining and seriously beating a college
student with a cattle prod, an official newspaper reported today.
   The People's Daily said the Guiyang City Intermediate Court in
southern China's Guizhou province sentenced guard Chen Wei to 2
years in prison and guard Shun Li to 1{ years for the attack.
   The report said the incident occurred on June 18 when a
temporary worker at the provincial museum tried to stop Zou Zuen, a
student from Guizhou People's University, from entering a room at
the museum, saying he smelled of alcohol.
   When Zou protested, the two security guards dragged him to their
office, handcuffed him to an iron bed and beat him with a cattle
prod, the paper said.
   They also forced Zou to kneel and confess that he was ``making
trouble and beating others after drinking.''
   The report said Zou suffered serious mental and physical
injuries in the attack.
   The Chinese government acknowledges that its attempts to
establish a working body of law and guarantee the rights of
citizens are still marred by abuse of power by public officials,
and the state-run press occasionally carries reports of police and
other officials beating and torturing suspects in criminal cases.
</TEXT>
