<DOCNO> AP880811-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MagicFestival     08-11 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Magic Festival,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magicians Worldwide Materialize In Small Town For Magic Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resident have staged their annual
disappearing act as magicians from around the world materialized
for the magic festival that put this tiny village on the map.
   ``Most of the local folks plan their vacations for this week and
take off,'' said Greg Bordner, president of Abbott's Magic
Manufacturing Co., which sponsors the 51-year-old festival and
bills itself as the largest manufacturer of magic tricks in the
world.
   ``There's no question we get a lot of strange people here _
throwing fire around and sticking cards to the ceilings,'' Bordner
said Wednesday, the first day of the four-day festival.
   About 1,000 amateur and professional magicians, ranging from
illusionists and ventriloquists to the guy who pulls rabbits out of
a hat at birthday parties, flock each year to this rural community
near the Indiana border.
   About 3,000 others _ three times the town's population _ come
for the magic shows, which include a special appearance each year
by magician Harry Blackstone Jr. Blackstone's famous father, Harry
Blackstone Sr., spent summers here and introduced Australian
magician Percy Abbott to the area. In 1934, Abbott founded the
magic company, now a successful mail-order operation, with
Bordner's father, Recil Bordner.
   The local restaurant, Blackstone Inn, is located on the town's
main street, Blackstone Avenue.
   The magicians began arriving early in the week, some setting up
booths in the ``demonstration room'' _ the elementary school's
gymnasium _ to show their newest tricks and sell their trick cards,
scarves and handcuffs.
   Bordner recalls how magicians David Copperfield and Doug Henning
attended the festival years ago, ``when they were just two more
kids in the crowd.''
   Franz Harary, 26, who designs illusions for magician David
Copperfield and such entertainers as Michael Jackson and Alice
Cooper, moved four years ago from his hometown of Ann Arbor to
Hollywood, but he wouldn't think of missing the Colon festival.
   ``This place is like a mecca. The biggest guys from all over are
here,'' said Harary, who attended his first festival 13 years ago
after discovering a magic trick in a box of cereal. ``Abbott's is
like a part of me.''
   While Harary swaps secrets with established performers from
Japan, England and Czechoslovakia, Jim Caputo just wants to learn a
new card trick or a slicker way to pull a rabbit out of a hat.
Caputo, a research chemist at Upjohn Co. in Kalamazoo, does magic
shows at children's birthday parties on weekends.
   ``People think scientists aren't much fun, but you'd be
surprised,'' Caputo said. ``Next to kids, scientists are my best
audiences. I guess they have such rigid views, they're easy to
fool.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KidnapTrial     08-11 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kidnap Trial,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Convicted Of Kidnapping Elderly Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted a young couple of kidnapping
an elderly Louisiana woman, drugging her and stealing her life
savings of $100,000.
   After less than two hours of deliberations, the jury Wednesday
found Terry Barrett, 29, and Virginia Barrett, 30, guilty of
kidnapping, conspiracy, mail fraud and interstate transportation of
fraudulently taken securities.
   The couple could receive a maximum penalty of life sentences
plus 55 years and $2 million in fines from U.S. District Judge
Harold Murphy, who set sentencing for Sept. 23.
   Lucille Knight, 84, testified that the Barretts came to her
mobile home in Hammond, La., on Feb. 2, 1986, apparently drugged
her and then drove her to Ringgold, where she was held captive for
four months.
   Three young women who stayed with the Barretts testified that
the couple instructed them to give Mrs. Knight a variety of drugs.
She was finally rescued by a former sheriff's detective after she
managed to smuggle out a letter to a sister in Louisiana.
   Mrs. Knight, who worked in a state hospital in California for
more than 30 years, testified she did not know her savings were
gone until after she returned to Hammond. She has sued a bank in
Hammond for allowing her money to be withdrawn without her approval.
   The Barretts were accused of getting Mrs. Knight's money with
forged signatures on personal checks, cashier's checks,
certificates of deposit, and Social Security and retirement checks.
They admitted Monday to forging checks on Mrs. Knight's account but
denied the kidnapping charges.
   According to testimony, the Barretts placed Mrs. Knight's money
in their own bank account in Chattanooga, Tenn., where they
operated a bakery, and depleted the funds within four months.
   ``The taking of an elderly woman by drugging her for four
months, holding her against her will and taking all of her life
savings is fundamentally evil,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas D.
Bever said after the verdict. ``We're very pleased with the
verdict.''
   Defense Attorney John E. Sawhill III had no immediate comment on
the verdict.
</TEXT>
