<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeSillers     08-11 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeSillers Reported Burglary After She Was Asked To Return
Belongings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers reported her apartment burglarized
four days after she was asked to turn over thousands of dollars
worth of valuables allegedly bought with donations for her dying
son's liver transplants.
   The day after the burglary report was filed, a judge acted on
the request for the valuables made by the curator of the estate of
Ms. DeSillers' son, Ronnie, and ordered her to turn them over or
face contempt charges.
   Ms. DeSillers told Metro-Dade police the break-in occurred
sometime between July 30 and Aug. 2. Missing are a $1,500 stereo,
jewelry, leather goods, clothing and a $50 bottle of Passion
perfume, she told police.
   Police said that there were no signs of forced entry at Ms.
DeSillers' fifth-floor Miami apartment.
   ``It could only mean two things,'' Detective Barry Garafola
said. ``A lock pick, or someone had a key.''
   The burglary report Sunday came four days after court-appointed
curator Karen Gievers demanded that Ms. DeSillers turn over such
items as her BMW car, jewelry and clothing that she allegedly
purchased with funds donated to Ronnie.
   The 7-year-old boy died in April 1987 after three liver
transplants.
   On Monday, Dade Circuit Judge Francis J. Christie followed Ms.
Gievers' request and ordered Ms. DeSillers to turn over the
belongings by Tuesday. When she failed to comply, in part because
she dismissed an attorney who had advised her to give up the items,
the judge held a hearing Wednesday and extended the deadline to 4
p.m. today.
   Ms. DeSillers, who took in $690,000 in contributions, including
$1,000 from President Reagan, has been accused of spending $200,000
on personal expense, including $11,000 in jewelry and $13,500 on
the BMW.
   Ms. DeSillers' new lawyer ridiculed the court-imposed deadline
for his client to turn over the valuables, including some clothing.
   ``I guess they just want to make sure Maria walks around nude.
Do they want her pantyhose? What's the value of a blouse purchased
a year ago? Nobody wants to buy her used clothes,'' lawyer Frank
Johnson said after Wednesday's hearing.
   Ms. Gievers also contends that since Ronnie died, his mother
gave a total of $40,000 to her brother, ex-husband and
ex-boyfriend. She also is accused of paying herself $88,000 to head
her now-defunct Ronnie DeSillers National Foundation.
   Ms. DeSillers has maintained she is heir to the $243,000
remaining in the estate of Ronnie, who died awaiting a fourth
transplant at Pittsburgh Children's Hospital.
   Ms. DeSillers has refused to pay a $262,000 bill from the
hospital, which she blames for her son's death, a charge doctors
there vehemently deny.
</TEXT>
