<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalStrike     08-11 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Strike,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Nurses Avert Joining Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's 1,600 public nurses narrowly
avoided joining a two-week-old strike by nearly 4,000 private
nurses and support workers when they approved a new one-year
contract by a narrow margin.
   Nurses at San Francisco General Hospital and other public health
facilities voted 320-307 Wednesday for the new pact, said Donna
Gerber, field representative for Local 790 of the United Public
Employees union.
   ``This is not a mandate for the management of the city,'' said
Gerber. ``The management of this city must get the message that the
nurses are fed up.''
   The union mainly sought a staffing ratio of four patients to one
nurse. Nurses say they sometimes care for seven to 10 patients at a
time. However, a tentative pact reached Sunday calls for an
unspecific ``modified ratio,'' which Gerber said might be a
sticking point for many of the voting nurses.
   ``There's no question that some of our members see this as too
little, too late,'' she said.
   About 2,200 private nurses and 1,700 support workers went on
strike Aug. 2 against eight private hospitals in a wage dispute.
They have since resumed talks with hospital administrators.
   The California Nurses Association wants raises of 11 percent the
first year of a new contract and 10 percent the second year. Karen
Henry, a spokeswoman for Affiliated Hospitals, a group of private
area hospitals, said the group has offered raises of 18 percent
over 31 months.
   Members of Local 250 of the Hospital Health Care Workers Union,
representing the support workers, are striking over health benefits
and sick leave.
</TEXT>
