<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WildfiresRdp     08-11 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wildfires Rdp,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Fire Contained; Fires Burn In Four Other States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon firefighters contained a wildfire that charred 13,000
acres of the Deschutes National Forest while their counterparts
fought to gain the upper hand in blazes in Idaho, Nevada, Wyoming
and Montana.
   Fire lines around the Paulina, Ore., fire were completed
Wednesday evening, said Forest Service spokeswoman Laura Allen. She
said the blaze was expected to be controlled by 1,400 firefighters
and support personnel by Friday night.
   The fire, about 25 miles southeast of Bend, threatened two small
resorts before the winds shifted. Plans for evacuating the resorts
were canceled Tuesday night.
   The fire, which began Aug. 4, was human-caused, but the means
has not been determined.
   In Wyoming, a blaze that has charred 30,000 acres of Yellowstone
National park threatened a park campground.
   Spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo said winds of 15-25 mph fanned the fire
Wednesday afternoon, but firefighters hoped to hold it about three
miles from the camp site.
   Like the rest of the fires burning on about 191,000 acres of
Yellowstone, the blaze has been stable for several days.Anzelmo
said a string of cool days has given fire managers hope that they
may be close to containing the blazes.
   In central Idaho, increased air traffic by firefighters and
smoke at a month-old, 13,000-acre wilderness fire north of Stanley
prompted the closure of a Forest Service guard station and a nearby
private airstrip Wednesday, arousing the ire of some Idaho boating
outfitters.
   The air strip closure forced outfitters and private rafters to
fly into an airstrip 10 miles downstream to put in on the Middle
Fork of the Salmon River.
   ``There's going to be a smoke problem in there plus our own air
traffic,'' said Challis National Forest spokesman Jim James. ``Our
priority No. 1 is public safety on the river.''
   Meanwhile, in the Targhee National Forest in eastern Idaho, hot
spots flared in the 1,500-acre Spring Canyon II blaze.
   Scattered thunderstorms were expected to reach Idaho this
afternoon and fire officials are concerned lightning could create
another round of wildfires, said Forest Service fire information
officer Gary Cornell.
   Four fires caused by lightning June 25 have burned together in
central Idaho's Payette National Forest, said forest spokesman Dave
Olson. The perimeter of the fire encompasses about 12,000 acres of
burning and untouched forest.
   To the north in the Nez Perce National Forest, some 200
firefighters contained a 1,000-acre blaze on the Main Salmon River
Wednesday night, said Mary Zabinski, a fire information officer.
   Near Carson City, Nev., a fast-moving brush fire was reported 50
percent contained today after roaring through at least 1,800 acres.
   The fire, which was sparked by lightning Wednesday, burned into
the back yards of several homes before moving into Sierra Nevada
foothills to the west, sending up a huge, mushroom-shaped cloud of
flame and smoke visible 20 miles away.
   Residents who were evacuated soon after the blaze began later
were able to return to their homes, and no structures were damaged.
   South of Helena, Mont., nearly 800 firefighters planned today to
assault a human-caused wildfire burning unhindered on over 700
acres in the Elkhorn Mountains. Gusty winds and temperatures in the
mid-90s fueled the flames Wednesday, said fire information officer
Dave Turner.
   Meanwhile, 60 miles to the northwest, a 33,000-acre fire caused
by lightning was being allowed to burn unchecked in the Scapegoat
Wilderness. and Clark National Forest officials closed the
wilderness south of Welcome Pass to the public because of the
continuing fire danger.
</TEXT>
