<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0704EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BoatPeople     08-11 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat People,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ninety Vietnamese Boat People Want To Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Vietnamese boat people asking to
be sent back home shot up during the past week after talks between
Hong Kong and Vietnam over large-scale repatriation, a government
spokeswoman said today.
   At least 90 Vietnamese who fled to this British colony by boat
have volunteered to return home, including about 70 who made the
request after last week's talks, according to the spokeswoman, who
demanded anonymity.
   Only 21 boat people have been voluntarily repatriated from Hong
Kong since 1978, including two in July.
   Hong Kong and Vietnam officials met in Hanoi to discuss
repatriating boat people viewed by the British colony not as
political refugees but as illegal immigrants fleeing a battered
economy.
   No agreement was reached but further talks are expected.
   Vietnam has said it would repatriate boat people who want to
return home, while Hong Kong is seeking to send back most
Vietnamese who arrived after mid-June.
   After the Vietnam War ended in 1975, Hong Kong considered all
Vietnamese arriving by boat to be political refugees eligible for
resettlement in third countries.
   But under a new policy which took effect June 16 to curb the
surging number of arrivals, all incoming Vietnamese are considered
illegal immigrants subject to repatriation unless they can prove
they fled communist Vietnam because of persecution.
   The spokeswoman said some of the 90 volunteers were classified
as illegal immigrants while others were classified as refugees
entitled to be resettled overseas. She said she had no further
details.
   The repatriation applications will be forwarded to the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees to discuss with Hanoi.
   About 7,000 Vietnamese have sailed into Hong Kong since the new
policy took effect, bringing the number of boat people in the
colony to about 23,000.
   United Nations officials could not be reached for immediate
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0716EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DinosaurGrave     08-11 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dinosaur Grave,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Mass Grave of Baby Dinosaurs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from China and Canada said today that
they unearthed a mass grave of sheep-sized baby dinosaurs who were
apparently buried during a sandstorm 75 million years ago.
   Dr. Philip Currie, of the Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology in
Alberta, said the joint team excavated the skulls of five baby
Pinacosaurus in the wastelands of southern Inner Mongolia.
   He said they found a sixth baby on the last day of their summer
expedition, ``and it appears likely there are a number of other
specimens.''
   One adult, which in life was ``about the size of an extremely
heavy bull,'' was also discovered nearby, he said.
   ``We feel that the five babies were congregating together behind
a sand dune in a sandstorm,'' Currie said. Either they were buried
by sand or killed by the collapsing dune, he said.
   Currie said it was first time the plant-eating reptile had been
found to be ``gregarious,'' or living and moving in groups.
   The Canada-China Dinosaur Project, working together for the
second straight summer in the fertile and largely untouched
dinosaur fields of Inner Mongolia and Xinjiang in China's far west,
found the remains of about 50 other dinosaurs and their nests, and
40 other mammals, turtles and lizards.
   The Bayan Manduhau area of southern Inner Mongolia where the
babies were dug up was first explored by American and Swedish
paleontologists in 1928 and 1931. This year's find was in a spot
that was inaccessible at that time because of lack of roads.
   Hou Lianhai of the Chinese Academy of Science's Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology, said the team in
Xinjiang had excavated a meat-eating theropod but needed another
year to dig up a brontosaurus-like sauropod.
   Both beasts were discovered in Xinjiang during the first
expedition last year. The sauropod, about 160 million years old and
estimated to have been 100 feet long, is one of the largest of its
kind to have been found in Asia, Hou said.
   At a news conference, Currie and Hou also revealed one nearly
intact oblong-shaped egg, about eight inches long, and several
broken egg shells of the Protoceratops, a pig-sized horned dinosaur.
   Currie said the year's finds will help understand the histories
of dinosaurs in Asia and North America. He said the fossils
discovered in Inner Mongolia were the same age as those found in
Alberta, another great repository of dinosaurs, and that many of
the same kinds of reptiles were turning up.
   He said it was still not clear whether the dinosaurs migrated
from either the dry, dune-coursed Asian deserts or the wetter lands
of North America, or whether they may have developed independently.
   The dinosaur project is to return to China again next year and
in the future may carry out further research in either China or
northern Canada. Noble said there are also plans to stage a world
tour of dinosaur fossils from around 1991.
   The project is coordinated by the Ex-Terra Foundation and
supported by the Canadian government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
