<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneFire     08-11 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Fire,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Aborts Takeoff; At Least Nine Passengers Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engine fire forced a United Airlines
737 with 107 people aboard to abort its takeoff, and at least nine
passengers were injured evacuating the burning twin-engine jet,
authorities said.
   The jet, which was en route to Chicago, was traveling at 100 to
115 mph and had not left the ground when the pilot applied the
brakes at Little Rock Regional Airport on Wednesday, said United
spokesman Rob Doughty.
   Passengers and flight attendants opened emergency hatches and
either climbed onto the wings or slid down evacuation chutes.
   Two passengers were in satisfactory condition today at St.
Vincent Infirmary Medical Center, nursing supervisors said. Among
seven others treated at hospitals and released were two women who
suffered broken ankles, officials said.
   Joe P. Carrigan, FAA assistant air traffic manager, said it is
uncertain if the aircraft would have crashed if it had taken off.
   ``An aircraft can fly on one engine,'' Carrigan said. ``There
are a lot of factors. It certainly would have tested his pilotage.''
   Doughty said the cause of the fire was under investigation.
</TEXT>
