<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0817EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Ultrasonic     08-11 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Ultrasonic,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Launching Superfast Passenger Jet Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is launching a project to develop an
ultrasonic passenger plane that will be able to fly between New
York and Tokyo in three to five hours, officials said today.
   The powerful Ministry of International Trade and Industry, which
helped engineer Japan's success in automobiles and computer chips,
is putting together teams of companies that will conduct research
on advanced engines and fuselage materials for the plane, MITI
officials said.
   Although the plane's top speed has not been decided, engineers
expect it will be able to fly up to five times the speed of sound,
or nearly 4,000 mph, the officials said. A non-stop flight between
Tokyo and New York now takes about 13 hours. The world's fastest
passenger jet now is the European-built Concorde, which can fly
about twice the speed of sound.
   An official in MITI's Aircraft Division said the two research
projects, to begin in 1989, will take seven to eight years to
complete.
   The government plans to allocate about $225 million to $260
million for engine research, and $52 million to $60 million for
research on fuselage materials, he said. The allocations still must
be approved formally by Japan's Finance Ministry and Parliament.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said MITI
decided to begin the research programs after it was approached in
1986 by the U.S. Boeing Co. and McDonnell Douglas about possible
Japanese participation in a similar superfast plane project in the
United States.
   Last year, the U.S. government reportedly began issuing
contracts for development of portions of the U.S. ultrasonic plane,
dubbed the ``Orient Express'' by President Reagan.
   After the MITI research projects end, the Japanese companies
involved will get together with U.S. companies working on superfast
plane technology and decide on plans for further development of the
plane, possibly with government guidance, the official said.
   Industry analysts say production of such an advanced plane would
take massive technical and financial resources, more than any
single company or country can provide.
   Although most of the Japanese research program is likely to be
conducted independently, the MITI officials said they don't intend
to compete with the United States.
   ``It's a very big project, so I don't think we will be
competitive,'' one official said. ``We'll need to work together.''
   Japan is advanced in many aspects of aviation and aerospace
technology, but the country's aircraft industry has had little
success so far on the international market. In recent years, MITI
has made the industry a high priority and has supported development
of key aircraft projects.
   Japanese companies are involved in manufacturing fuselage
sections for the Boeing 767 airliner, but analysts say the industry
is eager to achieve the status of full partner, rather than
subcontractor, in future joint projects.
   The MITI research projects would give Japanese companies a
chance to catch up with, and perhaps surpass, U.S. engine and
fuselage technology.
   The official in MITI's Aircraft Division said development of a
superfast plane would give Japan a major opportunity to boost its
aviation industry.
   The engine research, to focus on a combination turbo-jet and
ram-jet design, will be led by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and will
include Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries and Kawasaki Heavy
Industries, the official said.
   A group of about 20 companies will conduct the research on new
fuselage materials that meet the requirement of being able to
withstand temperatures above 900 degrees, he said.
</TEXT>
