<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan's School,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School President Attended Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan's old school _ a brick building
erected 80 years ago _ has been sold for $500.
   The only bidder on South Central School was the
privately-supported Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home Preservation
Foundation, which owns the Ronald Reagan Boyhood Home on the same
street.
   Charles T. Beckman, foundation secretary, said the group may use
the 46,000-square-foot building to house presidential memorabilia
or restore it as it was when Reagan attended fifth grade there. He
said the decision will be up to the president.
   Months ago the Dixon School Board set a selling price of $76,500
on the 1908 building, but there were no bidders at that price.
Assistant Superintendent Robert Aubry said the district has no use
for the building.
   ``It's in need of substantial repairs. A property is worth what
someone is willing to pay you,'' he said.
   South Central School is the only school still standing in Dixon
that Reagan attended. Classes have not been held there for several
years, but the building was used to house district offices.
</TEXT>
