<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DroughtOutlook     08-11 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Outlook,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecast Promises Little Drought Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 10-day outlook promises little relief from
the drought plaguing the nation, despite the wet remains of
tropical storm Beryl, the National Weather Service reports.
   While the remnants of Beryl could provide significant rain for
the Southeast, that's the only region likely to benefit, the agency
said in a drought advisory.
   Higher than normal temperatures are expected from the Northern
Plains to New England during the next five days, according to the
outlook, and that could persist for as long as 10 days.
   Normal rainfall is expected over much of the eastern two-thirds
of the nation, but significant shortages of water remain. Despite
some recent storms, six to 12 inches of rain are still needed to
return the Mississippi, Ohio and Tennessee valleys to near-normal
conditions.
   The Missouri Valley can continue to expect below-normal rain,
while it could be somewhat above normal in the Great Lakes and New
England regions, the forecast said.
   The forest fire potential for the next five days will be very
high to extreme in the far West, Great Basin and Northern Plains
states, the report added. The risk is medium in a band extending
from Arizona to Michigan and medium to low in the South and East.
</TEXT>
