<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Corruption,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Probe Looks Into Alleged Diversion Of Funds To Chun Family Tomb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National legislators today inspected
the tomb of former President Chun Doo-hwan's parents to investigate
allegations that he diverted government funds for a lavish memorial.
   Governing and opposition party lawmakers visited Chun's
birthplace near the southern city of Hapchon as part of a probe of
alleged corruption involving Chun and his family.
   The opposition says Chun ordered government officials to
construct a large garden and decorations around the tomb.
   The Korean news agency Yonhap said the lawmakers earlier visited
the southern city of Kwangju to inspect a governor's residence.
   They found that the government spent about $1.7 million to
transform the governor's residence into a luxurious safe house for
Chun, Yonhap said.
   Officials said the legislators, from a special assembly
committee, also planned to inspect a luxury lakeside villa built by
Chun and now used by President Roh Tae-woo as a presidential summer
house.
   The opposition wants the former president, who left office in
February at the end of a seven-year term, to testify before the
assembly about corruption under his administration. Roh's governing
party has opposed the idea.
   Roh played a key role in helping Chun seize power with military
backing in 1980. Roh won election in December when the opposition
fielded two presidential candidates.
   Chun's younger brother, Chun Kyong-hwan, is on trial on charges
of embezzling millions of dollars. His wife, Lee Soon-ja, and her
family also have been under public fire for alleged
influence-peddling and corruption during her husband's
administraion.
   Son Joo-hwan, a senior governing party lawmaker, today said his
party would disclose alleged corruption by opposition leaders if
the opposition pressed for Chun's testimony.
   Son claimed opposition leaders Kim Dae-jung and Kim Young-sam
have diverted party funds to invest in real estate, stocks and
other private businesses.
