<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BlackConvention     08-11 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Convention,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activist Seeks Blacks-Only Convention to Select Mayoral Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans are under way for a pair of blacks-only
conventions at which a single black candidate would be selected to
run for mayor next year.
   ``White people remain true to their people first,'' said Lu
Palmer, chairman of the Black Independent Political Organization
and the moving force behind the plan. ``We, as black people, should
think of black people first.''
   Palmer said Wednesday he fears that if more than one black
candidate surfaces, a white candidate will win easily in next
year's special election to serve out the remaining two years in the
late Harold Washington's term.
   Washington, Chicago's first black mayor, died of a heart attack
in November.
   ``Politically, economically, socially ..., nothing in the city
or the country matters as much as race,'' Palmer said.
   The first convention, on Aug. 27, would allow representatives of
black churches and other organizations to hear from all ``serious''
black candidates, he said.
   Delegates would poll their organizations and vote at a second
convention in late September. Each candidate would be asked to sign
a pledge to abide by the results, Palmer said.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer, a black selected with white support in
December to serve until the special election, said he has not
decided whether to attend the conventions and questioned the
concept of anall-black selection process.
   ``Due to the fact that we're making an effort to make this one
Chicago, I'm not sure that it's a good idea,'' he said.
   Supporters of Alderman Timothy Evans, considered Sawyer's chief
rival in the mayoral contest, said the conventions could be rigged
in favor of yet another potential black candidate, Alderman Danny
Davis.
   Davis said he will participate in the conventions but would
prefer that the conventions be open to ``the entire progressive
community.''
   ``We know that race and ethnicity have long undergirded politics
in Chicago,'' Davis said. ``But I hope and desire to try and help
Chicago move beyond the politics of race.''
</TEXT>
