<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Ethiopian Hostages,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy Reports Two Hostages Freed by Ethiopian Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Italian technicians kidnapped by Ethiopian
rebels in November have been freed, the Italian Foreign Ministry
reported today.
   It said the two men, Salvatore Barone and Paolo Bellini, reached
the Sudanese capital of Khartoum today. It gave no details on their
release but said it came after a ``long and complex action'' by the
Italian government.
   The two men were abducted Nov. 16 at Lake Tana in northwestern
Ethiopia, where they were working on a project to build a dike on
the Blue Nile and construct roads in the area.
   A little known group called the Ethiopian People's Revolutionary
Party claimed responsibility, saying the Italians were seized
because the project they were working on would strengthen the
Ethiopian government.
   In May, there were reports the men were released but they turned
out to be false.
   A third Italian, Giuseppe Micelli, has been held by Ethiopian
rebels since June.
