<2ND_LINE>PM-Libya-West Bank, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0474,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Says Libya Will Pay Employees in West Bank, Gaza</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf pvs, ``Jordan ruled...'' to ADD background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi said his
country will pay the salaries of former Jordanian employees in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Radio Monte Carlo
reported today.
   Libya ``announces through your radio station that it will take
the responsibility of paying the salaries,'' Gadhafi told the
radio's Paris-based Arabic service. In the interview, conducted
Wednesday by phone, the Libyan leader estimated the cost at about
$1 million a month.
   Jordan has been paying the salaries of 21,200 Palestinians in
the occupied territories but King Hussein announced last week that
he was handing over that responsibility to the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   He challenged the PLO to set up a Palestinian state in the West
Bank, where the PLO has been helping lead an 8-month-old uprising
against Israeli rule that has killed nearly 239 Palestinians and
four Israelis.
   Some of Jordan's cuts are being phased in gradually.
   According to Jordanian figures, the salaries were costing around
$45 million a year, but Hussein said only a fraction of those
affected were classified as civil servants.
   The rest worked in institutions that received Jordanian
subsidies.
   Gadhafi did not say how many people's salaries he would pay, but
said he would begin the payments Aug. 16. He also said he supported
the setting up of a Palestinian government-in-exile.
   Asked about Hussein's moves to turn over responsibility for the
occupied territories to the PLO, Gadhafi said the king had never
done anything for Jerusalem, the occupied territories or Palestine
in general.
   In addition to retiring or laying off the employees, Hussein
canceled a proposed $1.3 billion development plan for the occupied
lands, abolished a government ministry responsible for the area and
dissolved the lower house of Parliament, half of whose members were
Palestinian.
   Jordan ruled the West Bank from 1948 until Israel seized it in
1967. Jordan has paid salaries of government workers there and in
the Gaza Strip, which Israel seized from Egypt in 1967, but Jordan
claimed sovereignty only over the West Bank.
</TEXT>
