<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailhouseRomance     08-11 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailhouse Romance,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prisoner Seeking to Wed Female Inmate Launches Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel bars are the only thing that stand
between William Ernest Kuenzell and his true love.
   The murder suspect said he's found his bride-to-be in an
adjoining cell at the Talladega County jail and vows he won't eat
until he can marry her. The unidentified woman is serving a
four-year sentence for burglary.
   ``It's been a heck of a way to carry on a romance, by hollering
at each other from their jail cells,'' said sheriff's Lt. Charles
Bonner. ``The only time the two see each other is once a week
during Sunday morning church service in one of the courtrooms.''
   Sheriff's investigator Alan Yates said the only other time the
two can glimpse each other is ``if one of them is being escorted up
or down the hall at the jail.''
   The Sheriff's Department has no policy on marriages between
prisoners, but Bonner said he doubted Sheriff Jerry Studdard would
approve such a union. Studdard was out of town and could not be
reached for comment.
   ``We've had marriages performed in the jail before, but it has
always been when an outsider came in to marry a prisoner,'' Bonner
said.
   Kuenzell began his hunger strike Sunday. He appeared in good
health Wednesday, Bonner said.
   ``He is checked twice a week by a doctor. If he continues the
strike and it becomes necessary, we can get a court order to have
him force fed,'' Bonner said.
   Kuenzell is charged in the 1987 shotgun slaying of a convenience
store clerk. His trial is scheduled to begin next week.
</TEXT>
