<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-KhmerRouge 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Khmer Rouge, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0513,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Reiterates Support For Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with quote. Pickup 4th pvs,
``Jin also...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China today said it will ship weapons to the
Khmer Rouge until Vietnam withdraws all its troops from Cambodia.
   The announcement came several weeks after Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, the leader of the Cambodian resistance, accused the Khmer
Rouge of killing his followers and threatened to unite with
anti-Khmer Rouge forces to drive them from Cambodia.
   ``So long as Vietnam doesn't withdraw from Cambodia, China will
continue to assist the resistance group, including the Khmer
Rouge,'' Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua said today.
   In the past, China has said it would ``respect'' the wishes of
the prince. Today, Jin said China had no comment on Sihanouk's
statements.
   Jin also told a news conference that a date had yet to be set
for talks with the Soviet Union in Beijing on Cambodia.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and forced the Khmer Rouge
from power. During its four-year rule, the Khmer Rouge killed
millions of Cambodians while pushing a fanatical brand of agrarian
communism.
   In the early 1980s, a three-party resistance group, made up of
Sihanouk; Son Sann, a Western-leaning politician; and the Khmer
Rouge, was established to fight the Vietnamese occupation.
   As the resistance group relied more and more on China and the
capitalist countries of Southeast Asia, Vietnam moved closer to the
Soviet Union.
   Vietnam has pledged to withdraw its 120,000 troops from Cambodia
by 1991 but wants the Khmer Rouge to play no future role in the
Cambodian government.
   The three-party resistance group held its first meeting with the
Vietnamese-backed Cambodian government in late July in Indonesia.
   Sihanouk went to Indonesia and spoke to those attending the
conference but refused to attend the meeting itself.
   Upon his return to Beijing after the conference, Sihanouk said
it had been a success but chances for peace were slim.
   In previous weeks, he had criticized the Khmer Rouge and said he
was willing to unite with anti-Khmer Rouge factions. The prince is
known for his contradictory statements and for his tendency to
resign as president of the resistance group. He most recently quit
in early July.
   Jin said those who were calling on China to stop supporting the
Khmer Rouge ``would only help the Vietnamese aggressors achieve
their goal in Cambodia.''
   He said China supports a Cambodia that is ``independent,
peaceful and non-aligned.''
   The spokesman said China would not support ``any party
monopolizing power at the expense of any other party,'' a reference
to concerns that the Khmer Rouge will regain power once Vietnam
leaves Cambodia.
   Recent reports have said diplomats from China and the Soviet
Union will meet in Beijing this month to discuss a Cambodian
settlement.
   Jin said he had no information on the meeting, but a Soviet
diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the meeting
would occur after Aug. 20 but before the end of the month.
   He said the Soviet Union was waiting for results of a meeting
scheduled Aug. 15 on the Cambodian question between five countries.
Indonesia, Zimbabwe, India, Cuba and Vietnam are scheduled to meet
in Harare, Zimbabwe.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
