<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Perpich-Education     08-11 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perpich-Education,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perpich School Choice Plan Drawing Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rudy Perpich will recommend expanding
Minnesota's school-choice plan to other states when he becomes the
chairman of a national education group on Saturday, and the plan
already is drawing opposition.
   Perpich's plan allows parents and students to choose their
schools regardless of where they live and puts schools in
competition for those students.
   Several members of the policy and priorities committee of the
Education Commission of the States objected to the proposal
Wednesday at the organization's annual meeting in Baltimore.
   Critics told Perpich the plan would sharpen disparities between
poor and wealthy districts rather than increase opportunities for
equal education for all.
   ``What you're going to end up with is very, very good schools
and very, very mediocre schools. ... I think the charge is to make
all schools great,'' said Colorado state Sen. Regis Groff.
   Perpich is defending the plan, which encountered opposition
before its 1987 adoption in Minnesota.
   ``Together we must work toward the day when parents and students
have the freedom to choose a school on the basis of its excellence
instead of its geographical location,'' Perpich said in the text of
a speech to be given give Saturday when he succeeds Missouri Gov.
John Ashcroft as commission chairman.
   ``The failure of our schools to provide equal access to
educational excellence is creating a situation that, if trends
continue, will force businesses to hire more than a million new
service and production workers every year who can't read, write or
count.''
   He estimated that it costs business up to $25 billion a year in
fees and lost productivity to educate those workers.
</TEXT>
