<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0442 08-11 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New in first 9 grafs to UPDATE with speech; picks up 3rd graf
pvs bgng: Dukakis also ...; minor editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today lauded President Reagan
for reaching arms agreements with the Soviet Union but said his
space-based defense plan should be scrapped in favor of beefing up
conventional forces.
   The Democratic presidential nominee, in a speech at New York
University, did not mention Republican challenger George Bush by
name but made it clear he believed Bush would continue defense
policies that Dukakis said had benefitted greedy contractors at the
expense of national security.
   ``We've got to have a real leader in the White House who will
insist that when it comes to our national security we're going to
make our decisions based not on what's good for one company or one
military service or one political party but on what's good for
America,'' Dukakis said in his prepared text.
   ``My friends, the test of a successful defense policy isn't how
much money we spend; it's how much security we buy,'' Dukakis said.
``And for the past eight years, we haven't gotten what we've gone
into debt for.''
   Dukakis said that if elected he would seek to expand on the arms
agreements negotiated with the Soviets by Reagan but promised to
``judge Soviet leaders not by what they say but what they do.''
   Dukakis promised to ``clean up the mess'' in Pentagon
procurement policies and redirect defense dollars from the
``seemingly endless development of new and more expensive nuclear
weapons systems,'' a reference to the president's Star Wars missile
defense program, to new tanks and other supplies for conventional
forces and the Coast Guard.
   ``We have to build strong military forces based on sound
planning and tough management, not wishful thinking and blank
checks,'' Dukakis sad.
   He said the choice in November presented ``the opportunity to
restore America's leadership in the world. Or we can settle for
second best.''
   The speech came at the beginning of a five-state campaign swing.
From New York, the Massachusetts governor was traveling to New
Jersey to tour Fort Dix.
   Dukakis also had evening appearances scheduled in two
Connecticut communities before heading to Richmond, Va., to spend
the night at the governor's mansion. He was to campaign in Virginia
and Florida on Friday before spending the weekend on Cape Cod.
   The Massachusetts governor on Wednesday tended to state
business, including a groundbreaking ceremony that was part of a $6
billion effort to clean up Boston Harbor, the nation's filthiest.
   Dukakis balked at spending money for new sewage treatment plants
during his first term as governor in the mid-1970s, but said it was
``revisionist history'' to blame him for delays in beginning the
cleanup.
   ``Nobody could really tell us what to do to clean up this
place,'' Dukakis said. ``There were very respected people, experts
in the field, who disagreed.''
   But the state now faces a federal court timetable to stop
polluting the harbor by 1999, with several deadlines relating to
sewage treatment and sludge dumping spread throughout the next
decade.
   The cleanup is the largest public works project in Massachusetts
history, and Dukakis, as he did last week in California, boasted of
the jobs it would create.
   But Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, took Dukakis to task
on the cleanup.
   ``If it takes the governor of Massachusetts 11 years to clean up
his own harbor, Americans must question his commitment to the even
larger environmental questions which face our nation,'' he said.
   Atwater said the delay will cause the average Boston water bill
to skyrocket over the next eight years.
   A Gallup survey released Tuesday put Dukakis' support at 49
percent and Bush's at 42 percent in telephone interviews with 1,004
registered voters Aug. 5-7. A Gallup poll just two weeks ago gave
Dukakis a 17-point margin _ 54 percent to 37 percent. Each survey
had a 3 percentage point margin of error.
   ``The race has always been tight,'' Dukakis said in shrugging
off the new numbers. ``This is going to be a very tough,
competitive 90 days.''
   ``The only thing that these numbers tell you is that the
Democratic ticket is competitive in every region of the country and
in every state of the country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
