<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Egypt-Sinking 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Sinking, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0511,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies of Five Italians, Four Egyptians Reported Found</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf at end to UPDATE with most survivors flying back
to Italy.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers today pulled from the Nile the
bodies of five Italian tourists and four Egyptians who were on a
tour boat that sank in a storm, the Middle East News Agency said.
Twenty-four people remained missing.
   The state-owned agency quoted police Gen. Ibrahim Bassiouny,
head of security of Aswan, 600 miles south of Cairo, as saying the
nine bodies were found when the search resumed this morning.
   The steamer Nubia was sailing from Aswan to Luxor on Wednesday
when the storm hit and it capsized and sank. It was carrying 51
Italians and an Egyptian crew of 45.
   Both Luxor and Aswan are favorite tourist resorts. Luxor is
famed for its Valley of the Kings Pharaonic necropolis and the
Karnak temple complex.
   An Italian Embassy spokesman in Cairo said 35 Italians were
rescued, some suffering minor injuries and shock, on Wednesday.
   Twenty-seven Egyptian crewmen also were rescued on Wednesday and
the body of one was picked up from the water.
   The Cairo newspaper Al-Ahram said most of the tourists were
below deck in their cabins when the boat sank.
   The paper quoted skipper Mohammed Ahmed Ibrahim, who was
injured, as saying the boat sank because of the strong currents
resulting from the storm.
   The Italian news agency ANSA quoted tour director Paolo Fissora
as saying, ``An extremely violent storm arrived all of a sudden,
and in 30 seconds, the huge ship had gone to the bottom.
   ``I don't remember it all very well. In just a few minutes, I
found myself in the water,'' Fissora told ANSA in a telephone
interview.
   Italian ambassador Giovanni Migliuolo and senior Egyptian
security men immediately rushed to the scene. Egyptian divers were
flown to the site to search for the missing.
   The embassy spokesman said most of the Italian survivors had
flown back to Italy from Luxor on a chartered plane. He said one or
two of them with relatives or friends among the missing opted to
stay.
</TEXT>
