<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BizWeekProbe     08-11 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biz Week Probe,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Printer Fires Three More Employees In Business Week Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that prints Business Week magazine says
it has fired three more production workers and exhausted all leads
in its investigation of employees who leaked advance copies of an
influential column.
   Investigators believe the leaked information was used to buy and
sell stocks to take advantage of changes in their price after the
magazine came out.
   ``We're not totally sure that it's all over,'' R.R. Donnelley &
Sons spokesman Arthur Prine said Wednesday. ``We're not pursuing
any new leads at this moment. If any more evidence or leads turn
up, we'll be investigating them.''
   The firings late last week at the company's Old Saybrook, Conn.,
plant brought to seven the number of Donnelley employees who have
either been fired or resigned in connection with the company's
investigation.
   No criminal charges have been filed. The Chicago-based company
said it is considering pressing charges for theft.
   Investigations of the scandal also have resulted in firings or
resignations of several stockbrokers.
   Prine said Donnelley would continue to cooperate with the
Securities and Exchange Commission in its investigation.
   The latest three workers fired were involved in passing advance
copies of Business Week to William Dillon, a former Merrill Lynch &
Co. stockbroker who allegedly traded on the information in the
``Inside Wall Street'' column, Prine said.
   Donnelley earlier fired two other workers at the Old Saybrook
plant and fired a quality-control supervisor at its Torrance,
Calif., plant suspected of trading in Business Week-touted stocks.
   A Donnelley production supervisor in Torrance who also bought
and sold stocks mentioned in the column resigned, the company said.
   Federal authorities are investigating to determine whether laws
were broken. Buying and selling stocks on information unavailable
to the public is insider trading and constitutes fraud under
federal securities laws.
</TEXT>
