   The Philippine News Agency quoted Col. Eduardo Resos, army
provincial commander, as saying the military has pinpointed where
the kidnappers took David Blair Stiffler, a New York construction
worker, and his wife, Elpidia.
   The Stifflers were abducted at gunpoint on July 30 by Moslem
bandits while aboard a van near Marawi, 510 miles south of Manila.
Lanao del Sur is known as a lawless province where numerous
kidnappings occured in the past.
   The report said efforts by civilian negotiators to get the
kidnappers to free their hostages had bogged down. The civilian
officials gave the kidnappers until noon today to free the couple,
but the kidnappers ignored the deadline.
   The military issued a similar ultimatum, then extended the
deadline to noon Friday (midnight EDT tonight).
   Resos said troops have sealed off all exits points and have
brought in artillery and helicopters for possible rescue operations.
   ``We are still hoping that the kidnappers will come to their
senses and relase their hostages in the name of peace,'' the agency
quoted Resos as saying.
   There are no telephone lines to Marawi. In the past the military
has issued ultimatums but extended them after they elapsed.
</TEXT>
