<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-CreditCards     08-11 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Credit Cards,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan To Allow Banks To Issue Credit Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks in Taiwan will be allowed to issue
credit cards, the government announced today.
   The United States has urged Taiwan to allow credit cards as part
of a program to open financial markets.
   Jacob Chao, general manager of American Express International
(Taiwan) Inc., said his company had sought permission to issue
credit cards in Taiwan for five years.
   Local banks have been allowed to issue only debit cards, which
draw on funds already deposited. Businesses are not restricted from
accepting credit cards from foreign customers.
   Wang Chao-ming, spokesman for the government's Council for
Economic Planning and Development, made the announcement. He said
the government planned two years ago to let banks issue credit
cards but delayed the move because of concern it might lead to an
outflow of foreign reserves to overseas credit card companies.
Taiwan has $71 billion in foreign reserves.
   The new rules will take effect after a formal announcement by
the Finance Ministry. No date for that announcement was set.
</TEXT>
