<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Temptation,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scorsese Film Draws Protest in Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of protesters picketed and prayed
outside a Toronto movie theater when Martin Scorsese's film, ``The
Last Temptation of Christ,'' debuted in Canada at a special preview
screening.
   ``Martin Scorsese is crucifying Christ again on celluloid,''
said Gary Gould, one of a dozen people at the demonstration
Wednesday night.
   Roman Catholic women chanted the rosary and three male Baptists
carried signs saying ``Read The True Story'' and ``Once Was
Enough.'' The evangelical organization Renaissance Canada urged
federal Justice Minister Ray Hnatyshyn to ban the film as ``hate
literature'' under the Criminal Code.
   None of the protesters had seen the movie, which opens to the
public on Friday.
   Canada's leading critic, Jay Scott of The Globe and Mail,
strongly defended the film. He began a half-page review by saying
the film was not, as some have alleged, ``disrespectful,
irreverent, blasphemous or anti-religious.''
   He termed it an intense exploration of the conflict between
spirit and flesh, and a ``courageous film that people of all
religions or no religion should be able to watch with identical
fascination.''
   Scorsese attended Wednesday's screening, a benefit for the
Canadian Center for Advanced Film Studies. The center was founded
by Norman Jewison, who directed the controversial ``Jesus Christ
Superstar.''
</TEXT>
