<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Ga-Congressional     08-11 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ga-Congressional,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gloves Come Off in Suburban Atlanta Congressional Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just hours after former actor Ben Jones won the
Democratic nomination for Congress, the gloves came off in the race
for the suburban Atlanta seat, with incumbent Pat Swindall raising
the issue of Jones' past alcoholism.
   Jones, 46, who appeared on the ``Dukes of Hazzard'' TV series,
branded Swindall's remarks a ploy to divert attention from the
Republican's admission that he considered accepting laundered drug
money to finance an expensive home.
   ``He's obviously trying to deflect attention from his own
problems of the present by dealing with problems of my past,''
Jones said Wednesday.
   The race heated up Wednesday, the day after Jones soundly
defeated two challengers to win the 4th District's Democratic
nomination a second time. Two years ago, Jones got 47 percent of
the vote in losing to Swindall.
   Swindall, who was unopposed for the GOP nomination, sent a
letter to Jones Wednesday congratulating him and saying that before
the two debate, ``several issues regarding your qualifications for
office'' must be resolved.
   Specifically, Swindall raised ``the issue of your alcoholism and
past arrests'' and asked Jones for copies of his arrest and health
records by Friday.
   Jones in turn suggested Swindall ``meet me at Emory Hospital on
Friday and that we have a complete physical and mental evaluation''
as well as random drug testing throughout the campaign.
   Swindall said Wednesday night he would not oblige Jones. Jones
said his arrest records are part of the public record and Swindall
could obtain them himself.
   The former actor said that he has not taken a drink since 1977
and that he has often spoke to church and student groups about his
alcoholism.
   He was arrested several times during his drinking days on
misdemeanor disorderly conduct charges.
   He said his driving record included speeding tickets and driving
with an expired license, but that he has never been arrested for
drunken driving.
   Swindall was charged with drunken driving in 1980 but records
indicate he was not prosecuted because of insufficient evidence.
Earlier this year, it was learned that Swindall was involved in an
undercover money-laundering investigation.
   A government videotape showed Swindall pursuing an $850,000 loan
_ even after learning it might be financed with drug money _ until
he was told by a man later identified as a federal agent that
Swindall would have to accept the proceeds in person and sign a
receipt.
   Swindall said later he was ``embarrassed and ashamed'' that he
considered accepting the loan but said he did not violate any law
because he did not take the money. He has asked the House Ethics
Committee to investigate his actions.
</TEXT>
