<HEAD>Ultra-Orthodox Plant Bombs To Protest Secular Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant ultra-Orthodox Israelis planted five
bombs in a Tel Aviv suburb today to protest the sale of secular
newspapers, police said.
   Three exploded but caused no injuries. Police said the bombs
went off before dawn near newspaper stands selling secular dailies
in the Bnei Brak suburb, most of whose residents are observant Jews.
   Two other bombs were discovered and dismantled near the homes of
two shop owners who sell secular newspapers, police spokeswoman
Dalia Gilad said.
   Mrs. Gilad said a radical, Jerusalem-based, ultra-Orthodox group
claimed responsibility for the explosions in calls to Israeli
newspapers and the shopkeepers themselves.
   ``They gave the exact location of the bombs,'' Mrs. Gilad said.
The callers said they were protesting the sale of secular
newspapers, she reported.
   In the past, the group has painted slogans on the tombstones of
Israel's founding fathers in Jerusalem. Some ultra-Orthodox Jews
are anti-Zionist and believe Israel should have been founded only
after the coming of the Messiah.
   ``It's a miracle there were no casualties and property damage
was so small,'' Israel radio quoted local police Commander Arie
Amit as saying.
   Mrs. Gilad said large police forces searched Bnei Brak for other
bombs.
</TEXT>
