<2ND_LINE>PM-Explorer Stamps,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Stamps to Honor Antarctic Explorers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is issuing a block of
commemorative stamps honoring four American explorers of the
Antarctic.
   Nathaniel B. Palmer, Charles Wilkes, Richard E. Byrd and Lincoln
Ellsworth will be pictured on stamps to be issued Sept. 14 in
ceremonies at the National Geographic Society in Washington.
   Palmer was the first American to view Antarctica, discovering
the peninsula that bears his name in 1820. Wilkes led an expedition
in 1836-1843 that proved Antarctica to be a separate continent.
   Perhaps the best-known American explorer of the Antarctic, Byrd
conducted five expdeditions to the region and organized
photographic mapping of the continent by air in the 1920s and `30s.
   Ellsworth led four expeditions southward in the 1930s and was
the first person to fly over both the Arctic and Antarctic.
</TEXT>
