<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Jordan     08-11 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Jordan,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Leaders Disagree On Jordan's West Bank Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top aides of PLO leader Yasser
Arafat disagreed over the implications of Jordan's move to cut ties
to the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, with one calling
it a violation of Arab trust.
   ``It is regrettable that the move was taken at the start of an
international political vacuum (that prevails) from here till after
the American elections,'' Khaled Al-Hassan said in an interview
published today in the Saudi Arabian newspaper Al-Sharq Al-Awsat.
   ``Jordan was committed by Arab summit resolutions to certain
obligations toward the West Bank until the land is liberated. ...
The legal and administrative disengagement is a violation of those
commitments,'' he said.
   Al-Hassan is member of the central committee of Fatah, the
leadership of the main guerrilla group under the PLO umbrella.
   But in the neighboring United Arab Emirates, Arafat's right-hand
man in Fatah, Salah Khalaf, was quoted as saying: ``It is a
courageous decision, and enables the Palestine Liberation
Organization to shoulder its responsibility and take over new
political rights.''
   The statements by Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad, were published
in the newspaper Al-Bayan of Dubai.
   In his first comments on the move, made this week to Al-Sharq
Al-Awsat, Arafat expressed anger that King Hussein of Jordan had
acted without consulting the PLO. He also criticized the timing of
the move but would not talk at length ``so as not to explode
relations with Jordan.''
   However, a rival Palestinian group charged today that Arafat was
well aware of the measures before the king announced them.
   In Damascus, a spokesman, Fatah-Uprising, another faction led by
Col. Abu Mousa, said the group has ``information that contacts took
place between King Hussein and Yasser Arafat on the eve of
announcing the Jordanian decision ... contrary to what the PLO
claimed about not having been consulted in advance.''
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said the
group was staunchly opposed to forming a Palestinian
government-in-exile.
   Hussein's measures, which cut Jordan's political and
administrative links with 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, left an administrative vacuum in the
Israeli-occupied areas.
   Palestinians in the areas have been rioting against Israeli
military rule for the past eight months. Nearly 240 Palestinians
and four Israelis have been killed since the violence began Dec 8.
   The PLO seeks an independent Palestinian state on the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, both seized by Israel in June 1967.
   Al-Hassan also told Al-Sharq Al-Awsat the PLO was not consulted
before Jordan acted. ``This step casts thick shadows on the
relationship of Palestinian-Jordanian partnership,'' he said.
   He said problems would develop when government employees who no
longer receive salaries from Jordan seek other jobs and those who
used to have Jordanian passports seek other travel documents.
   ``The move has political implications that could have grave
implications for others than the PLO,'' he said. He did not
elaborate.
</TEXT>
