<HEAD>Teen Who Pleaded Guilty To Riot Gets Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who pleaded guilty to riot in the
Howard Beach racial attack that left a black man dead has been
placed on five years' probation.
   State Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos imposed the sentence
Wednesday on Harry Buonocore, 19. Buonocore accepted the plea
bargain before the start of the second trial to result from the
attack in the Queens neighborhood in 1986.
   Three teen-agers were convicted of manslaughter in the first
trial in the death of Michael Griffith, who was struck and killed
by a car while fleeing the gang of whites that had attacked him and
two other black men.
   Three of the five defendants in the second trial were convicted
last month of riot. They face up to a year in jail at sentencing
next month.
