<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlantBodyguard     08-11 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Bodyguard,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tennis Club Must Hire Botanist to Guard Endangered Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Thompson need not take time to stop
and smell the flowers _ he'll be paying someone else upwards of
$20,000 to handle that.
   Thompson, who plans to add a pool to his 10-acre Oakland Hills
Tennis Club, was told by the city Planning Commission Wednesday he
must have a botanist on duty during the project because of a nearby
patch of endangered wildflowers.
   The patch is only one of three known sites in the world for the
white and maroon Clarkia franciscana.
   ``I'm very privileged to have it on my land,'' Thompson said,
``but it's more of a nuisance than anything.''
   The botanist _ who at $100 an hour Thompson figures may cost as
much as $20,000 _ would have to stay during excavation and concrete
pouring for the pool, which is 20 feet from the wildflowers.
   ``With what it's costing,'' said Michael Dean, his attorney, ``I
told him maybe he should charge admission for people to see it.''
   Clarkia, an annual, blooms in the spring. In the heat of summer
it withers, leaving seeds behind.
   ``They won't even be out when we're building,'' Thompson said.
``You won't even be able to tell they're there.''
   Clarkia, known as the Presidio Clarkia, was discovered at the
Army's Presidio base in San Francisco in 1958. It is one of 187
plants on the state's endangered species list and a candidate for
the federal government's list.
   ``You never know,'' said Jim Burns, Thompson's architect.
``There might be a future cure for cancer found in that plant.''
</TEXT>
