<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Ship Attack,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Police Raided Home Of Mastermind of Greek Ship Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security police today said they raided
the home of a Palestinian, and a newspaper said the man
masterminded the terrorist attack on a Greek cruise ship last month.
   Police spokesman Ingvar Eriksson said investigators found four
Kalashnykov assault rifles among a cache of weapons hidden in a
forest a few miles from the home of Samir Mohammed Khaidir. He
would not say when the raid took place.
   The newspaper Aftonbladet said police conducted the raid in late
July and they believe Khaidir was the operations chief of the Abu
Nidal terrorist group and masterminded the July 11 assault on the
cruise ship ``City of Poros.''
   Ericksson declined to discuss Khaidir's role but said he was
believed to be one of nine people killed in the attack. More than
90 people were wounded in the assault on the ship in the
Mediterranean. The Abu Nidal group issued a statement after the
attack saying its members were not responsible.
   He said Khaidir, who was born in Lebanon in 1948 and described
himself as an international businessman, lived in a Stockholm
suburb since 1986 under the name of his Finnish-born wife. The name
is barred from publication under Swedish press laws, Eriksson said.
   Aftonbladet said police raided his apartment after an airline
ticket to Scandinavia was found in a Greek hotel room.
   Khaidir left Stockholm at the beginning of June and flew via
Copenhagen, Denmark, to Athens, under the name Hejab Aballa, the
paper said.
   Eriksson refused to discuss evidence found in the apartment and
said police were still investigating the seized documents.
   The newspaper said some documents linked Khaidir to the
hijacking of a Pan Am airliner to Karachi in 1986 and other
operations claimed by Abu Nidal. Sixteen people were killed in a
rescue operation by Pakistani authorities.
</TEXT>
