<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Walk-UpOrder     08-11 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walk-Up Order,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pedestrian Insists On Ordering At Drive-In Window</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Jones may be taking commercials a bit
too seriously.
   Jones ordered a hamburger at the drive-through window at a
Wendy's restaurant Wednesday. Like the man in the Wendy's
commercial, he wasn't driving a car.
   Wendy's would not serve him and had to call the police when he
refused to get out of the way of other, behind-the-wheel customers.
He was not arrested.
   Jones said he saw the TV ad and was hoping to get the special
sale price good only at the window. ``There's nothing there that
says you have to be in a car,'' he said. ``It just seemed
ridiculous I couldn't get the burgers on sale.''
   In the commercial, a pedestrian picks up an order at the
drive-through window. Told that he's not in a car, he responds,
``That's what they told me at the car wash.''
   The ad and special sale price are part of a promotion to
increase sales at the window, said Frank Gallardo, Wendy's district
manager. He said company policy is to serve only people in a
vehicle because the traffic makes the lane dangerous for
pedestrians.
   Although similar incidents have occurred, Gallardo said, this
was the first time police had to be called.
   ``The strange thing is, he had a vehicle he could have used,''
Gallardo said.
</TEXT>
