<DOCNO> AP880811-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignMoney     08-11 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Money,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PACs Boost Contributions To Congressional Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political action committees have boosted their
contributions to House and Senate candidates, Democrats and
incumbents in the 1987-88 election cycle, but they're giving less
to Republicans.
   Statistics released Thursday by the Federal Election Commission
said Democratic candidates experienced the most dramatic jump in
PAC donations, collecting $52 million from Jan. 1, 1987 to June 30,
1988. That's 44.4 percent better than they did last time around.
   Republicans, by contrast, collected $28 million from PACs _ a
6.7 percent drop. Since Democrats wrested control of the Senate in
1986, the GOP has been in the minority in both chambers.
   Incumbents received $66 million from PACs, a 29.4 percent
increase over the last election cycle. Challengers remained steady
with PAC donations of $7 million. Candidates for open seats
received $6 million, a 25 percent drop from two years ago.
   House candidates experienced a 29.3 percent rise in PAC
contributions, up to $53 million. And PACs were not the only rising
financial indicator for House candidates, according to the FEC
analysis.
   Spending by House candidates rose 11 percent this year to $111
million and fund-raising was up nearly 12 percent, to $154 million,
the agency said. Greater numbers of House incumbents are seeking
re-election, accounting for part of the across-the-board jump.
   On the Senate side, spending and fund-raising dropped _ at least
partly due to the differences between 1986 and 1988 candidates and
races. Spending fell 23.9 percent to $70 million, while
fund-raising declined 6.5 percent to $116 million, the FEC said.
   PAC contributions to Senate candidates continued to rise,
however, from $24 million two years ago to $27 million during the
current cycle.
   Overall, money raised by House and Senate candidates so far in
this cycle came to $270 million, up 3 percent from two years ago.
Spending by candidates for the two chambers stood at $181 million,
a 5.7 percent decline.
   The FEC said the number of candidates participating in federal
elections continued to decline, a trend that started in 1984. The
decline this year is confined to Democrats, the agency said,
particularly challengers and open seat campaigns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
