<HEAD>Angola Apologizes For Shooting At President's Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GABORONE, Botswana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola has apologized for the attack
by one of its warplanes on a private jet carrying Botswana's
president, a Cabinet minister said Thursday.
   Ponatshego Kedikilwe, minister for presidential affairs, said
Angola sent a note to Botswana saying the plane carrying President
Quett Masire had been mistaken for an enemy aircraft.
   One of two jet engines on Masire's 10-seater plane was shot off
Sunday as it flew 38,000 feet over Angola on the way from Gaborone
to a meeting in the Angolan capital, Luanda. The pilot made an
emergency landing at the town of Kuito in central Bie province.
   Masire and one of his aides were slightly injured when fragments
from the right engine penetrated the cabin.
   Kedikilwe, who was aboard the plane, said cordial relations
between Angola and Botswana would not be affected by the incident.
   Angola said the plane was flying in a corridor that has been
closed because of the war being waged by Angola and its Cuban
allies against South African- and U.S.-backed rebels.
