<HEAD>67 Men Wanted in Sex Cases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday that 67
white men, including a minister and prominent businessmen, are
suspects in child sex rings that operated in Johannesburg and Cape
Town.
   All the suspects are being investigated in connection with
sexual abuse of white boys, said Leon Mellet, a spokesman for the
Law and Order Ministry. He said some have been arrested and others
were being sought.
   He said the investigation started in June.
   Mellet said the suspects, 38 in Johannesburg and 29 in Cape
Town, also included a school principal and an engineer.
   One man, who police allege had kept a 17-year-old youth a
virtual prisoner at his home, committed suicide after police
questioning, Mellet said.
   Mellet said the case involved rings that allegedly traded boys,
and police concentrated on cases involving child prostitution,
indecent assault, sexual activity with minors and sodomy.
