<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 3rdLd-Writethru a0544 08-11 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0544,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burma Faces Anarchy, Military Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Burma commander warning of
anarchy, 15 more killed, wounded; CORRECTS spelling of Okkalapa
throughout. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``The protests...'' TRIMS
thereafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military commander today warned
that Burma faces anarchy, and official media said 15 more people
were killed and 81 wounded as anti-government violence spread to
Rangoon's suburbs.
   ``The people are now facing anarchy of the violence-makers,''
said the commander, Sau Maung, in a Radio Rangoon broadcast.
   The state-owned radio said demonstrators were preparing
firebombs and planning to ``escalate'' violent activities. The
radio said the 15 people were killed and 81 wounded in Rangoon
today. That brings the official death count from violence
throughout the country since Tuesday to about 95.
   Government offices, police stations and railway stations also
were destroyed and rice warehouses looted, it said. But the
broadcast said only one large demonstration was held in the Rangoon
area today when 1,000 people rallied in the suburb of North
Okkalapa.
   The radio said three aircraft dropped leaflets when 10,000
people surrounded a military unit in Okkalapa on Wednesday. The
radio said troops would have to open fire if the crowds did not
disperse.
   Diplomats in Rangoon, the capital, said soldiers and several
thousand anti-government demonstrators continued the demonstration
in the suburb today.
   Diplomats said cited unconfirmed reports indicated that at least
two truckloads of troops sided with the residents of North Okkalapa
and that residents erected barricades in the area.
   Reliable reports said people fought fiercely with troops in the
area Wednesday and that residents used weapons that were either
captured or turned over to them by military defectors. The
warplanes reportedly dropped the leaflets that day.
   Burma's official Radio Rangoon said rioters beheaded two
policemen Wednesday in North Okkalapa and that two other people
were killed. It said a third policemen was beheaded in nearby South
Okkalapa.
   The protests against the authoritarian rule of new President
Sein Lwin are the worst since Burma's democracy was overthrown 26
years ago.
   Burmese leaders were believed to have met in an all-night
emergency session to discuss ways to cope with the nationwide
turmoil, Japan's Kyodo News Agency reported today.
   The agency said Buddhist leaders today appealed for calm in a
statement printed on top of the front page of the state-run
English-language newspaper The Guardian.
   Travelers returning from Rangoon say the city of 3.5 million was
barely functioning, with most shops and markets closed, few
government workers reporting to offices and public transportation
almost at a standstill. The city's vital river port had stopped
operating, and some diplomats said they were running short of food.
   The demonstrations are by far the largest since a coup by Ne Win
ended democracy in Burma in 1962. Sein Lwin became president and
head of the government party last month when Ne Win resigned.
   Protesters accuse Sein Lwin of ruthlessly suppressing student
riots in March and June, when he was an army general, and earlier
harsh measures against dissenters.
   The government appears to be sealing itself off from the outside
world and has stopped issuing tourist visas at most of its missions
abroad. The government has tried to keep foreign journalists out
since trouble began after the transfer of power.
   In Washington, the State Department said Wednesday that the U.S.
Embassy was closed temporarily, but some ``essential personnel''
reported for work today. The British, Japanese and French
governments have warned their nationals to avoid traveling to Burma
for the time being.
   Official American personnel and their dependents, 154 people,
are safe at their homes, said State Department spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley.
   Five lawmakers introduced a resolution in the U.S. Senate
condemning the shooting of unarmed demonstrators. It asks that
one-party rule end and urges President Reagan to raise the issue of
human rights abuses with Burmese authorities.
   Chants and placards by demonstrators have called for restoration
of democracy, the overthrow of Sein Lwin and the release of
Brigadier Aung Gyi and other prisoners.
   Aung Gyi, the system's most strident critic, and at least a
dozen other prominent figures were arrested late last month. They
included Associated Press correspondent Sein Win.
   The Foreign Correspondents Club of Thailand today joined several
professional and human rights organizations calling for Sein Win's
release.
</TEXT>
