<HEAD>Greece Signs Barter Deal For 50 Soviet Trolleys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece has signed a $4.1 million barter
deal for 50 Soviet-built trolley buses to update its aging
electric-powered fleet, the Transport Ministry said Thursday.
   According to an agreement signed Wednesday with the Soviet firm
Massinov Export, the first 15 trolleys will be delivered in January
1989 and the remaining 35 by June, a ministry announcement said.
   Each trolley costs $83,050 but most will be paid for in exports
of Greek oranges and other farm products, said a spokesman for
ILPAP, the state-owned Athens trolley bus company.
   The new trolleys will replace some of the 154 Italian-made
trolley buses circulating in Athens since the 1950s.
   The remainder of the 400-trolley fleet consists of Soviet-made
vehicles bought in the 1970s.
</TEXT>
