<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ecuador 1stLd-Writethru a0468 08-11 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecuador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Socialist President Promises Emergency Plan To Fight Economic
Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, ``Attending the...'' to
UPDATE with Ortega-Borja meeting. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``We
have...'' DELETES grafs 17-end to conform.
^By EDUARDO GALLARDO</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist President Rodrigo Borja, sworn
in for a four-year term, accused his archconservative predecessor
of dragging Ecuador into economic disaster and promised an
emergency plan to end the crisis.
   Borja, 53, received the yellow, blue and red presidential sash
from Wilfrido Lucero, president of the National Legislature, during
Wednesday night's inauguration.
   The outgoing president, Leon Febres Cordero, refused to
personally hand over the sash to Borja. In 1984, Borja lost a
bitter runoff to Febres Cordero, who was the Reagan
administration's closest ally in South America.
   Attending the ceremony were seven foreign leaders, including
Cuba's Fidel Castro. The United States was represented by Secretary
of State George P. Shultz, who was booed by some people in the
crowd.
   Borja today met President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua, who could
not come to the inauguration because the outgoing president refused
to let him into the country. Febres Cordero broke diplomatic ties
with Nicaragua in 1985, and Ortega and Borja planned to restore
relations later today.
   Borja, head of Ecuador's Democratic Left Party, has promised a
non-aligned policy and said that one of his first official acts
will be to restore ties with Nicaragua.
   ``We have received a country in moral and economic bankrupcy,''
Borja said during his 2{-hour inaugural speech. The leftist law
professor said the free-market economic system Febres Cordero
encouraged has fueled inflation and impoverished the nation of 10
million.
   ``You don't have to be an economist to know that,'' Borja said.
``It is enough to go to the market, walk along the country roads or
visit shantytowns to feel the daily drama of poor people.''
   He promised an emergency plan to solve the problem, but gave no
details.
   Borja won the presidency in May, defeating populist candidate
Abdala Bucaram. Febres Cordero, who served one term, was not
eligible for re-election.
   In a farewell speech earlier, Febres Cordero defended his
government's efforts to deal with what he called Ecuador's worst
economic crisis. He noted that oil prices, which provide 60 percent
of the nation's hard currency earnings, had recently plunged to $13
a barrel from $27 a barrel in 1984.
   In addition, he said, the economy was severely affected by
earthquakes that crippled the oil industry for six months last year.
   Ecuador's economy, burdened by a $9.2 billion debt, shrank by
3.5 percent in 1987. Less than half the work force has full-time
jobs and inflation is running at an annual rate of 55 percent.
   In an apparent reference to the new president's stated plans to
drop the free-market economy, Shultz told reporters after meeting
with Borja: ``I think that one of the things that is crystal clear
in the world today is that method of running an economy by central
control, as advocated by the left, simply doesn't work.''
   ``The most recent sample right here in this neighborhood is the
example of Nicaragua,'' he said.
   Borja said Ecuador cannot pay its foreign debt under the present
conditions: ``In the friendliest possible manner, I ask from our
creditors a more understanding attitude, as the basis for a lasting
understanding.''
   Ecuador is more than $1 billion in arrears in the service of its
debt.
   Also attending the inauguration were presidents Oscar Arias of
Costa Rica, Jaime Lusinchi of Venezuela, Virgilio Barco of
Colombia, Raul Alfonsin of Argentina, Julio Sanguinetti of Uruguay
and Mario Soares of Portugal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
