<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Armenian     08-11 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Armenian,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Activist's Requests To Return Rebuffed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An expelled Armenian activist's requests to return
to the Soviet Union are not being taken seriously by the
government, a legal official said Thursday.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan was stripped of his Soviet citizenship and
expelled from the country to Soviet-allied Ethiopia on July 21.
   The 39-year-old Armenian activist was arrested in March for his
part in spreading word to Western journalists about the Armenian
people's campaign to have a region of neighboring Azerbaijan
annexed to their republic.
   Pavel A. Laptiev, an aide with the Soviet State
Prosecutor-General's office, appeared at a Foreign Ministry
briefing to discuss the handling of Ayrikyan's case.
   Laptiev contended Ayrikyan had asked during his imprisonment to
be allowed to emigrate to the United States.
   Ayrikyan, however, told reporters in Paris last week that after
his arrest, Soviet authorities gave him the choice of returning to
prison or going to the United States. He said he was expelled
because Soviet officials feared putting him on trial would lead to
more inter-ethnic hostility.
   The U.S. government declined to issue Ayrikyan an immigration
visa on the grounds that he was leaving the Soviet Union against
his will.
   In news conferences in Paris, Rome and Bonn, West Germany,
Ayrikyan has said he would like to return to Armenia. He said he
has applied to the Soviet Embassy in Paris for permission to do so.
   Soviet officials indicate the appeal will be rejected.
   ``His requests to be reinstated cannot be taken seriously,''
Laptiev told reporters.
   Laptiev disputed Western news reports that suggested Ayrikyan
was summarily expelled against his wishes, but conceded the
activist was stripped of Soviet citizenship in the same action that
dropped charges against him.
   Soviet law does not allow emigration if a criminal case is
pending against the applicant, Laptiev said. To clear that
obstacle, preliminary charges that allowed Ayrikyan to be jailed
for more than four months this year were dropped by an order of the
Presidium of the Supreme Soviet.
   Ethnic rioting killed at least 32 people in Azerbaijan after
Armenians launched a campaign in February to annex a part of
Azerbaijan to Armenia.
</TEXT>
