<1ST_LINE>u w PM-AIDEmbezzlement     08-11 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AID Embezzlement,520</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0612 to fix spelling of `AID' and `Forfeit' in
headline</NOTE>
<HEAD>Former AID Employee Pleads Guilty, Agrees To Forfeit Wealth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Agency for International Development
employee pleaded guilty today to embezzling $1.2 million from the
government and agreed to forfeit the proceeds of a lavish lifestyle
resulting from his crime.
   William J. Burns, 48, pleaded guilty to embezzlement, filing
false claims and attempted tax evasion before U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson, who scheduled sentencing for Oct. 11.
   The judge reminded Burns that he could receive up to 20 years
imprisonment and be fined up to $500,000 upon the convictions.
   But under sentencing guidelines implemented last year that take
into account a defendant's past criminal history, Burns would
receive a prison term ranging from 2 1@2 to three years and a
month, according to Justice Department prosecutor James Cole.
   Both sides may withdraw from the plea agreement if the sentence
calculated by the probation department is different from the range
estimated by the prosecution and defense.
   Burns, who was a $35,108-a-year financial manager, admitted that
since 1982 he submitted false claim forms to arrange for the
issuance of travel reimbursement checks to a Vincent Kauffman.
   As a financial officer, Burns could sign the forms to authorize
issuance of the checks.
   The checks were sent to a Washington bank account that Burns set
up under Kauffman's name. Cole told Johnson that all of the
deposits into the account were Treasury checks. Burns withdrew
money by forging checks to himself and signing Kauffman's signature
or using an automatic teller card to get cash.
   The money was used to purchase ``a house, car, furs, trips,
jewels and other personal luxury items for Mr. Burns and his
family,'' Cole said.
   Burns admitted filing two false claim forms in June for more
than $56,000. Burns also pleaded guilty to a charge that he failed
to report any of the money he embezzled as income to avoid paying
taxes on $475,685.
   According to the plea agreement, Burns agreed to surrender his
$300,000 house in Burtonsville, Md., and all the possessions and
property he bought with the money.
   Burns's wife, Kathy, will be allowed to keep a car and $10,000
and necessary household goods ``to get a start in life with her two
children,'' Cole told the judge.
   Burns and his attorney, David Addis, left the U.S. Courthouse
without commenting on the case.
   During the proceeding, Addis said his client ``has demonstrated
his desire to make a bad situation better.''
   Urging Johnson to allow Burns to remain free on $500,000 bond,
Addis argued Burns won't jump bail. ``He has a family, he has two
children, he knows he has injured them terribly. He is not going to
do anything to compound that.''
   The judge allowed Burns to remain free on bond pending
sentencing.
   As part of the plea agreement, Burns and his wife agreed to give
government investigators a full accounting of their assets. Burns
agreed to make up the difference between the money the government
collects from selling his property and the amount he stole from the
government.
   He also faces civil tax penalties, Cole said.
   Burns also agreed to cooperate with a continuing investigation,
Cole said. Investigators determined that there was an unspecified
amount of additional money taken in a related embezzlement scheme,
Cole said.
</TEXT>
