<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CoolingCosts     08-11 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cooling Costs,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Wave Costs Americans $255 Million Extra in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   July's hot weather cost Americans more than a
quarter-billion dollars more than normal in keeping cool, the
government reported Thursday.
   The national air conditioning bill for July was $4.3 billion,
some $255 million more than would have been expected in normal
weather, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
reported.
   That averaged out to a July air conditioning bill of $104 for
the typical home, $6 more than normal.
   Costs varied with the weather from region to region, with only
the west south central states spending less on cooling than in a
typical July.
   Here is a regional rundown of the estimated cost, per household,
of air conditioning in July.
   _West South Central, $131, $4 less than normal. Includes
Louisiana, Texas, Oklahoma and Arkansas.
   _East South Central, $112, $4 more than normal. Includes
Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Alabama.
   _South Atlantic, $112, $5 more than normnal. Includes Maryland,
Delaware, District of Columbia, West Virginia, Virginia, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and Florida.
   _West North Central, $112, $8 more than normal. Includes North
Dakota, South Dakota, Minnesota, Nebraska, Iowa, Kansas and
Missouri.
   _East North Central, $103, $16 more than normal. Includes
Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio.
   _Middle Atlantic, $94, $14 more than normal. Includes New York,
New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   _Mountain, $89, $4 more than normal. Includes Montana, Idaho,
Wyoming, Nevada, Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico.
   _New England, $56, $4 more than normal. Includes Maine, Vermont,
New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island.
   _Pacific, $53, $1 more than normal. Includes Washington, Oregon
and California.
   The monthly study of climate impacts does not include estimates
for Alaska and Hawaii.
</TEXT>
