<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     08-11 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Called Cleanest Ever After Test Firing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An examination of space shuttle
Discovery a day after its test firing turned up no problems to
stand in the way of getting the shuttle ready for flight, NASA said
Thursday.
   ``This vehicle is the cleanest we've ever had after a
flight-readiness firing,'' said Lisa Malone, a spokeswoman for
NASA's Kennedy Space Center. ``We haven't turned up anything
unusual.''
   The successful firing of the three huge engines was a spirit
lifter for space workers here who have had to overcome one problem
after another since Discovery was transported to the launch pad
July 4.
   Miss Malone said officials of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration will not set a launch date until a repair unrelated
to the hot-fire test of the engines is completed.
   That repair, which involves cutting a hole in the Discovery's
bulkhead to gain access to pipe connection that is leaking gas, is
scheduled to begin Wednesday and will take about six days. The leak
is in the system used to steer Discovery in space.
   NASA has one other milestone to meet before setting a date for
the first flight since Challenger exploded in January 1986. That is
a test, scheduled for Aug. 18, of a shuttle booster rocket at the
manufacturing plant in Utah. The test is the fifth in a series of
the booster, which was heavily redesigned after Challenger.
   A faulty joint in Challenger's right booster allowed flames to
escape and triggered the destruction of the shuttle. The joint and
other booster systems have been thoroughly redesigned.
   The rocket will be deliberately flawed, with grooves, cuts and
debondings introduced in critical areas like insulation and O-ring
seals.
   ``It is a significant flaw demonstration test,'' said Robert
Crippen, deputy director of shuttle operations. ``Some say there is
a risk in it, but we have to test the booster to withstand these
worst-case situations.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
