<2ND_LINE>AM-Crayfish,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Crayfish Season Opens, with Some American Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedes opened their annual crayfish
season Thursday with much singing and slurping, but the national
holiday had to be helped with imports from China and Louisiana.
   Sweden's crayfish stocks were decimated by a bacterial plague
beginning in the 1960s. Since then this country of 8.4 million
people has become one of the world's biggest importers of the
shellfish, with about 1,800 tons a year.
   The price of the scarce Swedish crayfish hit about $61 for two
pounds, but American imports were readily available at $15 bargains.
   U.S. imports of 1,000 tons this year ended Turkey's previous
dominanation of the market.
   Technically, Thursday is the opening of the fishing season for
the freshwater crustaceans. But traditionally, no one eats even the
imported varieties until Aug. 11.
   The crayfish are boiled in dill and smothered in tradition.
Swedes eat them wearing party hats and bibs. Time-honored rules say
each claw should be downed with a glass of schnapps.
   With an influx of imports from new countries, Swedish newspapers
held gourmet tests to evaluate this year's crop. Judges were
Swedish celebrities, actors or famous chefs.
   Svenska Dagbladet proclaimed an American West Coast variety
named ``California Sunshine'' as the best. ``Fresh and tasty'' with
``beautiful coloring,'' the paper judged. The Chinese jumbo Prino
``looked great but tasted disgusting,'' it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
