<HEAD>Youth Who Pledged To Turn His Life Around Is Wanted In Slaying</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adolph cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adolph Hitler Clark, a 17-year-old who
said he wanted to turn his life around after years of problems
because of his name, is wanted in a fatal shooting over crack
cocaine.
   Police said Thursday that Clark, a high school dropout, is named
in a warrant for the Aug. 2 shooting death of Terry Lamar Combs, 35.
   Combs was shot after he drove up to several men who offered to
sell him crack, police said. Detective Frank Japour said Combs was
shot with an ``Uzi-type weapon'' after trying to haggle with one of
the dealers.
   Witnesses identified Clark as the man who fired the gun, Japour
said. He was being sought Thursday, police said.
   In an interview with The Florida Times-Union last year, Clark
said he had developed a poor self-image because of his name and
thought that crime was expected of him.
   He was named Adolph after an uncle and his father followed that
by Hitler, saying later that he thought it ``would be good for a
middle name,'' Clark said.
   The first name of the German dictator was spelled Adolf.
   Clark said he was teased for years by other children and finally
became involved in a series of crimes.
   By age 16, Clark had been in and out of police custody for eight
years in juvenile cases and was brought into court to face trial as
an adult on an auto theft charge.
   In a letter to a judge last year, Clark said he was led into
crime by poorly chosen friends and promised to reform.
   ``I know I can live a righteous life. I just need a chance to
prove it,'' he wrote from the Montgomery Correctional Center.
   But instead, Japour said, Clark has ``graduated through the
ranks. Now, he stands accused of murder.''
</TEXT>
