<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WyomingSenate 1stLd-Writethru a0636 08-11 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyoming Senate, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wallop Says He's Not Worried By Any Democratic Resurgence in the
West</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `If Dukakis ...,' to CORRECT that Wallop
faces minimal opposition in Republican primary.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ANGELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Malcolm Wallop says he's not
worried a Democratic resurgence in the West being forecast by some
pollsters will sweep him from office in November.
   Wyoming voters, he says, have too much to lose by a presidential
victory by Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis to turn to the
Democrats. Besides, he adds, he's done a good job in his two terms
in the Senate.
   The three Democrats vying in Tuesday's primary for the chance to
run against Wallop, however, point to findings indicating their
party is the strongest it's been in the West since 1964. And they
say Wallop has ignored Wyoming concerns and is out of step even
with his own party _ for instance, his vote against ratification of
the Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty.
   In a report last week, Andrew Kohut, head of The Gallup
Organization, said polls conducted for the Times Mirror Co. show
that the traditionally conservative outlook of westerners appears
to have changed.
   ``Traditionally anti-government voters in the Rocky Mountains
are now calling for more government action on social issues than is
the average American voter.''
   And, he said, Western voters are dissatisfied with the general
course of the nation and have not found in Vice President George
Bush the anti-establishment leader they once saw in Ronald Reagan.
   This is good news for the three Democratic hopefuls.
   ``Reagan is personally popular in parts of Wyoming, but his
policies and the results of those policies are not and people are
ready for a change,'' said state Sen. John Vinich, a 14-year
veteran of the Legislature who announced for Wallop's seat last
fall. ``People are looking to the Democratic Party for that change,
and of course, Wyoming presently has a full congressional
delegation of the minority party back there.''
   The state's other senator, Alan Simpson, has been mentioned as a
possible running mate for George Bush. Wyoming's lone congressman
is Dick Cheney.
   In the primary, Vinich faces Lynn Simons, in her third term as
state schools superintendent, and Pete Maxfield, a University of
Wyoming professor trying to repeat the success of Democrat Gale
McGee, another professor who served 18 years in the Senate.
   Maxfield, who like McGee 30 years ago is making his first
venture into politics, also believes the Reagan administration has
lost its Teflon coating.
   ``I have family members who voted for Reagan, but would not vote
for Bush because of their concerns about the deficit and the
increase in the (national) debt,'' said Maxfield, a tax law expert.
   Simons, however, is not as certain that the presidential race
will have a strong impact on the Senate contest.
   ``I think that it would be an advantage to have a strong
Democratic ticket from the top down in Wyoming,'' she said. ``I
also believe that Wyoming voters are very independent voters, and
there may or may not be a `coattails' effect.''
   Wallop, through it all, is sticking to his conservative guns.
   If Dukakis is going to win the West in November, he'll have to
change his views, said the senator, who faces only minimal
opposition for his party's Senate nomination.
   ``Dukakis stands for nothing but increased federal control,
decreased multiple use (of wildlands) and an increase in the
withdrawal of state's rights to control their resources,'' Wallop
said. ``These are all critical Wyoming issues.''
   Taking issue with the Democrats' claims that he ignored state
concerns while focusing on national and international affairs, he
said: ``My experience is of no use if my performance with that
experience hasn't been good. I say it has been good for jobs,
agriculture, education, the recreation industry and taxpayers. It
has been good for the state.''
</TEXT>
