<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Oilfield Flood,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Largest Oilfield Submerged by Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty days of uninterrupted rain have put 40
percent of the oil wells in China's largest oil producing area
under water, authorities said Thursday.
   The Daqing Oilfield in northeast China has been submerged under
up to 32 inches of water, according to the Central Flood
Headquarters.
   The official Xinhua News Agency reported that the flooding has
reduced petroleum output by 952,000 barrels.
   Last year, Daqing pumped 388.85 million barrels of oil, 50
percent of China's total, Xinhua said.
   It also said 9,000 homes in the area have been flooded, and
1,200 are on the verge of collapse.
   Rainstorms, typhoons and floods have killed nearly 1,000 people
in areas of southern, coastal and northeastern China since the
spring.
</TEXT>
