<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Doctors     08-11 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Doctors,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Stage Day-long Strike Over Pay, Patient Backlog</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7,000 doctors walked off the job at
Israel's state-run hospitals Thursday to protest a stalemate in
talks on pay and a government plan to deal with a backlog of
patients who need operations.
   The day-long strike prompted some health officials to demand
reform of Israel's public health system, which has been crippled in
recent years by job actions by nurses and emergency medical workers
as well as the physicians.
   Israel's state-run medical system provides free service to all
members of health plans. All doctors in state-run hospitals
participated in the strike. Israel has 9,000 physicians.
   Finance Minister Moshe Nissim condemned the striking doctors and
said the government had ``reached the limit'' on what it could give.
   ``I think there also must be a limit to how much doctors can
torture their patients,'' he said on Israel radio.
   Rubi Steinberg, a spokesman for the doctors' union, said
physicians were demanding pay increases of up to 30 percent and an
improvement in a proposed government program to give hospitals
enough funds to operate on 15,000 patients in the next nine months.
   The doctors want the program to last longer and encompass about
45,000 patients they estimate are awaiting major operations as well
as an estimated 60,000 people on the waiting list for minor surgery
and treatment.
   Currently, Steinberg said, a doctor with a 10-year tenure earns
$1,000 to $1,100 a month, not counting night and emergency stand-by
duties, and a beginner's basic salary may be as low as $500 a month.
   ``We're protesting against the stalemate in negotiations. Every
proposal we raise is rejected,'' he said.
   Some health officials said Israel's medical system urgently
needs to be reformed. They cited frequent strikes by hospital
maintenance staff, nurses, emergency medical service workers and
the doctors.
   In 1983, doctors walked off their jobs for most of four months,
staged a hunger strike to protest working conditions and
established temporary private clinics.
   ``The system has not functioned for years and continues to
deteriorate,'' Steinberg said. ``Doctors have not gotten proper
salaries. Many have decided to change their profession or
emigrate.''
   Prof. Charles Greenblatt of the Hebrew University's medical
school blamed ``poor morale, the lack of a financial basis, and
continuous confrontations that are not settled by negotiations.''
   ``There's something wrong with the whole system,'' he said. ``It
is not patient-oriented.''
   Greenblatt suggested reforming the system by establishing
smaller regional hospitals and ending free medical care.
</TEXT>
