<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeavyFish     08-11 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Heavy Fish,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced In Rigging Prize-Winning Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unemployed beer salesman who tried to
snare a fishing contest's $105,000 prize by placing lead weights in
a bass instead tipped the scales of justice against him.
   David Scott Lynd, 25, received two years' probation Wednesday in
an attempted felony theft charge that was filed when lead weights
were discovered in his prize catch during the KYKX Big Bass Classic
fishing tournament at Lake 'O The Pines in May.
   State District Judge Bill Porter said the sentence was the
lightest that could be assessed for the heavy fish. Texas law
provides a maximum of two to 10 years in prison and a fine of up to
$5,000 for attempted felony theft.
   Lynd denied placing the weights in his bass and also denied
buying them at a Garland store, although game wardens found an
itemized cash register receipt detailing the purchase in Lynd's
fishing boat after he was arrested.
   Lynd's attorney, Jerry Biesel, told jurors Lynd would not have
placed the weights in the fish because he knew tournament judges
would cut it open for inspection.
   ``He is no rocket scientist,'' Biesel told jurors, ``but he
isn't crazy.''
   Lynd, of Garland, showed no emotion after the verdict and
sentence were handed down. He later referred all questions to
Biesel.
   Biesel also declined comment, but Marion County Attorney Marion
Hileman said after the two-day trial he was disappointed with the
sentence.
   Mike Gatons, KYKX vice president and general manager, said he
was ``very satisfied with the jury verdict'' and that it showed the
radio station, which hosts the bass tournament at Lake 'O The Pines
each spring, is committed to holding a ``good and clean
tournament.''
   Lynd's fish weighed 7.64 pounds, leading the 6,000-plus field of
contestants before being disallowed by tournament officials. A
7.43-pounder then took the prize.
</TEXT>
