<HEAD>Government Plans to Release Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Ministry said Thursday it
will release more than 20 political prisoners around Aug. 15
marking the anniversary of the liberation of the Korean peninsula
from Japan.
   Ministry officials said the political prisoners would be
released on parole along with 1,400 other non-political criminals.
   On June, the government of President Roh Tae-woo released 46
political prisoners on parole, including Kim Keun-tae, who received
the Robert F. Kennedy Award for Human Rights.
   Roh has released hundreds of political prisoners since June 29,
1987, when nationwide protests forced the government to accept
demands for democratic reforms.
   Opposition groups maintain there are more than 500 disidents
imprisoned for political beliefs or anti-govenment activity, with
many of them still on trial.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea after its liberation in 1945 from Japan's
36-year-old occupation.
