<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bigfoot can relax for now; Grover Krantz
has been grounded.
   The Washington State University anthropology professor said
Wednesday that he doubts he'll be able to get his ultra-light
helicopter running in time to search for the fabled Sasquatch
before he has to return to the classroom.
   Last spring, Krantz announced plans to use the helicopter and
heat-seeking infrared devices to search for the hairy, man-like
beast in the Blue Mountains east of Walla Walla.
   But he's been unable to figure out how to get the throttle of
the helicopter he built from a kit to operate properly.
   Because the fall term is approaching and he has to get back to
the classroom, Krantz said it probably will be spring before the
search begins in earnest.
   Krantz conducts the search for Bigfoot on his own time and
without any financial support from the university.
   The expert on human evolution said he searches for evidence of
Bigfoot because he can neither prove nor disprove the existence of
the creature.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cat napping in the wheel well of a
small plane became a flying feline when the craft took off on a
45-mile flight.
   ``At least she was intelligent enough to wait until the engines
stopped. ... Then she deplaned and stepped down,'' said Alton
Hilton, president of Daytona Beach Regional Airport.
   The cat, Patricia, had napped in the plane's front wheel well
before, said Allison Barksdale, whose father owns a small grass
airfield near Orlando. But no one told the cat that a pilot planned
to fly the plane Wednesday.
   When it took off, the cat either hung on or jumped into a nook
as the plane reached 2,500 feet and a speed of more than 125 mph,
Miss Barksdale said. The Cessna 310 landed without incident.
   ``I can't say that we've ever had any hitchiking cats come
through before,'' Hilton.
   ``Just think of the ride that thing had!'' said airport employee
Manuel San Jose.
</TEXT>
