<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Nazi     08-11 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Nazi,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Nazi Camp Guard Wants To Return To Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Nazi SS concentration
camp guard sentenced to death in Czechoslovakia wants to return to
Italy, which expelled him this week, a prosecutor said Thursday.
   Prosecutor Klaus Schacht also said Anton Maloth was hospitalized
near Munich, delaying interrogation for at least three weeks
because of a serious illness that Schacht refused to specify.
   Czechoslovakia sentenced Maloth, 76, to death in absentia in
1948 for war crimes at the Theresienstadt concentration camp, and
it asked Italy on Tuesday to extradite him.
   Italian officials put Maloth on an airplane from Verona to
Munich on Wednesday, after his arrest last week at his wife's home
in the northern Italian town of Merano.
   Italy and Czechoslovakia have no extradition treaty, and Italian
law bars extraditing someone facing the death penalty. Italy does
not have capital punishment.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Peter Rothen said officials
determined Maloth is a West German citizen and cannot be extradited
under its constitution.
   Schacht, who is leading the inquiry into Maloth's past, said he
has no plans to bring criminal charges against the former
concentration camp guard. West German officials say Maloth is free
to move about as he pleases.
   At a news conference Thursday in Dortmund, Schacht said: ``He
wants to stay temporarily in Munich and apply for a West German
passport. Then he wants to return to Merano legally.''
   Asked whether Maloth could face interrogation after that, the
prosecutor said: ``The attending physician has already expressed
his doubts. At this point, he is not able to take care of himself.''
   The director of the national memorial in the town where the Nazi
camp was located told the Czechoslovak Communist Party daily
newspaper Rude Pravo that 2,400 documents provide evidence of
Maloth's crimes.
   The CTK news agency, which carried excerpts of the interview,
quoted Vaclav Novak as saying the crimes included ``grievous bodily
harms, killings and murders.''
   Maloth ``voluntarily and with pleasure asked to be a member of
execution squads,'' Novak told Rude Pravo.
   CTK quoted Novak as saying ``several dozen'' witnesses to
Maloth's crimes are still alive.
   Maloth was arrested at his wife's home in Merano in northern
Italy last week. Vienna-based Nazi hunter Simon Wiesenthal said
Maloth had been hiding with his family in Italy for 15 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
