<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ToyGuns     08-11 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Guns,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Members Consider Ban on Toy Guns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel on Thursday considered federal
regulations on deadly looking toy guns that police sometimes
mistake for the real thing.
   An outright ban on the toys, among the topics of a House
hearing, is opposed by toy manufacturers, whose products often are
exact replicas of machine guns and assault rifles.
   The $300 million-a-year industry supports a measure requiring
them to identify their harmless products with bright orange
markings.
   But ban supporters say that bits of tape or paint aren't enough
to assure police officers that they aren't staring down the barrel
of a real threat.
   The hearing by the House Energy and Commerce subcommittee on
consumer protection was chaired by Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., who
showed what appeared to be an Israeli-made Uzi machine gun. ``Is it
real, or is it a toy?'' Florio asked the audience.
   It was a water pistol. But Florio also showed an actual Uzi, and
the two were all but identical.
   Florio and police experts showed several examples of actual
firearms and obvious toy knock-offs, including replicas of a MAC-10
machine pistol and a .45-caliber pistol.
   The hearing came four days after an incident in Woodbridge,
N.J., in which a police officer was wounded trying to apprehend a
man armed with a real-looking toy pistol.
   Patrolman William McSweeney was wounded in the leg by another
policeman's gun that discharged in a struggle with a suspect. The
suspect's weapon turned out to be a replica of a .45 automatic.
   Two bills are pending in Congress to regulate such
``look-alike'' guns.
   One, sponsored by Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., would require tne
orange markings. The other, offered by Rep. Mel Levine, D-Calif.,
calls for an outright ban on any toy gun resembling a real weapon.
   Levine said his legislation ``is meant to make child's play
safer than it is. It is not meant to ban all toy guns, just those
that are highly realistic.''
   Nationally syndicated television consumer advocate David
Horowitz testified that New York City police last year confiscated
more than 1,400 toy guns used in crimes.
   Horowitz himself was held hostage during a live TV broadcast
last year by a man holding what later turned out to be a fake gun.
   ``I could see the gun, and so could my colleagues on the set,
and there was no doubt in any of our minds that it was the real
thing,'' he said.
   Horowitz said toy manufacturers refuse to stop selling
look-alike guns, because they sell better than unrealistic plastic
weapons.
   Toy manufacturers supported Dole's bill, calling for the orange
markings, but said the Levine measure was too harsh.
   They said a ban on toy guns would cost jobs in the toy industry,
although guns represent less than 1 percent of the overall dollar
value of toy sales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
