<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Chateau     08-11 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Chateau,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chateau's Historic But Leaky Roof to Be Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOIRY, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a castle built for the
finance minister of King Francis II are selling slate tiles from
its historic but leaky roof to raise money for badly needed
renovations.
   Vicountess Annabelle de la Panouse, a native of Waysata, Minn.,
ordered workers to remove 67,000 gray slate tiles one-by-one and
save those in the best condition. They were installed on the
chateau of Thoiry, now a tourist attraction, 125 years ago during
the reign of Napoleon III.
   The vicountess said renovation of the 60-room chateau was being
delayed by lack of funds for roof repair, which will cost about $1
million.
   ``Some rooms I started but had to stop because it was raining on
the paint work,'' she said.
   As with many other French historical sites maintained by private
families without government funds, the chateau's owners seek ways
to exploit its picturesque country setting and long history to
increase revenue.
   It has an African animal preserve with more than 1,200 animals,
and another generator of revenue is an outdoor concert series on
the grounds.
   Roof tiles will be sold in the chateau gift shop with
certificates of authenticity. In addition to helping restore the
chateau, those buying the tiles will have something with practical
use, Madame de la Panouse said.
   ``You can buy some colored chalk and make your shopping list on
the slate, which comes in all different sizes and shapes,'' she
said. ``It is certainly more elegant than using a scrap of paper or
the back of an envelope.''
   Archives and collections exhibited on the ground floor include
reports of the national treasury, letters from Louis XIV and the
pitcher and wash basin in Sevres porcelain used by Marie-Antoinette
while awaiting the guillotine in Conciergerie Prison.
   Also on display are one of two waltz scores by Frederick Chopin
given to Clemence de la Panouse, a 19th century arts patron.
   The chateau was built in 1564 for Raoul Moreau, who served as
finance minister for Francis II and his successors Charles IX and
Henry III. It passed among family members through 14 generations
and 400 years to Madame de la Panouse's husband, Paul.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
