<DOCNO> AP880811-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DefenseSpending 5thLd-Writethru a0676 08-11 0973</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Spending, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0676,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Defense Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Transposes 5th and 6th grafs to fix transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate today approved 90-4 a Pentagon
budget bill that includes restrictions on spending for American
troops overseas as a message to U.S. allies to do more for allied
defense, and new restrictions on Pentagon consultants.
   It was the second attempt by the Senate to approve a defense
bill President Reagan will accept. Reagan vetoed the first measure
last week because of cuts in his Star Wars budget along with arms
control restrictions he opposed.
   The new version retains the same Star Wars reductions, but none
of the arms control limitations. It will now go to a House-Senate
conference committee to resolve differences between the two
chambers' versions.
   The vote was the last major item on the Senate agenda before a
summer recess for next week's Republican presidential convention.
   Voting against the bill were Sens. Kent Conrad, D-N.D.; Mark
Hatfield, R-Ore.; Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.; and William Proxmire,
D-Wis. Not voting were Sens. Joseph Biden, D-Del.; Thad Cochran,
R-Miss.; Bob Kasten, R-Wis.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; Lowell
Weicker, R-Conn.; and James Exon, D-Neb.
   Earlier today, the Senate gave voice vote approval to a
``burden-sharing'' proposal backed by Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga.,
chairman of the Armed Services Committee.
   The plan orders a major review by the Pentagon of U.S. overseas
commitments, a new cap on U.S. troop deployments to Japan and South
Korea, and a new ceiling on spending for U.S. military personnel
stationed overseas. U.S. allies would have to pay for the American
troops if the costs rise above the 1988 levels.
   But before adopting the amendment, the Senate voted 59-36 to
eliminate a provision for a 10 percent reduction in the total of
American dependents stationed overseas with servicemen.
   ``I can't think of anything more damaging to the morale of our
troops than to limit dependents,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
an opponent of the limit.
   But Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., said, ``enough is enough. We
have 413,000 dependents worldwide. That is far more than any other
nation in history.''
   There has been an increasingly loud chorus of election-year
congressional calls for more defense help, particularly from Japan
and European members of the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   ``Despite the shift in economic fortunes'' since World War II,
``the United States bears a disproportionate share of the cost of
the common defense,'' Nunn said Wednesday.
   ``Someplace, sometime, we have to draw the line,'' said Nunn.
``I hope this will stimulate a more equitable burden-sharing.''
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, agreed: ``There's a limit to the
pocketbooks of the taxpayers of the United States.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said, ``There have
been legitimate complaints in the United States that we are bearing
a disproportionately large burden in NATO today.''
   Later, the chamber gave voice vote endorsement to an amendment
by Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., which would require defense
consultants to register and list all their clients.
   Pryor's amendment arises in the wake of the ongoing Pentagon
bribery investigation, which involves allegations that consultants
paid Defense Department officials for inside information about
future contracts. No charges have yet been filed.
   ``How bad do we want this system to get before we finally pay
some attention to it?'' Pryor asked.
   Earlier Wednesday, the Senate voted to add a Pentagon spending
plan praised by Reagan to its latest defense budget effort.
   In addition, the chamber, with all Republicans voting ``no,''
voted 49-47 approval of a Democratic-backed plan to provide $27
million in humanitarian aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels after Oct.
1. The vote could mean a possible second vote in Congress this fall
on releasing $16.3 million in stockpiled weapons to the Contras,
who oppose Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government.
   Last week, Reagan vetoed the bill which authorizes the Pentagon
budget for the fiscal year starting Oct. 1. He specifically
objected to cuts in his proposed Star Wars budget and
Democratic-backed restrictions on arms control policies.
   The authorization measure is the first step of the two-track
congressional budget process, which also includes an appropriation
bill to pay for the programs authorized in the earlier legislation.
   The bill now under consideration is the Pentagon appropriation
bill. As it worked on the measure late Wednesday, the Senate voted
90-2 approval of an amendment which, in essence, added the earlier
Senate version of the authorization bill.
   When the Senate is finished, the entire matter will go to a
House-Senate conference committee to work out differences between
the bill and the companion measure passed two months ago by the
House.
   The Senate appropriation bill includes $4 billion for the
Strategic Defense Initiative, as Star Wars is formally known. But
the Senate version of the authorization bill provides $4.6 billion.
   The latter figure is closer to Reagan's original request of $4.8
billion for SDI, which receives $3.9 billion in the current fiscal
year.
   In addition, the Senate version does not have any of the arms
control restrictions Reagan opposes.
   The vote was part of a complicated legislative tactic to work
out a defense spending compromise that Reagan will approve, Nunn
told his colleagues.
   ``Tonight, we begin the process of putting Humpty Dumpty back
together again,'' Nunn told his colleagues. ``This may be mission
impossible, but I'm going to try.''
   Reagan vetoed the defense bill despite the advice of Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and national security adviser Colin
Powell, who both said it should be signed. They were involved in
earlier negotiations with congressional leaders over the
legislation.
   ``We need to have the executive branch sort out whom the
Congress should work with on national security issues,'' said Nunn.
``We have to know who's speaking for the administration. Can we
deal with the secretary of defense, can we deal with the national
security adviser?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
