<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FinancialFlight 1stLd-Writethru a0645 08-11 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Financial Flight, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financial Planner Flees; $25 Million in Clients' Money Unaccounted
For</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf with 1 graf to CORRECT waiter to waitress and
clarify that Gherman did not make $1 million by selling $1 million
in insurance.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financial planner who managed investments for
about 50 doctors has skipped town, leaving a note of apology and
$25 million of his clients' money unaccounted for.
   Henry Gherman, 51, handled pension funds, personal investments
and managed medical offices for South Florida clients who received
copies of a handwritten letter of apology in the mail Wednesday.
   ``By the time you receive this letter, I will be gone,'' the
letters said. ``I have run away.''
   Gherman fled the Miami area Monday and sources close to the case
believe he may have left the country.
   FBI spokesman Paul Miller said Gherman and his companies are
under investigation for possible wire fraud, bank fraud,
embezzlement and interstate transportation of stolen property.
   ``I have taken this action because I am unable to face the
humiliation, disgrace and consequences'' that would follow once his
company, Financial & Investment Planning Inc., collapsed, the notes
said. He addded that he would try to return the doctors' money.
   ``(I) have been unable to come up with any solution other than
running,'' he wrote. ``I am truly sorry.''
   A Dade Circuit judge on Wednesday granted a request by 12 of
Gherman's clients to appoint a receiver to oversee the finances of
Gherman, his family and his companies.
   ``All we know is that Henry Gherman is not here and a large
amount of money is not here,'' said Jay Solowsky, attorney for the
doctors.
   The doctors also filed a $25 million lawsuit accusing Gherman of
fraudulently shifting clients' money to his wife and two children.
   Solowsky said Gherman accepted money from clients to invest in
certificates of deposit but that banks had no record of CDs being
purchased. Gherman also accepted money to buy medical malpractice
insurance for his clients but failed to pay premiums, Solowsky said.
   Gherman is neither a lawyer nor an accountant and his companies
are not registered with the state as an investment adviser,
Solowsky said.
   Gherman, the son of a waitress, was hailed as a financial whiz
kid when he sold $1 million worth of insurance in one year for the
John Hancock Co., and his investment savvy made him a millionaire
before he was 30. But his financial troubles began in July 1969,
when Gherman, then 34, filed for personal bankruptcy, listing $1
million in unpaid bills for casinos, hotel rooms, credit card
purchases, clothes and flowers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
