<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MrsCuomo'sBrother     08-11 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mrs Cuomo's Brother,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Brother-In-Law Got State Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo's wife encouraged New
York's health commissioner to award a $113,000 research contract to
a California university that later paid $73,000 of that to her
brother, state officials said Thursday.
   Matilda Cuomo's brother, Joseph Raffa of San Diego, exchanged
the research money for a $48,000-a-year job with a California
company that he later unsuccessfully recommended be hired by New
York state to continue the cancer registry research work he had
begun, the newspaper Newsday reported.
   The contract, with the University of California at San
Francisco, was designed to study how New York might benefit from a
computerized and regionalized cancer registry system being
developed in California, said Frances Tarlton, a spokeswoman for
New York state Health Commissioner Dr. David Axelrod.
   Cancer registries are used by researchers to track where cancer
cases are occurring.
   Cuomo, in a statement issued by his office, defended his wife as
someone who ``has voluntarily contributed extraordinary amounts of
her time and energy ... to improving health care and education in
New York.''
   ``Any suggestion that she would do anything for any reason other
than to help the people of this state, would be both inaccurate and
terribly unfair,'' Cuomo said, noting that his wife and her brother
``have been active volunteers in the fight against cancer for many
years.''
   The 18-month study that ended last summer was arranged for Raffa
by Axelrod and former New York state Thruway Executive Director
Alexander Levine, who a state investigation panel has recommended
face criminal prosecution on an unrelated matter.
   Raffa, contacted Thursday morning at his California home by The
Associated Press, defended the research project and said he did it
out of a desire to help people, not to make money.
   ``I'm trying to do a good thing for humanity and I get kicked in
the behind for it,'' Raffa said. ``She (Mrs. Cuomo) never twisted
anybody's arm. First of all, she's not dumb enough to do that and
Axelrod is too smart. If he didn't believe in the project, he
wouldn't have done it.''
   Axelrod, through Tarlton, said he hadn't been pressured to enter
into the contract. Levine refused to be interviewed for the Newsday
story.
   The Long Island newspaper said Raffa had no experience in public
health statistics work, but he did have computer expertise before
taking on the cancer registry research work.
   A specialist in cancer registries and head of New Mexico's tumor
registry program, Dr. Mary Lerchen, reviewed Raffa's work for
Newsday and said ``the information gathered by the author was
neither comprehensive nor documented.''
   Axelrod said, however, he was satisfied with the study and that
New York ``learned a great deal about the cancer registry, its
potential, its problems.''
   Tarlton said some of Raffa's recommendations were implemented
while others were not because of their high cost. She said the
university subcontracted for the research work with Raffa and
that's how he got the $73,000.
   Levine, a long-time aide to Cuomo, resigned his highway post
last year after it was revealed that he had established a computer
software business, headed by his daughter and other Levine
associates, that engineering companies seeking to do business with
the Thruway were encouraged to use. The State Investigation
Commission has recommended that Levine be prosecuted for extortion,
a recommendation federal authorities are considering.
</TEXT>
