<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NuclearTesting     08-11 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Testing,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear Test Should Help Treaties Advance, U.S. Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. arms control officials said
Thursday that a U.S.-Soviet nuclear test experiment next week in
Nevada would be a major step toward finalizing long-stalled
treaties on limiting nuclear explosions.
   Soviet scientists will for the first time on Aug. 17 monitor a
U.S. underground nuclear blast at the Nevada Test Site as part of
efforts to assess techniques for verifying the treaties signed in
the mid-1970s.
   On Sept. 14, U.S. scientists will observe a nuclear explosion at
the Soviet testing ground near Semipalatinsk.
   ``We believe there have been likely violations by the Soviet
Union of these treaties in the past ... The problem is inadequate
verification,'' said Paul Robinson, chief U.S. negotiator at the
nuclear testing talks in Geneva.
   ``I believe that the confidence building of achieving effective
verification is going to break the roadblock between us ... and be
a very significant step in allowing us to move forward,'' he told
reporters in a U.S. government-sponsored satellite broadcast from
Washington to five European cities.
   The 1974 Threshold Test Ban Treaty and the 1976 Peaceful Nuclear
Explosions Treaty prohibit nuclear blasts with a yield of more than
150,000 tons of TNT.
   Neither treaty has been ratified because of problems over
verification.
   During the verification tests, the United States will use a
system known by the acronym CORRTEX to measure the yields of the
blasts. CORRTEX, which stands for continuous reflectrometry for
radius versus time experiment, determines the yield of a nuclear
explosion by measuring the shock wave from the blast.
   ``If the Soviets will agree to the use of this type of
measurement, we feel confident that these two treaties will be
effectively verifiable and we will be prepared to submit them to
the Senate for ratification,'' said Victor E. Alessi, director of
the Energy Department's Office of Arms Control.
   ``We are confident the test will demonstrate the effectiveness
of CORRTEX and ... that there will be no further need for tests,''
he said.
   Alessi said the cost of the project, agreed to in December at
the U.S.-Soviet summit in Washington, was $25 million.
   The project, he said, ``involves for the first time sending
large numbers of United States scientists to a distant and remote
part of the Soviet Union.''
   Robinson said 45 Soviet scientists were at the Nevada Test Site
and the United States would have a similar number monitoring the
Soviet explosion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0661 08-11 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks Tough On Defense, Denounces Pentagon Waste</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 3 grafs after 4th graf bgn: The Democratic ... to
UPDATE with Dukakis firing rifle on target range, commenting on
prime rate increase. Picks up 5th graf pvs bgng: In the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, countering George Bush's
assertion that a Dukakis presidency would weaken the country,
portrayed himself Thursday as a tough-minded leader who would
strengthen conventional forces and weed out Pentagon waste.
   ``We've got to put our defense dollars where our defense needs
are greatest,'' Dukakis said in a speech at New York University
before heading to New Jersey to tour the Army base at Fort Dix.
   ``We've got to use those dollars to buy weapons that work,'' he
said. ``And we've got to to manage those dollars to strengthen our
military forces, not to line the pockets of dishonest contractors
and wheeler-dealer consultants.''
   The Democratic nominee, on a two-day campaign trip to five
states, spent eight weeks at Fort Dix in 1955 _ receiving basic
training after joining the Army. From Fort Dix, Dukakis was
traveling to Connecticut for several receptions. He campaigns in
Virginia and Florida on Friday.
   During his tour of Fort Dix, Dukakis fired a rifle on the target
range. ``It was fun to be out there,'' he told reporters later at
the base gates.
   Dukakis also toured a C-141 transport plane and a tank training
area. He told reporters he thought it was a mistake that the Reagan
administration is cutting by the number of Army tanks it will buy
in the next five years. That ``deprives our soldiers of the
equipment we need and drives up the cost of each tank by 30
percent,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked by reporters for his reaction to the increase in the prime
lending rate by major U.S. banks, Dukakis replied, ``I think it's
very regrettable. I think it's what happens after eight years of
borrowing and spending, borrowing and spending.''
   In the audience for the NYU speech was New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo, Mayor Ed Koch, local leaders of Jesse Jackson's presidential
campaign and Dukakis advisers on defense and foreign policy
matters, including former Defense Secretary Harold Brown.
   The always-controversial Koch yawned throughout Dukakis' speech.
Afterward, Koch said he supported Dukakis but would appreciate some
encouragement from the Dukakis campaign.
   ``I will go where they will ask me to go; I won't go where they
don't want me to go,'' Koch said.
   Cuomo, who introduced Dukakis, said Bush's only responsibility
during the Reagan years has been to head the administration's
anti-drug efforts.
   ``And we are losing that war,'' Cuomo said. ``This country and
this world cannot afford second-rate leadership in these critical
times.''
   Dukakis sounded a similar theme in his speech, although he did
not refer by name to Bush, who has portrayed the Democratic nominee
as weak on foreign policy and defense issues.
   ``This November, we Americans face a fundamental choice,''
Dukakis said. ``We can seize the opportunity to restore America's
leadership in the world, or we can settle for second best.''
   Referring to Reagan administration anti-drug efforts, Dukakis
said he would be a president who ``believes that we don't need more
rhetoric or photo opportunities in the war against drugs; we need
results.''
   Dukakis aides had billed the speech as a major address on
foreign policy and national security, but the Massachusetts
governor unveiled no new positions on either front. On Thursday,
the aides said the speech was a ``framework'' of Dukakis' positions
that he wanted to give before the Republican National Convention
and that the governor would be more specific about his ideas in the
next few weeks.
   Dukakis repeated his desire to continue Reagan's progress on
nuclear arms reductions with the Soviet Union but lambasted the
president's ``Star Wars' space-based missile defense program as
unnecessary and too expensive.
   Dukakis promised to beef up conventional forces with new tanks,
equipment and supplies and said the military should be considered
for use in anti-drug and anti-terrorism efforts.
   He also recalled the words of John F. Kennedy to emphasize his
belief that United States' international strength depends on a
strong domestic economy.
   ``He understood that building a full-employment, low-inflation
economy that creates opportunity for every single citizen in this
country was essential to our strength at home and abroad,'' Dukakis
said.
   ``Above all, we've got to have a real leader in the White House
who will insist that when it comes to our national security we're
going to make decisions based not on what's good for one company or
one military service or one political party, but on what's good for
the United States of America,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
