<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Rosary-Messages     08-11 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rosary-Messages,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Wrestling with Logistics of Hosting Thousands for Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of a Catholic church readied
Thursday for as many as 20,000 people expected at a feast day
celebration this weekend after parishioners claiming to have
received divine messages predicted miracles would occur.
   Volunteers at St. John Neumann Roman Catholic Church answered
telephones and finished banners, while others hurried to finish an
altar and pulpit being constructed on the roof of the underground
church.
   Worshipers have chartered buses and booked hotel rooms to come
to the church for Monday's Feast of the Assumption, the climax of
four days of worship and the day Roman Catholics celebrate their
belief in the Virgin Mary's assumption into heaven.
   The church attracted attention after parishioners claimed to
have received messages from Mary during weekly rosary recitations
and predicted miracles of physical and spiritual healing would
occur coinciding with the feast.
   As word spread in the past month about the claims, the church
office was forced to install four new phone lines to handle
inquiries.
   Church officials are uncertain how many people will attend the
four days of worship, highlighted by a Monday evening service.
   Although the church's sanctuary seats 850, the Mass and rosary
Monday will be held outside to accommodate the pilgrims, said the
church's pastoral assistant, Cynthia Wynn.
   ``We feel like people will be all over that field and spread
across the parking lot,'' she said, surveying a large grassy area
beneath the improvised rooftop altar.
   Parishioner David Garza, an attorney, said trying to plan the
event without knowing how many will attend hasn't been easy.
   ``We are one of the smallest parishes in town. We don't have a
lot of money, but people have been very generous,'' he said.
   Ideas for how to accommodate the crowd were based on his trip
last September to see Pope John Paul II in San Antonio, Garza said.
   ``I started writing in my notebook all the things that I
remembered from the pope's visit _ medical tents, water,
ambulances,'' he said.
   St. John Neumann will have 20 portable toilets, two medical
tents, two first-aid stations, and drinking water will be
available, he said.
   Since early spring, parishioners Mike Slate, Mary Constancio and
Theresa Werner have claimed to receive messages from the Virgin
Mary during Monday night rosary service, and attendance has swelled
from a handful to more than 1,000.
   At Monday's outdoor service, the church plans to distribute
50,000 copies of a booklet containing the weekly messages, which
included predicting miracles during the festival and pleas to work
for peace.
</TEXT>
