<1ST_LINE>r a AM-President'sWives     08-11 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-President's Wives,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Roosevelt Most Admired</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-three years after her husband died in
office and 26 years after her own death, Eleanor Roosevelt is the
president's wife most admired by American women, according to a
poll in the September Ladies Home Journal.
   The wife of Franklin D. Roosevelt was named by 28 percent of the
women surveyed for the magazine by the Roper Organization.
   Nancy Reagan, the incumbent first lady, was second, with 26
percent.
   The rest of the most-admired were: Jacqueline Onassis, widow of
John F. Kennedy, 20 percent; Betty Ford, 17 percent; Rosalynn
Carter, 11 percent; Patricia Nixon, 7 percent; Lady Bird Johnson
and Mamie Eisenhower, 6 percent each; and Bess Truman, 5 percent.
   The percentages add up to more than 100 because some of those
polled named more than one.
   The poll, conducted among 1,000 women during the third week of
April, is projectable for the entire country with an error margin
of 3 percent, the magazine said.
   Sixty-nine percent of the women polled said that when a
president and his wife disagree on a controversial issue, she
should keep quiet about it in public. Twenty-five percent said she
should speak out, and 7 percent had no opinion.
   Forty-nine percent said a wife with a career should give it up
when her husband enters the White House. Forty-one percent said she
should keep working, and 10 percent were undecided.
   Asked how a president's wife should spend her time, 57 percent
suggested becoming active in a cause, 17 percent said be a helper
of her husband, 14 percent said entertain and attend ceremonies and
5 percent said get involved in government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
