<HEAD>Senate Condemns Human Rights Abuses in Romania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 93-0 approval Thursday of a
resolution condemning human rights abuses in Romania.
   The non-binding document said President Reagan should tell
Romania that favorable U.S. trade privileges won't be considered
until the eastern European nation takes a number of steps to
improve its human rights record.
   The resolution said there is ``a persistent pattern of severe
human rights abuses'' in Romania, including denial of emigration
and interruption of the lives of ethnic minorities.
   The Romanian government is also about to bulldoze 7,000 small
villages and replace them with government-owned farm collectives,
the resolution noted.
</TEXT>
