<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietInspectors     08-11 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Missile Experts End Visit to Belgium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet experts left Thursday after
winding up inspections of U.S. cruise missiles at two sites under
the new treaty to eliminate medium- and shorter-range nuclear
weapons.
   The 20 inspectors posed for photographs and bid farewell to
their U.S. escorts before boarding an Aeroflot flight back to
Moscow.
   The inspectors arrived Monday and then broke up into two teams
to count missiles at Florennes Air Base, 40 miles south of
Brussels, and the European Repair Facility at nearby Gosselies.
   ``It was a very good inspection ... characterized by a very
cooperative spirit,'' said U.S. Air Force Col. John Fer, head of
the U.S. On-Site Inspection Agency's European office at Rhein-Main
Air Base in Germany. ``It was cordial but at the same time it was
very professional and very well done.''
   The experts finished their inspections Wednesday and then went
on a tour of Brussels and shopped for T-shirts, souvenirs,
chocolate and toys, the U.S. escorts said.
   Belgium is the fourth Western European country the Soviets have
visited since the 60-day inspection period began July 1.
   Fer said there are additional missile facilities in Germany and
Italy that the inspectors have yet to check.
   The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States and five
Western European countries. U.S. experts are inspecting 133 sites
in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   The inspections, giving the Soviets and the Americans an
unprecedented look at each other's facilities, can last up to 24
hours, with a possible eight-hour extension.
   In Belgium, the Soviets visited Florennes where U.S. officials
have said 16 ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares are
kept along with four launchers and eight spares. The 485th U.S.
Tactical Missile Wing is based at Florennes.
   There was no indication how many unarmed cruise missiles are at
the Gosselies facility, which is run by the Belgian defense
contractor Sabca.
   On June 21, there were 55 missiles at the plant, which is the
only one in Europe that maintains and repairs cruise missiles, U.S.
officials said.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty provides for
elimination within three years of all U.S. and Soviet land-based
missiles with ranges from about 300 to 3,400 miles. President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed the treaty in
December in Washington.
</TEXT>
