<HEAD>More Than 1,000 Officers To Work Security At Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New Orleans Police Department will go
into its ``Mardi Gras mode'' to provide security for the Aug. 15-18
Republican National Convention in the Louisiana Superdome.
   Police Deputy Chief Ray Holman said Wednesday officers will work
12-hour shifts instead of eight hours, starting this weekend.
   About 750 department officers, plus over 1,000 local, state and
federal law enforcement officers, will work security during the
convention, he said.
   The indoor stadium will be evacuated at 1 p.m. Sunday for a bomb
sweep.
   From then on, only authorized traffic will be allowed near the
Superdome, and checkpoints in the area will be staffed by police.
   Only vehicles that have been searched will be allowed inside any
of the nine entrances through an eight-foot chain-link fence that
surrounds the Superdome.
   ``We'll have about 1,100 law-enforcement officers covering
everything, including internal and external security ... to protect
convention visitors,'' Holman said.
