<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HongKong-Refugees     08-11 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong-Refugees,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>90 Vietnamese Boat People Want to Go Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 90 among thousands of Vietnamese boat
people who flooded this colony's shores in recent months have asked
to be returned home, a government spokeswoman said Thursday.
   Most of the refugees seeking a return trip _ about 70 _ have
come forward in the past week, since Hong Kong opened talks with
Hanoi about large-scale repatriation, said the spokeswoman, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. Vietnam has said it is ready to
take back refugees who want to return.
   After the Vietnam War ended in 1975, Hong Kong considered all
Vietnamese arriving by boat as political refugees eligible for
resettlement in third countries.
   An estimated 23,000 refugees have come to this tiny British
colony, whose 5.5 million people already are crowded in the
20-square-mile enclave. Hong Kong, with its active business
community, is on the southeastern coast of China about 500 miles
from Vietnam's northern border.
   A new policy took effect in Hong Kong on June 16 to curb the
surging number of arrivals. It labels all incoming Vietnamese as
illegal immigrants subject to repatriation except those who can
prove that persecution drove them from communist Vietnam.
   Despite the new rules, about 7,000 Vietnamese boat people have
sailed into Hong Kong since mid-June, and Hong Kong has been
packing most of them into temporary detention centers.
   The government spokeswoman said some of those who requested
repatriation were classified as illegal immigrants. But she said
others were classified as refugees entitled to be resettled.
   She said she had no further details.
   Only 21 boat people have been voluntarily repatriated from Hong
Kong since 1978, including two in July.
   Officials of Hong Kong and Vietnam met in Hanoi on Aug. 3-4 to
discuss repatriations. No agreement was reached, but more talks
were expected.
   The repatriation applications of the 90 volunteers will be
forwarded to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees for discussion
with Hanoi. U.N. officials could not be reached immediately for
comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
