<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CincinnatiArchbishop     08-11 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cincinnati Archbishop,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cincinnati Archbishop Leaves Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk, spiritual
leader of 550,000 Roman Catholics in the Archdiocese of Cincinnati,
was released from a hospital Thursday after treatment for a
ruptured brain artery.
   Pilarczyk, 53, waved to reporters and photographers from a
wheelchair before he was ushered into a waiting car.
   Doctors have said the archbishop may be able return to work in
about a month. His condition was listed as good, Karen Kinsella,
spokeswoman for Good Samaritan Hospital, said Thursday.
   Pilarczyk underwent surfery July 25 to repair an aneurysm near
the base of his brain. He suffered the aneurysm two days earlier as
he was vacationing in Gatlinburg, Tenn. He was moved to Cincinnati
for the operation.
   An aneurysm is a sac formed in the wall of an artery and is
blamed on a congenital weakness in the arterial wall.
   Pilarczyk's doctors said the archbishop gave them approval to
use an experimental drug, which they said may have helped save his
life by possibly preventing arterial spasms that can occur even
after surgery. The drug, called nicardipine, relaxes the arterial
wall and prevents spasms, doctors said.
   John M. Tew Jr., a neurosurgeon, used a laser to operate and
seal off the ruptured artery. Tew and the other doctors said they
rerouted the blood supply in the archbishop's brain to prevent a
recurrence of the potentially fatal rupture.
   Pilarczyk, archbishop since 1982 in the 19-county southwestern
Ohio archdiocese, is a native of Dayton. He succeeded Joseph
Cardinal Bernardin as head of the Cincinnati Archdiocese after
Bernardin was elevated to the Chicago Archdiocese by Pope John Paul
II.
</TEXT>
