<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     08-11 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Leaders Urge Vigilance as Iran, Iraq Trade Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-UN</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian leaders told their countrymen
Thursday that the war with Iraq was not over and urged them to stay
on guard. Each side accused the other of belligerent acts.
   President Ali Khamenei said Iran ``must not trust the deceiving
enemy, therefore we say that the war is apparently, not definitely,
about to end.''
   Both Iran and Iraq have accepted U.N. Resolution 598 calling for
a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war. The truce is to go into effect
Aug. 20.
   Tehran radio, in quoting Khamenei's remarks, said he was
speaking at ceremonies in Iran on Thursday where ``people from all
walks of life donated tens of millions of rials in cash and tens of
pieces of gold to assist at the war fronts.''
   The radio was monitored in Nicosia.
   The commander of Iran's Revolutionary Guards, Mohsen Rezai, was
quoted on Thursday as saying that ``troops all along the war front
are on full alert.''
   Rezai told the newspaper Kayhan that the state of alert will
continue ``until full implementation of Resolution 598 was
ensured.''
   Iraq on Thursday accused Iran of shelling Iraqi military
positions near the Shatt al-Arab waterway, where the Persian Gulf
war broke out in September 1980.
   The accusation was in a brief statement issued by the Iraqi
Mission to the United Nations in New York. The report was not
carried on newscasts late Thursday in Iraq.
   According to the statement, ``the Iranian armed forces bombarded
Iraqi military positions of the 3rd Armed Corps Sector'' with
howitzer fire, mortar shells and small missiles. The sector
mentioned is near Iraq's southern port city of Basra.
   Iraqi positions in the 7th Army Corps Sector near the southern
Faw peninsula were also bombarded and tanks fired across the
northern border, the account said.
   Iran gave U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar a
letter pledging it would not launch any attacks in the interim.
   Iraq did not submit a similar letter, but Perez de Cuellar said
Tuesday he had received assurances from both Iran and Iraq that
they would exercise restraint.
   Tehran radio on Wednesday accused Iraqi planes of intruding over
southwest Iran. Iraqi media carried no reports on air force
activity, and there was no independent confirmation of such flights.
   Iran's U.N. ambassador, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, later said
the cease-fire could be jeopardized if Iraqi warplanes continued to
buzz Iranian cities. He lodged a protest with the secretary-general.
   Attempts inside Iraq to confirm the reports of Iranian firing
failed. The official Iraqi news service carried a summary of the
report issued at the United Nations.
   One of the six members of a U.N. team sent to Baghdad to prepare
for the arrival of the full cease-fire observer force said the team
had yet to begin its monitoring work. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The United Nations is to send 350 observers to monitor the
cease-fire.
   Also on Thursday, Prime Minister Hussein Musavi of Iran told
Oman's foreign minister, Yusuf Bin Alawi, that nations in the
region should establish positive relations to avoid threats from
foreign powers.
   ``We must expand our relations in all fields,'' he said in a
Tehran radio report. ``As to the security of the Persian Gulf and
Indian Ocean, which can only be provided by the regional countries,
we must go on having exchanges of views.''
   Foreign navies maintain about 60 ships in and around the gulf to
protect neutral shipping from Iranian attacks that grew out of the
gulf war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
