<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotCars     08-11 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hot Cars,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Border Patrol Gets High-Performance Cars for Pursuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four high-performance sports cars will be
deployed by the U.S. Border Patrol along the Arizona-Mexico border
in hopes of making high-speed chases shorter, safer and less
frequent, officials said.
   Two Pontiac Trans-Am Formula 350s, a Camero IROC Z-28 and a
special service Ford Mustang soon will be deployed in the Border
Patrol's Tucson Sector, which was chosen to test and evaluate the
high-performance vehicles, said Robert S. Coffin, the sector's
chief deputy patrol officer.
   The four cars, valued at about $60,000, were purchased with
money from the Border Alliance, an interagency group that fights
drug-smuggling along the Mexican border, Coffin said. The cars will
have Border Patrol decals, sirens and flashing lights, he said.
   The cars are to be deployed Aug. 22, according to Ronald Dowdy,
chief patrol agent for the Tucson Sector.
   Dowdy and Coffin said the idea is to make high-speed pursuits
shorter, and therefore safer. The agency also is publicizing the
use of the high-performance cars in hopes of discouraging suspects
from trying to run away, the officials said.
   One advantage of the high-performance cars is faster
acceleration, Dowdy said. He said agents often are parked when
someone speeds past them and catching up can be difficult.
   ``They're going 65 and we're going 0,'' he said.
   Nine officers have been chosen to be part of the pilot program.
They are being sent to a special high-speed driving school first.
``We want them to learn to handle vehicles at high speeds before we
put them out there in these vehicles,'' Coffin said.
   The officers will evaluate the performance of the cars and make
a recommendation to the Border Patrol in about six months. If the
cars are found to be effective, more could be purchased in the
future, Coffin said.
   The Arizona Department of Public Safety began experimenting with
high-performance cars in 1986 with the purchase of 10 Mustangs. The
department now has 20 to 25 such cars on highway patrol duty, and
another 20 are about to be put on highways, said Sgt. Allan
Schmidt, a department spokesman.
   Dowdy said the Border Patrol, which has a fleet of about 200
cars, initially plans to deploy the high-performance vehicles along
Interstates 19 and 10 in southern Arizona.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
