<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsInstitutions     08-11 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Institutions,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>S&L Capital Loss Slows in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings and loan associations lost capital at
a slower rate in the second quarter, reflecting efforts of federal
regulators to close or bail out insolvent institutions, statistics
released Thursday indicate.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said the industry's capital
declined by $1.72 billion in the April-June period, compared with a
drop of $3.51 billion in the first quarter and $4.68 billion in the
last three months of 1987.
   Changes in capital, which is the difference between an
institution's loans and other assets and what it owes to depositors
and other creditors, often reflect profits or losses.
   However, an economist with an industry trade group said S&L
losses likely are not improving as much as the capital figures
would indicate. That is because the Federal Home Loan Bank Board is
closing or rescuing more institutions with negative capital, said
Martin Regalia, chief economist of the National Council of Savings
Institutions.
   ``Looking at these numbers, things are apparently not getting
any worse, but I wouldn't want to go out on a limb and say they've
gotten a whole lot better,'' Regalia said.
   ``But, it's plus in the sense that (regulators) are doing the
right thing. ... This is an indication that the bank board has made
some moves to get rid of bad institutions and that's heartening,''
he said.
   Federally insured S&Ls lost a record $3.81 billion in the fourth
quarter of 1987 and a near-record $3.78 billion in the first three
months of this year. Industrywide profit and loss figures for the
second quarter will not be available until September.
   The bank board also reported that S&L depositors withdrew more
money from their accounts than they deposited in June for the
second consecutive month. Net withdrawal were $2.9 billion in June
after withdrawals of $1.0 billion in May.
   James Barth, chief economist of the bank board, attributed the
deposit shrinkage to normal seasonal factors such as spending on
vacations. Also, he said as stock prices recover some S&L customers
are apparently withdrawing money to buy stock.
   Before May, net deposits grew for seven consecutive months as
investors, battered by the October crash, sought a safe haven in
federally insured savings accounts.
   For the first six months of the year, net deposits were up $12.2
billion, compared with net withdrawals of $15.4 billion in the
first half of 1987.
   Savings institutions closed $24.8 billion in mortgages in June,
up from $21.2 billion in May. However, for the first six months
mortgage lending was down 15.2 percent from the same period last
year.
   Barth said that is because mortgage rates were higher during the
first half of 1988 than a year ago and fewer people are refinancing
their loans.
   Regalia said the expected decline in housing activity later this
year as interest rates increase likely will cut into healthy thrift
institutions' profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
