<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     08-11 0885</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Polls Suggest Bush-Dole Ticket Best, But Marginally</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private polls conducted by George Bush's
presidential campaign have shown that former rival Sen. Bob Dole,
R-Kan., would give him a larger boost than others being considered
for the No. 2 spot on the ticket, but even this lift is a small
one, campaign sources said Thursday.
   Sources familiar with Bush's selection process, who spoke only
on the condition of anonymity, said a Bush-Dole ticket showed up as
only marginally stronger than other potential combinations for
which polling was done.
   Dole's advantage ``is a little bit, but not enough to make much
of a difference,'' said one source.
   A ticket of Bush and Bob Dole ran stronger than a hypothetical
ticket of Bush and Dole's wife, former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole, the sources said.
   Bush's polling, by his chief pollster, Robert Teeter, is all but
complete, suggesting that the vice president will likely make up
his mind in the closely guarded process based on criteria other
than polling, the sources said. Bush has said he will not announce
his choice until the convention.
   The soon-to-be Republican presidential nominee appeared with a
group of black supporters, members of a 100-strong group calling
itself ``Black Americans for Bush,'' and said he would have a
``broad-based'' Cabinet.
   However, he declined to say whether he would name a black to
that Cabinet, a promise he had previously made only to Hispanics.
   Bush also declined to be drawn into a discussion of whether he
was considering Lt. Gen. Colin L. Powell, the first black ever to
hold the post of national security adviser, for the No. 2 spot.
   He said he had ``worked closely with Colin Powell and I have
great respect for him.'' But, he said, ``Don't put it into any vice
presidential equation.''
   Sources said that Bush has not done any polling on Powell and
that he is not under active consideration.
   Those who were contacted earlier by Bush, and asked to provide
financial data, include both Doles, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York, and
Sens. Alan Simpson, of Wyoming, Pete Domenici of New Mexico and Dan
Quayle of Indiana, according to campaign aides.
   Govs. George Deukmejian of California, Jim Thompson of Illinois,
John Sununu of New Hampshire, Carroll Campbell of South Carolina
and former governor Lamar Alexander of Tennessee were also among
those on the original list of those under consideration, the aides
said. Deukmejian has since withdrawn his name from consideration.
   Bush sources said that polling data indicated that candidates
from small states _ like Simpson _ only helped the ticket
significantly in those states and would have little impact
nationally.
   Simpson, a close friend of Bush, does not expect to be given a
spot on the ticket, a spokesman, Mary Kay Hill, said on Thursday.
   ``I don't think the call will come. I think they'll need to play
Electoral College politics,'' she said.
   She said Simpson and Bush talked about 10 days ago and Simpson
told the vice president ``he did not feel he could help him''
because of some controverisal positions he has taken, including
limits on cost-of-living increases for Social Security recipients
and veterans.
   Sources also suggested that no polling had been done on
Domenici, suggesting that he may no longer be under active
consideration.
   Meanwhile, Kemp said he has no expectations that he'll get
picked, and is ``not sitting by the telephone'' waiting to be
asked. But the New York congressman said he would, naturally, jump
at the job.
   ``If I'm asked, I would be happy. If I'm not, I'm going to be
equally happy,'' Kemp said in an interview taped Thursday for the
syndicated television show, McLaughlin's ``One on One.''
   In another development, two Tennessee Republicans mentioned as
vice presidential prospects, Alexander and former Sen. Howard H.
Baker Jr., said they plan only minimal participation in next week's
convention.
   Alexander, now president of the University of Tennessee, will
fly to New Orleans on Sunday to address a meeting of the Republican
governors and return to Nashville that evening. Alexander has said
he would not refuse the No. 2 spot, but most Tennessee Republican
leaders say they do not believe he will be asked.
   Baker, former White House chief of staff, said he is among hosts
for a luncheon Monday in New Orleans honoring first lady Nancy
Reagan and will meet the with Tennessee's congressional delegation.
He will make a brief trip back to Tennessee, then return to New
Orleans on Thursday for a luncheon in honor of his work as Senate
majority leader and of Sen. Bob Dole's work as minority leader.
   In his meeting with black supporters, Bush said that, while he
was aware that most black voters traditionally voted Democratic,
``we have a good shot, we have a chance''
   He said that in his campaign he would demonstrate ``my
commitment in the field of civil rights and in opening the arms of
this party ... I will be a fair-play kind of person.''
   The coalition of blacks supporting Bush includes Joshua Smith,
president of the Maxima Corp., Porcia Scott, editor of the Atlanta
Daily World Newspaper, James Cheek, president of Howard University,
entertainer Lionel Hampton and Larry Brown, former running back for
the Washington Redskins.
</TEXT>
