<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietHarvest     08-11 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Harvest,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Says Soviet Grain Harvest Prospects Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crop Report Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for this year's grain harvest in the
Soviet Union have declined slightly from earlier indications, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Officials said the Soviet harvest is now expected to be around
210 million metric tons, a decline of 5 million tons from the level
forecast in recent months. Yields were said to be smaller than
expected.
   Production of spring-planted grain has been hit hardest,
including spring wheat, oats and barley, the USDA report said. The
output of spring wheat could be the lowest since 1984.
   ``However, this is not expected to result in additional Soviet
wheat imports at this time as smaller supplies of quality wheat
worldwide have sharply driven up prices,'' the report said.
``Instead, as the Soviets are expected to limit any potential
(inventory) stock buildup in 1988-89 and could even draw on stocks
accumulated in recent years if necessary.''
   Part of the reason for the reduction in USDA's estimate was said
to be a smaller-than-expected planted area, as reported by Moscow,
as well as deterioration in spring grain yields.
   Even so, at 210 million tons of grain, the Soviet harvest would
be one of the largest on record. The largest was 237.4 million tons
in 1978.
</TEXT>
