<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     08-11 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Six, Set Off Bombs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist rebels killed six peasants they accused
of aiding the military, officials said Thursday.
   Other guerrillas belonging to a pro-Cuba group exploded a car
bomb shortly before Wednesday midnight at a state mining company
office, slightly wounding three passersby, police reported.
   A column of Maoist Shining Path guerrillas entered Chilete
village in the Andes near Ayacucho, 225 miles southeast of Lima, on
Monday and ordered residents to a central plaza to witness a
``popular trial,'' the military said.
   Six peasants were shot to death after the guerrillas ruled that
they had been government informers and provided support to troops
in the region, the military said.
   The Shining Path has fought Peruvian governments for eight
years. Official figures put the number of dead at 15,000 and the
damage at $10 billion.
   Police said the Lima bombing was the work of the Tupac Amaru
revolutionary movement, which endorses Cuba-style Marxism and has
been active for four years. Its bombings normally occur when few
people are in the vicinity.
   The car bomb exploded at the suburban offices of Centromin, a
state mining company crippled by a 3-week-old miners' strike.
Parcel bombs exploded at the offices of two other mining companies
at about the same time, but police said they caused no casualties
or serious damage.
</TEXT>
