<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japanese-Canadians     08-11 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japanese-Canadians,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Declines To Copy U.S. Compensation Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All money figures in U.S. dollars</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said Thursday that
failure to redress the internment of 12,000 Japanese-Canadians
during World War II is a blot on the nation's honor, but he refused
to follow the U.S. example and promise cash compensation.
   Under questioning in Parliament, Mulroney said his Conservative
government was prepared to make a formal apology to
Japanese-Canadians whose goods and property were seized during the
war, and to set up a community fund to fight racism.
   But pressed by opposition Liberal and New Democratic Party
members to match the bill signed this week by President Reagan,
Mulroney made no commitments. The U.S. legislation gives 60,000
surviving Japanese-American internees $20,000 each.
   ``Compensation was not the sticking point,'' Mulroney argued,
noting that former Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's Liberal
government refused to even consider redress for Japanese-Canadians
interned as wartime security threats.
   Although their homes, fishing boats and belongings were sold
off, the internees were never discovered to have aided Japan or
hurt Canada. Nevertheless, successive governments until now
defended the internment as a necessary wartime precaution.
   Mulroney termed the incident a ``tragedy'' and said discussions
with Japanese-Canadians were making progress. Answering a question,
he said: ``It is a very serious (blot) on Canada's honor.''
   Four successive Cabinet ministers in charge of ethnic minorities
have failed to resolve a compensation claim by the National
Association of Japanese-Canadians. Association president Art Miki
said the current minister, Gerry Weiner, has declined to set a date
for new talks.
   Miki, a high school principal in Winnipeg, told The Associated
Press that passage of the U.S. bill gave Japanese-Canadians renewed
hope.
   ``Everyone you meet in our community was very pleased,'' said
Miki, 51, who was interned as a child. ``The American precedent
certainly strengthens our case.''
   He said the Mulroney government has been trying to treat the
survivors as a group. ``But it's individuals who make up the group.
The American government recognizes those individual rights.''
   Japanese-Canadians have a stronger case since, unlike most of
their American counterparts, they were not allowed to return to
their homes, Miki said.
   Many still live in the prairies where they were interned on
farms, never returning to British Columbia, where the majority
worked in the fishing industry.
   Miki said his group wants $20,500 compensation for each of the
12,000 survivors; a formal apology, and a community project fund of
$41 million instead of the $9.8 million proposed by the government.
   The demands total $287 million. A report commissioned by the
national association said the original 21,000 internees incurred
losses of $363 million in 1986 dollars.
   Miki said most of the survivors are in their 70s and the
mortality rate is about 1,000 a year.
   The Globe and Mail, Canada's national newspaper, said in an
editorial this week that the lack of compensation was ``shameful''
and the government should forget about offering ``piddling sums.''
   There was a small step towards reconciliation last week when the
town of Kaslo, British Columbia, one of the internment sites, held
a two-day event to acknowledge the injustice done to
Japanese-Canadians.
   A plaque unveiled on the occasion said: ``These innocent and
loyal Canadians did not pose a threat to national security but were
victims of racism and political expediency.''
</TEXT>
