<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IBMContract     08-11 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Contract,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burnley: Contract Dispute Shouldn't Delay Air Traffic Control
Overhaul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A temporary suspension of a $3.6 billion
contract with International Business Machines Corp. should not
seriously interfere with the planned modernization of air traffic
control computers, Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said
Thursday.
   The General Services Administration's board of appeals ordered
the contract suspended Wednesday after a competitor for the
contract, Hughes Aircraft Co., challenged the awarding of the
project to IBM.
   The appeals board, a semi-judicial body that resolves government
contract disputes, has scheduled 45 days to resolve the matter.
   Both IBM and Hughes, a subsidiary of General Motors Corp., had
competed for the $3.6 billion contract to build a new, automated
computer system for the Federal Aviation Administration's air
traffic control operations. The modernization project is to be
completed in the late 1990s.
   The Transporation Department selected IBM over Hughes on July
25. At a news conference announcing the award, officials said IBM
was selected primarily because it submitted a lower bid.
   Burnley told reporters he has ``a lot of confidence that in this
case everything was run by the numbers'' as far as the selection
was concerned.
   He suggested that if the matter was resolved after the 45-day
period, the project would not be adversely affected. ``If that's
all that happens I don't think it will hurt us at all.''
   But Burnley acknowledged ``it would become critical'' if there
were longer delays that would threaten the ability of IBM to hold
together the teams already assembled for the project.
   Meanwhile, Burnley said he was surprised at the decision by
Hughes to protest the contract award because, he said, he had been
assured by General Motors chairman Roger Smith several days after
IBM received the contract that no protest would be filed.
   Hughes Aircraft in its challenge asked that the contract with
IBM be revoked, arguing that the FAA and Transportation Department
had provided IBM unfair advantages.
   Hughes accused the FAA of failing to follow a requirement that
said technical merits were to be given greater weight than price
when awarding the contract.
   Hughes also claimed several irregularities caused its price to
be inflated. For example, Hughes's bid relied on IBM to provide
computer hardware. But, according to Hughes Aircraft, IBM charged
Hughes substantially more for the hardware than what IBM quoted the
FAA for the same items in their separate bid.
</TEXT>
