<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DOT-Drugs     08-11 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DOT-Drugs,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transportation Inspectors to Keep Eye Out for Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inspectors working for the Federal Aviation
Administration and other Transportation Department agencies are
being enlisted for the war against illegal drugs, Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley said Thursday.
   Burnley said the more than 4,200 DOT inspectors ``will receive
drug awareness training so they can serve as a new army of `eyes'
in the nation's anti-drug effort.''
   These inspectors are involved in monitoring airlines, trucking
companies, shipping vessels and the railroads.
   Burnley acknowledged that the DOT inspectors have no police
power to interfere in drug trafficking if it is discovered. But he
said they will be told to keep their eyes open for signs of
possible illegal drug activity and notify authorities.
   What might make an aviation inspector suspicious?
   A few items listed by the Transportation Department included:
   Evidence of adhesive tape near registration numbers, showing
possible alteration of the numbers; the presence of sophisticated
navigation instruments on inappropriate aircraft; warped or
misaligned aircraft doors indicating they have been opened in
flight, possibly for air drops; or unusual rivet patterns
indicating that the plane might have been altered to create hiding
places for drugs or extra fuel tanks.
</TEXT>
