<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     08-11 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Rejects Annexation; PLO Leaders Arrive In Jordan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel should neither annex the occupied
territories nor include the Palestine Liberation Organization in
discussions of their future, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
Thursday.
   PLO officials arrived in Jordan for meetings about King
Hussein's decision last week to give the organization full
responsibility for the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip,
where 1.5 million Palestinians live.
   There have been reports of disagreement among aides to chairman
Yasser Arafat about whether Hussein helped or hurt the PLO by
cutting ties to the territories, where an uprising began Dec. 8.
   Israeli soldiers fired on strone-throwing Palestinians in the
West Bank on Thursday and violent demonstrations were reported in
the Gaza Strip. A young Palestinian was wounded by gunfire.
   Shamir said Israel's enemies were using the rebellion to
undermine its morale.
   ``They have come to the conclusion they can and will attack
Israel's vulnerable points: Israeli morale, Israeli motivation and
Israel's faith in its righteousness,'' he said at a graduation
ceremony of the National Defense College.
   Earlier Thursday, he rejected demands for annexation by
right-wing groups.
   He said the status of the territories could be decided only in
talks with Palestinians not affiliated with the PLO, which Israel
regards as a terrorist organization.
   ``We honor our international obligations and we shall not make
any unilateral step, like imposing Israeli rule on the territories
that are subject to negotiations,'' Shamir said.
   His reference was to the U.S.-mediated Camp David accords
reached by Israel and Egypt in 1978, which call for five years of
autonomy for Palestinians before negotiations on the final status
of land captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Hussein's separation from the occupied lands included laying off
about 21,000 civil servants paid by his government.
   ``Jordan was committed by Arab summit resolutions to certain
obligations toward the West Bank until the land is liberated,''
Arafat aide Khaled Hassan was quoted as saying in an interview
published Thursday in the Saudi Arabian newspaper Al-Sharq al-Awsat.
   In neighboring Dubai, the newspaper Al-Bayan quoted Salah
Khalaf, anotehr aide to the PLO chief, as saying Hussein's
``courageous decision'' allows the PLO to ``shoulder its
responsibility and take over new political rights.''
   Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi said he would pay the salaries of
former employees of Jordan in the occupied lands, Monte Carlo radio
reported.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official said privately it was
``very hypothetical'' whether Israel would allow another Arab
country to send money into the territories.
   Soldiers in the West Bank wounding a 16-year-old Palestinian in
the right leg, officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus said.
   In the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, Palestinians set tires
ablaze and hurled rocks to protest the death Tuesday of a young
Arab burned to death in a suspected arson attack on a shack where
he was sleeping near Tel Aviv.
   A military court sentenced a Palestinian woman, Munira Daoud, to
eight months in prison for throwing a rock in April at a Jewish
settler guarding hiking Jewish teen-agers in the West Bank village
of Beita.
   The guard, Romam Aldubi, accidentally shot and killed
15-year-old Tirza Porat during the melee, according to an army
investigation.
   The military judge who passed sentence said he took into
consideration that Ms. Daoud's brother was killed in the
confrontation and the army had demolished her home in reprisal,
Israel radio said.
   Jewish settler Pinchas Wallerstein was charged Thursday with
manslaughter in the January shooting death of a Palestinian
teen-ager in Beitin, a West Bank village. Israel radio said the
maximum penalty is 20 years in prison.
</TEXT>
