<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Racism     08-11 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Racism,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Activist Arrested After Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish activist said Leningrad police detained
him and four other people Thursday after a rally by a Russian
nationalist group that condemns Jews and other ``alien races.''
   Abraham Demin, 29, telephoned The Associated Press and said he
had just been released from a police station to which he was taken
after arriving at a rally of the Pamyat group at the Rumyantsevsky
Garden in downtown Leningrad.
   Demin, who opposes Pamyat's activities, said he was accused of
``agitating,'' beaten and ordered to return to the station on
Friday for sentencing.
   Four other people, some of them who were clearly passersby at
the rally, also were detained, he said.
   Last week, the tabloid Moscow News published letters from
Soviets calling Pamyat racist and fascist. It has chapters in
Moscow and several other large Soviet cities and has held rallies
in Leningrad every Thursday since the end of June.
   One letter quoted a speaker at a rally July 7 as demanding
immediate deportation of Jews and other ``alien races.''
   Demin said about 200 people attended this week's rally, a
five-minute affair that lasted just long enough for Pamyat leaders
to say they were taking a vacation until early September, when the
rallies would resume in a building they did not name.
   He said about 50 police watched the scene.
   On Tuesday, police surrounded the Leningrad home of a prominent
dissident, 28-year-old Alexander Bogdanov, and arrested him for the
third time this year, Demin told the AP. He said Bogdanov He was
accused of disobeying a policeman and sentenced to 15 days in jail.
   Bogdanov had tried to put up anti-Pamyat posters at the group's
rally on Aug. 4, but police prevented him from doing so and later
confiscated the posters, Demin said.
</TEXT>
