<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildProstitution     08-11 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Prostitution,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say They Broke a Sex Ring Using Boys Across U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they've cracked a Tampa-based
child prostitution ring that sold the services of hundreds of boys
as young as 11, sometimes flying the children to meet clients in
distant cities.
   The network operated in several Florida counties and also sent
boys to Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Denver and Indianapolis,
investigators said.
   Three Florida men were arrested in June, police disclosed
Wednesday, and arrests were expected in other cities.
   Police said they first became aware of the operation when the
parents of an 11-year-old Tampa boy told police they wondered where
their son was getting large sums of cash.
   The man accused of being the ringleader, Wesley David Gonzalez,
26, of Daytona Beach, told authorities the clique used hundreds of
boys as sex slaves for scores of customers, said detective Robert
Sheehan.
   Gonzalez, also known as Michael David Gonzalez, was arrested in
June on charges of capital sexual battery, procuring children under
16 for prostitution and deriving financial support from
prostitution, Sheehan said.
   Gonzalez, an unemployed avionics technician, was being held
without bond at the Hillsborough County Jail.
   The other two men arrested in June were identified as Larry
Gorman, 38, and Michael Leroy Johnson, 30, both of Tampa. Police
said they helped Gonzalez find customers. Johnson was charged with
performing lewd and lascivious acts with a child; Gorman was
charged with performing a sexual act with a child. Both were
released on bond.
   Sheehan said Gonzalez understood the psyche of the boys he
recruited _ most of them runaways or children from poor or broken
homes _ because he was once one of them. He used boys to recruit
others, flashing wads of cash as a lure, according to the detective.
   ``A lot of the kids despised the sex, but the financial
inducements were too enticing to the youngsters,'' said Sheehan.
   Gonzalez told detectives he turned to prostitution when he was
12, taking up pimping when he ``basically became too old,'' Sheehan
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
