<DOCNO> AP880811-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     08-11 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops Urge Consensus on Presidential Nominee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FEDERICO QUILODRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic bishops urged Chile's
military commanders Thursday to avoid a possible deadlock in
October's yes-or-no presidential referendum by choosing a nominee
acceptable to the opposition.
   President Augusto Pinochet, the army commander who has ruled
Chile since a 1973 coup, is expected to be chosen at a meeting Aug.
30 of the army, navy, air force and national police commanders. The
nominee's name will be the only one on the ballot.
   The Rev. Carlos Gonzalez, president of the Episcopal Conference,
told a news conference Thursday ``we are probably headed for a
tie,'' meaning an edge either way of 3 percent of the vote.
Opposition leaders oppose continued rule by Pinochet.
   If the nominee wins a majority, he will begin an eight-year term
in March. If not, an open election will be held in 1990 and
Pinochet will stay in office until then.
   Gonzalez released a statement signed by the conference's leaders
that declared:
   ``Chile is becoming polarized and radicalized. A considerable
number of Chileans feel uncomfortable about the referendum being
called because they fear _ whether a vote of yes or no triumphs _
there exists the danger that the country is headed for a
confrontation.
   ``Many want to see the commanders ... present a candidate who
will preside impartially over the transition to democracy. The
candidate should be the fruit of an accord between the government
and the opposition.''
   The statement did not refer specifically to Pinochet's probable
nomination, but made clear the bishops prefer a less controversial
candidate.
   Pinochet, 72, has rejected previous suggestions that the choice
of a nominee be negotiated and his government has accused church
leaders of meddling in politics.
   Asked for comment on the proposal by Bishop Gonzalez, socialist
Ricardo Lagos told reporters the opposition would accept ``with all
seriousness'' an invitation from the government to negotiate. Lagos
is a leader of the 16-party opposition coalition supporting a
``no'' vote in the referendum.
   Pro-Pinochet leader Eduardo Doberti, however, was quoted by the
government news agency Orbe as saying the idea of a consensus
candidate ``has already been exhausted.'
   No date in October has been announced for the referendum. The
commanders are expected to reveal it along with the the candidate's
name.
</TEXT>
