<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Kahane     08-11 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Kahane,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militant Rabbi Gives Up U.S. Citizenship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rabbi Meir Kahane, who founded the Jewish
Defense League ago and favors deporting all Arabs from Israel, has
given up U.S. citizenship so he can run for re-election to
parliament, his spokesman said Thursday.
   Kahane, born in Brooklyn, successfully fought a U.S. attempt to
strip him of citizenship after he was elected to the Knesset in
1985.
   Spokesman Gad Servetman said Kahane, leader of the Kach Party,
took the action Wednesday in a letter addressed to the U.S. Embassy
in Tel Aviv. The purpose was to circumvent Israeli legislation
prohibiting Israelis who hold dual citizenship from serving in
parliament.
   Servetman said Kahane considered the fact that he might have
trouble re-entering the United States when he gave up his
citizenship.
   ``I know the rabbi was concerned, but as far as I understand, he
can still go to the United States,'' Servetman said.
   Kahane, who founded the Jewish Defense League in 1968, fought to
retain his U.S. passport in 1985 because he believed American
authorities would not grant him visas to enter the country.
   Well-known for his vitriolic tirades, Kahane advocates expelling
all Arabs from Israeli-held territory. Otherwise, he says, Israel
will eventually become an Arab state because the average Arab
family has more children than the average Israeli family.
 
</TEXT>
