<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-ABC     08-11 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-ABC,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Critize Fed On Discount Rate Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says he's opposed
to higher interest rates but won't criticize the Federal Reserve
for raising a key rate this week.
   ``I think the president has to work closely with the Fed even
though it's independent,'' Bush said in an interview with ABC News'
``Business Week,'' scheduled to be aired Sunday. A transcript of
the taped interview was released Thursday by the network.
   The Fed on Tuesday, claiming it was acting to keep the lid on
inflation, raised its discount rate _ the rate it charges for
short-term loans to its member banks _ to 6.5 percent from 6.0
percent.
   Rises in the bellwether rate usually push up other interest
rates throughout the economy.
   ``I don't want to see interest rates go higher,'' Bush said, but
he added that he didn't want to see inflation soar either.
   ``I can't assault them (the Fed) right now for this,'' Bush
said. ``You find a proper mix.''
   On another subject, Bush broke with the Reagan administration
and said if elected he would support a central recommendation of a
presidentially appointed commission on the Oct 19, 1987, stock
market crash calling for a single regulatory body _ preferably the
Fed _ to oversee financial markets.
   The commission was headed by New York investment banker Nicholas
Brady, a close friend of Bush's whom Reagan selected last week to
succeed James A. Baker III as treasury secretary.
   ``Giving the Fed a greater role in regulation, I think that
makes some sense,'' Bush said.
   Bush also said he would not act to curb corporate takeovers,
claiming that big is not bad. And he said that under a Bush
administration, ``we are not going to be patsies while we're
excluded from foreign markets.''
</TEXT>
