<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-UN 1stLd-Writethru a0696 08-11 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Accuses Iran Of Attacking Despite Truce</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Three grafs SUB for grafs 15-16 pvs, `U.N. spokesmen ... the
situation.' UPDATING with meeting with Iraqi envoy. PICKS up 17th
pvs, `Iran's envoys ... ' with minor editing to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Thursday accused Iran of firing
hundreds of shells and missiles at Iraqi military positions near
the Shatt al-Arab waterway, where the Persian Gulf war broke out
nearly eight years ago.
   A fragile truce had been in place since Monday, when
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced that Iran and
Iraq agreed to observe a cease-fire to begin on Aug. 20.
   ``The Iranian armed forces bombarded Iraqi military positions of
the Third Armed Corps Sector'' around Basra with hundreds of
howitzer and mortar shells and dozens of small missiles Wednesday
and Thursday, the Iraqi Mission said in a one-page statement to the
United Nations.
   It said Iran also bombarded Iraqi positions in the Seventh Armed
Corps Sector near the Faw peninsula, site of some of the war's most
ferocious offensives.
   The brief report to the United Nations did not include any
denunciations of Iran. Broadcast news in Iraq late Thursday did not
mention the accusations.
   The reported attacks could not be confirmed. Iran and Iraq both
rarely allow reporters near the war front.
   After Perez de Cuellar announced the Aug. 20 cease-fire date on
Monday, Iran gave him a letter pledging it would not launch any
attacks before that date.
   Iraq did not submit a similar letter, but the secretary-general
said Tuesday he received spoken assurances from both Iran and Iraq
that they would exercise restraint.
   The Iraqi Mission's letter also said an Iranian tank fired two
missiles at Iraqi positions in the ``northern sector.''
   The main attack on Basra involved 214 howitzer projectiles, 205
mortar shells and 32 small missiles, the letter said.
   The Faw bombardment involved 26 howitzer projectiles, 32 mortar
shells and 16 small missiles, it said. Iran also fired three
howitzer and 11 mortar shells at other Iraqi positions in the
Seventh Army Corps sector, it said.
   Basra and the Faw peninsula both are near the Shatt al-Arab, the
southern border between Iran and Iraq. The disputed waterway, which
leads into the Persian Gulf, is Iraq's only sea outlet, but wrecks
in the waterway and Iranian ships in the gulf have blocked it since
early in the war.
   Iraq invaded Iran in 1980 after border skirmishes in a bid to
gain complete control of the waterway.
   In recent months, Iraq recaptured large areas that had been
taken by Iran, including the Faw peninsula and marshland near
Basra. The reverses were seen as one reason Iran decided July 18 to
accept a Security Council cease-fire resolution that Iraq accepted
shortly after it was passed a year ago.
   The U.N. chief met later Thursday with Iraqi Ambassador Ismat
Kittani at Kittani's request.
   Asked later if he delivered a note of protest to the
secretary-general, Kittani replied, ``You assume wrongly. ... I
think our aim is to register with the U.N. a document of facts.''
   His tone was a marked contrast to the rancorous exchanges
between Iranian and Iraqi envoys that were customary up to last
month.
   Iran's envoys to the United Nations were not available for
comment. They left town for preparatory talks before peace talks
with Iraq due to begin Aug. 25 in Geneva, said a receptionist at
the Iranian Mission. She declined to give her name.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati registered a
protest Wednesday with the secretary-general, accusing Iraqi
warplanes of breaking the sound barrier over five Iranian cities in
violations of Iran's airspace.
   Perez de Cuellar said of the alleged overflights: ``I hope it is
something that doesn't mean that the Iraqis intended to break the
cease-fire. I am persuaded that if something happened, it was kind
of a mistake, a technical mistake, a misunderstanding.''
   In a letter to the secretary-general released Thursday,
Mahallati said the Iraqi planes broke the sound barrier over the
Iran cities of Bushehr, Ramhormoz, Masjid Suleiman and Gachsaran,
and invaded Iranian airspace over Piranshahr.
   Also Thursday, the Security Council approved the choice of
Yugoslavian Gen. Slavko Jovic, 58, as head of the U.N. Iran-Iraq
Military Observer Group, which is sending 350 officers from 24
countries to monitor the planned cease-fire.
   Morocco pledged Thursday to donate $2 million to set up the
force.
</TEXT>
