<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0767 08-11 0896</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0767,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Talks Defense; Bush Not Talking on Veep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with new polls, Bush comments, picking
up in 6th graf pvs, Private polls</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis went on the attack Thursday, saying if
he wins the White House there will be ``tough management, not
wishful thinking and blank checks'' for national defense. George
Bush said, ``I'm not gonna tell a soul'' before next week's
Republican convention who his running mate will be.
   Republicans labored in New Orleans to construct a staunchly
conservative platform crafted to Bush's specifications, complete
with a prohibition against higher taxes and abortions.
   ``We've built upon a constructive, conservative platform we had
in 1984, and then expanded it'' by including planks dealing with
drugs, AIDS and education, said Sen. Robert Kasten of Wisconsin,
co-chairman of the drafting committee.
   Three new polls showed Dukakis holding a lead over Bush,
although by less than in the days following last month's Democratic
National Convention. The margins ranged from 14 points in an NBC
News-Wall Street Journal survey conducted Aug. 5-8 to 12 points in
a CNN-USA Today poll conducted Aug. 5-8 to six points in a Business
Week survey conducted Aug. 4-9 _ the last a statistical dead head
because of the three-point plus-or-minus margin of error.
   Dukakis led Bush by 18 points in an NBC survey completed just
after the Democratic convention, but GOP strategists are counting
on their convention beginning next week to give the vice president
a corresponding boost.
   Slowly but surely, the mammoth Superdome was being prepared _
from the 10-story blue curtains that formed a telegenic backdrop
for the podium to the thousands of red, white and blue balloons
being inflated for next week's celebration of Bush's triumph.
   In Washington as in New Orleans, Bush was letting the suspense
build about his choice of a running mate.
   ``There won't be any leaks of this one because I'm not gonna
tell a soul and I haven't so far,'' Bush said in a CBS-TV
interview. He said some stories on the subject are ``close to
accurate and some of 'em are 180 degrees wrong.''
   Bush also said he plays horseshoes and jogs to help relieve the
pressure of preparing for his acceptance speech at next Thursday
night's convention session. ``I'm no William Jennings Bryan and I
think it'll go OK,'' he said in a reference to a renowned orator
who electrified the Democratic National Convention with his
speechmaking at the turn of the century but never won the White
House.
   Private polls conducted for the vice president indicate that
Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas would give him more of a boost than any
others in contention for the No. 2 spot on the ticket, but ``not
enough to make much of a difference,'' said one aide.
   Vendors next door to the Superdome hawked lapel buttons pairing
Bush with a variety of running mates, from likely contenders such
as Dole and Rep. Jack Kemp, to the far-far-fetched, like Oliver
North.
   Bush and his wife Barbara joined the president and first lady
Nancy Reagan at the White House for lunch. ``We're going to talk
about how to win,'' the vice president said as he arrived.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said afterward that the
vice president and president would stage a ``brief ceremony''
together at the Belle Chasse Naval Air Station in New Orleans next
Tuesday.
   Reagan had been scheduled to fly to New Orleans on Sunday, speak
to the convention Monday night and then leave Tuesday before Bush's
arrival.
   The seemingly innocuous presidential and vice presidential
comings and goings were fraught with political implications.
   The Bush campaign has relied all year on the vice president's
association with the president to bolster his campaign. Yet the
vice president's advisers also hope to use the convention to have
Bush come out of Reagan's political shadow and emerge as a strong
leader in his own right.
   Dukakis, campaigning in New York and New Jersey to kick off a
five-state swing, lauded Reagan for sealing an arms control
agreement with the Soviet Union, but criticized the
administration's military policy and Pentagon contract scandals.
   He also said Wednesday's increase in the prime lending rate
charged by major banks was ``regrettable, but I think it's what
happens after eight years of borrowing and spending, borrowing and
spending.''
   ``My friends, the test of a successful defense policy isn't how
much money we spend. It's how much security we buy,'' Dukakis said
in a speech at New York University. ``And for the past eight years,
we haven't gotten what we've gone into debt for.''
   ``We have to build strong military forces based on sound
planning and tough management, not wishful thinking and blank
checks,'' he said before heading off for Ft. Dix, N.J., where he
squeezed off a few rifle rounds at a firing range and toured a
C-141 transport plane.
   ``We've got to use those dollars to buy weapons that work,'' he
said. ``And we've got to to manage those dollars to strengthen our
military forces, not to line the pockets of dishonest contractors
and wheeler-dealer consultants.''
   Gov. Kay Orr of Nebraska said there was little prospect of a
floor fight at the convention over the lengthy platform document,
despite grumbling from Sen. Lowell Weicker and other dissenters
from some of the planks.
</TEXT>
