<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GOPPlatform 1stLd-Writethru a0721 08-11 0927</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Platform, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0721,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservative GOP Platform Nearing Completion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with AIDS, oil debate, panel returning
Friday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republicans finished work on major chunks of
their 1988 platform Thursday, crafting a document that toes the
conservative line on major issue.
   Near the end of the day, they recommended that the party support
reopening a major tax loophole for independent oil and gas
producers, but they defeated a proposal calling for expansion of
AIDS testing to bus drivers and other transportation workers.
   The convention platform committee completed their version of the
document save the defense and foreign policy sections, matters that
Nebraska Gov. Kay Orr, the committee chairman, said would be
wrapped up Friday morning.
   She said it was unlikely any minority planks would be pressed on
the convention floor next Tuesday.
   The 106-member platform committee, after spirited debates late
Wednesday over AIDS and abortion, turned to less controversial
issues Thursday such as urging schools to teach more geography and
foreign languages.
   But late Thursday, another bitter dispute over AIDS broke out.
   Porter Davis of Oklahoma proposed a plank calling for testing of
transportation personnel for the deadly disease.
   ``When you travel around New Orleans, you will take taxis and
buses,'' he said. ``When you go home, you will take planes and rely
on pilots and mechanics.''
   ``This is overkill,'' retorted Rep. Guy Molinari of New York.
``My God, we won't be able to get out of New Orleans if we adopted
this.''
   ``Fellow delegates, let's come to our senses. ... Why pick on
these people?'' said Bill Graham of North Carolina.
   The amendment was defeated without a formal vote tally.
   Earlier, the committee added language supporting efforts to
expand drug testing of transportation workers.
   A potential fight over apartheid was averted as Sen. Lowell P.
Weicker Jr. of Connecticut left town before the committee took up
the foreign policy plank. Weicker, who returned to Washington to
attend to Senate business, shelved plans to press an amendment
calling upon the GOP to back tough economic sanctions against South
Africa.
   Before leaving, Weicker got Sen. Robert Kasten of Wisconsin,
co-chairman of the committee, to press for adoption of another
Weicker amendment backing a merger of the Environmental Protection
Agency and the National Oceanographic and Atmospheric
Administration _ but not as a Cabinet-level Department of the
Enviornment, as Weicker originally sought.
   The amendment was adopted later without dissent.
   Another approved amendment calls for reopening a major tax break
for oil and gas producers. Currently, ``intangible drilling costs''
can greatly reduce an independent producer's taxes. But the
so-called alternative minimum tax can wipe out much of that
benefit, by forcing the producers to forego the deduction _ a
change made in the 1986 tax law.
   The platform plank calls for reversing that provision, in effect
reopening the loophole that was estimated in 1986 to cost the
Treasury up to $1 billion a year.
   The change, sponsored by Rick Montoya of New Mexico, was
approved by a voice vote.
   Charles Black, a Bush campaign liaison to the committee, told
reporters that the draft platform shows that ``George Bush is
running as a conservative, running on the policies (conservatives)
have promoted through Ronald Reagan over these eight years.''
   ``We have an opponent who is running from issues, who has
stipulated he's not running on issues, but on competence or some
kind of personal characteristics. So it's very important for George
Bush to have a platform that goes into detail on where we want to
take the country,'' Black said.
   The most hotly contested issue was Wednesday's 55-32 vote not to
change a line in the anti-abortion plank that declares: ``We
believe the unborn child has a fundamental individual right to life
which cannot be infringed.''
   Marjorie Bell Chambers of Los Alamos, N.M., who tried to strike
the last four words, said Thursday she would not seek to gather the
27 signatures needed to press a minority plank on that issue.
   She said she ``did not want to cause problems for the Bush
campaign with a floor fight'' even though she said the language
``smacks of some fanaticism.''
   By voice, the delegates on Wednesday also rejected an amendment
to allow Medicaid funding of abortion in cases of rape or incest,
and they refused to expand an AIDS plank to endorse all the
recommendations of a presidential commission.
   Black said Bush has endorsed the commission's call for
legislation to protect the rights of AIDS patients, but not the
entire report. President Reagan did not support the commission's
call for new anti-discrimination legislation.
   Sen. Robert Kasten of Wisconsin, co-chairman of the platform
committee, said GOP moderates got a chance to air their arguments
and ``made a clear impact on the platform'' in such areas as
committing the GOP to work toward catastrophic health care for
children _ a Weicker proposal that passed 53-30 Wednesday after the
senator assured delegates ``there would be no financial
commitment.''
   On other issues, Kasten said, ``they had clear opportunities and
they were defeated.'' Like Orr, Kasten said he does not expect any
minority planks.
   ``No one felt that their rights were trampled on,'' Kasten said.
   The delegates approved an amendment urging local school
districts to ``recognize the value of kindergarten and
pre-kindergarten programs.''
   That language irked some conservative delegates.
   Bunny Chambers of Oklahoma City said, ``We need to keep our
children in the home, with their mothers.'' Marylin Shannon of
Salem, Ore., said, ``I can't imagine Republicans wanting to saddle
public schools with the day care business.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
