<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Seals     08-11 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Seals,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disease Killing Harbor Seals Also Affecting Gray Seals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Dead Seals Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A virus that has killed thousands of harbor
seals in North Sea coastal waters also is affecting gray seals,
Swedish researchers said Thursday.
   An emaciated female gray seal at least 20 years old was found
dead last Sunday at Sibbarp, south of Malmo on Sweden's southwest
coast.
   Swedish experts said an autopsy showed the same lung damage as
in the harbor seals. They said another dead gray seal found later
near Ystad, farther south, has yet to be examined.
   ``The pneumonia suffered by this animal, which I judged had been
dead about 24 hours, is characteristic,'' said Dr. Anders Bergman,
the Uppsala veterinarian who performed the autopsy. ``We still hold
a hope however that various individuals of gray seals are more or
less resistant.
   ``It would seem to be the same type of virus. ... If we get in a
young one too, I am afraid we have a new disaster on our hands.
There is an obvious risk it will also spread to the third species
in our waters, the ringed seal.'' A similar gray seal case was
found in Denmark and researchers said material for comparison was
being sent to Sweden.
   Gray seals in the Baltic Sea and Bothnian Gulf are believed to
number 1,000-2,000, but only a few remain in the south Baltic
because of increasing chemical pollution of the waters.
</TEXT>
