<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-11 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Swelters In Heat, Humidity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the nation broiled under 90-degree weather Thursday,
with the East enduring high humidity as well. Remnants of tropical
storm Beryl soaked the Louisiana and Texas coasts.
   The temperature in Philadelphia climbed to 90 degrees Thursday
afternoon for the 44th time this summer. The summer of 1983 held
the previous record with 41 days of 90 degrees or higher in 110
years of recorded weather history.
   The oppressive heat and humidity stretched from southern New
England to Maryland and over much of Indiana and Illinois. The heat
brought pleas from an Albany, N.Y., utility for customers to cut
back their electricity use to avoid blackouts.
   Six inches of rain fell Thursday at Cushing, Texas, and 2 to 4
inches of rain fell in parts of northwest Louisiana Thursday
morning. Flash flood warnings were posted in northeast Texas.
   In the Houston area, thunderstorms produced heavy rain early
Thursday afternoon. Over an inch of rain fell in the northern part
of Harris County and street flooding was reported.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the
south Atlantic coastal states across the central and southern
Appalachians to the Great Lakes region. Scattered showers also
developed over New England.
   Lightning struck and killed a boater in northwest Minnesota. In
Wisconsin, wind gusts to 50 mph and pea-size hail was reported at
Ripon in the east-central part of the state. Thunderstorm winds
downed trees at Eden, Wis.
   Thunderstorms developed around midday in northwest Arizona and
southwest Utah. Thunderstorm gusts reached 63 mph at Milford, Utah.
   Skies were mostly sunny Thursday afternoon over the northern and
central Plains. Temperatures reached over 100 degrees in portions
of South Dakota.
   Skies were sunny in the Pacific Northwest where temperatures
were on the pleasant side. It was 65 degrees in Seattle at noon.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 104 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.,
and Phoeniz, Ariz. Thursday's low in the nation was 35 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Record-high temperatures were set in Beckley, W. Va., 88;
Binghamton, N.Y., 87; Buffalo, N.Y., 92; and Bridgeport, Conn., 92.
   Friday's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the Gulf Coast northward to eastern Kansas, southern Missouri,
the Ohio Valley and eastern portions of the Great Lakes region.
   Showers and thunderstorms were predicted for southwest Missouri,
eastern Oklahoma and western Arkansas. Widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms were forecast for portions of New England and the New
York City area. Widely scattered thunderstorms were also expected
to develop from the northern Great Lakes to North Dakota, and from
the Rockies to the mountains of Arizona.
   High temperatures were forecast in the upper 80s and 90s across
most of the nation; in the lower 80s from northern Michigan to
northern Minnesota; in the 70s and low 80s over the Pacific
Northwest and along the Pacific Coast. Temperatures between 95 and
110 degrees were predicted for the Dakotas and in the desert
Southwest.
</TEXT>
