<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     08-11 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholics, Protestants Bury Their Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Roman Catholic youth gunned
down by Protestant guerrillas and a British soldier killed by an
IRA bomb were buried Thursday, both victims of Northern Ireland's
sectarian violence.
   A funeral was held here for Seamus Morris, 18, one of two men
fatally shot Monday in north Belfast. The Protestant Action Force,
a paramilitary group, claimed responsibility for the deaths.
   Bishop Cahal Daly, Roman Catholic bishop of Down and Connor,
said in remarks at Morris' funeral that all Catholics in Northern
Ireland are now potential targets for paramilitary killers.
   ``Any Catholic at random in a Catholic street is a target,''
Daly said. ``Any member of the public happening to be at business
in a Catholic street at the time is a potential victim.
   ``It is a matter of great urgency that better protection be
provided by the security authorities for exposed Catholic
enclaves.''
   Morris, a student, and Peter Dolan, a 25-year-old beer
deliveryman who was buried Wednesday, were shot by gunmen who drove
into the Catholic Ardoyne area of north Belfast. They were killed
in broad daylight in a shopping district.
   Sinn Fein, the Irish Republican Army's legal political front,
has rejected suggestions that the killings were in retaliation for
a renewed IRA campaign against British targets that killed six
people last week.
   In London, a British army soldier killed Aug. 1 in an IRA
bombing was buried Thursday with full military honors and amid
tight security.
   Lance Cpl. Mickey Robbins' funeral was held in a military chapel
just 200 yards from where the bomb exploded in the Inglis Barracks
in north London. The funeal was guarded by soldiers armed with
machine guns who checked all mourners and even searched the cars of
senior army officers attending.
   Robbins' commander, Col. Peter Westcott, praised the 23-year-old
soldier ``who was deliberately murdered by terrorists whilst
sleeping peacefully in his bed.''
   The IRA wants to oust Britain from the predominantly Protestant
province of Northern Ireland and unite it with the Catholic Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
