<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-CommunistParty     08-11 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Communist Party,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Expels 109,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's Communist Party, which has 47 million
members, expelled or forced the resignation of 109,000 members last
year in a drive to clean up the party's sullied reputation, it was
reported Thursday.
   An official of the party's Organization Department, in an
interview with the state-run Xinhua News Agency, said 20,000 party
members were expelled. Xinhua said in its report that the number
included 30 senior officials ranked higher than the prefectural, or
state, level.
   It said the number of removals was the largest in recent years,
and showed the party's determination to root out corruption.
   The report noted that party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang
earlier this year said those who abuse their powers and extort
money, embezzle and betray the nation's interests must be
mercilessly removed from the party.
   Xinhua said most of those expelled were involved in smuggling,
bribery, embezzlement or violations concerning foreign affairs or
foreign nationals.
   The party's Discipline Inspection Commission, responding to
widespread complaints about corruption among party officials,
recently has issued regulations on the business dealings of party
officials.
   Xinhua claimed the party continued to enjoy high prestige among
the Chinese people. It said more than 8 million people applied to
join last year.
</TEXT>
