<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-SAfrica     08-11 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-SAfrica,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consul, 3 Others Expelled for Visa Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African Consul Dirk de Wet
and three of his countrymen were ordered expelled Thursday by the
Foreign Ministry for violating visa conditions.
   The three men _ Germt Olivier, Ismail Richards and Bennet Ndlazi
_ applied for visas to visit Argentina for talks with the consul,
according to the government news agency Telam. Instead, they
participated in a public seminar organized by the consulate, it
said.
   The topic of the seminar was not disclosed.
   Argentina in 1986 lowered the level of its diplomatic relations
with South Africa from embassy status to a consulate because of
apartheid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
