<DOCNO> AP880811-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Rebuttal     08-11 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Rebuttal,400</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese on Thursday
criticized two of his former top aides, who resigned their
positions and offered embarassing congressional testimony about the
outgoing attorney general.
   Meese's lawyers struck back at Arnold I. Burns and William F.
Weld in a 69-page statement filed with the Senate Judiciary
Committee _ where both men testified July 26.
   Attorneys Nathan Lewin and James E. Rocap III said their
statement was issued on behalf of Meese, whose ethical conduct was
investigated by Independent Counsel James McKay.
   McKay concluded Meese ``probably'' broke two tax laws and twice
violated a federal conflict-of-interest statute _ but he declined
to prosecute the attorney general.
   Weld, who resigned March 29 as chief of the criminal division,
told the committee that he resigned in protest after telling Meese
he had probably broken the law.
   Weld's conclusion was ``shocking and wrong,'' the rebuttal
statement said, because it was premised on statements containing
``distortions, inaccuracies and material omissions that completely
undermine his opinion.''
   And Burns _ ranked second to Meese as deputy attorney general _
testified he quit at the same time because of a ``deep malaise'' at
the department. He described Meese as living in ``a world of Alice
in Wonderland'' about his problems.
   The rebuttal statement mainly addressed Weld's testimony that if
Meese were an ordinary citizen, he probably would have been
prosecuted for taking gratuities from his longtime friend E. Robert
Wallach.
   The statement said McKay ``concluded that Mr. Meese was telling
the truth when he denied that any alleged benefits given to him by
Mr. Wallach were provided on account of any offiical actions.
   ``Mr. Weld neither heard the testimony nor read the grand jury
transcript. How can he in good faith assert publicly that there had
been a criminal violation of federal law without considering the
most direct and compelling evidence of Mr. Meese's state of mind _
his own sworn testimony in answer to the prosecutor's questions.''
   The statement said Burns' testimony about low department morale
was ``fully and convincingly repudiated'' by the acting
replacements for Burns and Weld, and a third department official.
   The three are Harold Christensen, acting deputy attorney
general; Francis A. Keating II, acting associate attorney general;
and Edward S.G. Dennis Jr. acting chief of the criminal division.
   ``Nothing of substance remains of Mr. Burns' testimony,'' the
statement said. ``His Alice in Wonderland metaphor had a 12-hour
life; it was broadcast on the evening and morning network news.''
</TEXT>
