<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AudiSettlement     08-11 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Audi Settlement,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Proposed Audi Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed settlement in a class-action lawsuit
that contended Audi 5000 sedans were defective and subject to
sudden accelerationed was thrown out Thursday by a judge.
   The proposed settlement offered rebates of $300 to $2,000 to
390,000 current or former owners who buy another Audi. Under the
settlement, Audi would acknowledge no liability.
   ``It puts people in a position where they have to buy an Audi to
reap any benefit,'' said Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas Rakowski.
``Clearly, it's a settlement that I couldn't live with.''
   Rakowski recommended that both sides try to negotiate another
settlement and he set another hearing for Aug. 31, officials said.
   Rakowski's action vacates an earlier order by another judge who
gave preliminary approval to the settlement before removing himself
from the case due to a conflict of interest.
   The case stems from a 1987 class-action lawsuit filed by a group
of Audi owners alleging the Audi 5000s with automatic transmissions
were defective because of sudden acceleration problems. The
settlement would have applied to owners of Audi 5000s built between
1978 and 1986.
   Thursday's ruling was praised by attorney Stephen Nassau, who
represents the Washington-based Audi Victims Network, a group of
Audi owners who contend their cars had sudden acceleration
problems. The group opposed the settlement.
   Joseph Bennett, national spokesman for Audi of America Inc.
based in Troy, Mich., said the automaker was disappointed by
Rakowski's decision.
   ``We're disappointed because better than 99{ percent of the Audi
owners out there apparently felt that (the settlement) was quite
fair,'' said Bennett, referring to the response to settlement
notices sent to Audi owners.
   Bennett said Audi had not decided whether to seek another
settlement or let the lawsuit go to trial.
   Circuit Judge Harold Siegan had given preliminary approval to
the settlement, but removed himself in July because of his
friendship with an attorney in the case.
   Siegan said he hadn't taken any evidence and said he thought
that his order should be vacated by the new judge, according to a
motion filed by Nassau.
   The Center for Auto Safety contends that at least 16,50
accidents, causing 402 injuries and five deaths, have been linked
to acceleration surges when an Audi 5000 was shifted from into gear
from park.
</TEXT>
