<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill 2ndLd-Writethru a0682 08-11 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0682,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ruptured Barge Spilling Oil Off Mississippi Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with leak stopped, 2,000 gallons spilled,
quotes, reduction in size of tanks. Deletes outdated material. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GULFPORT, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil barge struck a sunken barge early
Thursday, spilling more than 2,000 gallons of oil into the water
off the Mississippi coast before the leak was stopped, officials
said.
   Authorities were watching the movement of a two-mile oil slick
threatening barrier island beaches.
   ``The slick is tending to break up and it may not impact the
islands or the Mississippi coastline,'' said Eleana Turner of the
Mississippi Bureau of Pollution Control. ``The sun is evaporating a
lot of the oil, so things are looking pretty good.''
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Bob Morehead said late Thursday that
inspections showed the oil slick to be very light crude.
   ``Right now, based on the consistency of the oil and the
resources available, things are pretty much under control,''
Morehead said. ``If things stay the same, it looks like it's going
to reach the islands.''
   Cmdr. Donald Stansell of the Coast Guard's Mobile, Ala., office,
said an estimated 2,000 gallons of oil had spilled during the first
few hours after the barge was ruptured about 4:25 a.m. Thursday.
   Equipment was dispatched to remove as much oil as possible from
the water. Officials fear the slick could reach the popular beaches
of Cat or Ship islands, about 10 miles offshore, said Coast Guard
Capt. William Loefstedt.
   ``We hope to prevent damage if possible,'' he said. ``But things
change if the wind comes up and the direction of the oil slick
changes.''
   The barge was owned by Tenn-Tom Towing of Mobile, Ala., and was
being towed to a refinery in Louisiana, said Stansell. Stansell
said the amount of oil spilled so far classified the accident as
relatively minor.
   The accident occurred when the barge scraped over the top of a
barge laden with scrap iron that had sunk earlier in the week when
Tropical Storm Beryl hit, Loefstedt said. The accident occurred
near the Gulfport ship channel, between the coast and the barrier
islands.
   The damaged tanks on the oil barge held 8,600 barrels of oil, or
more than 270,900 gallons.
   Thursday afternoon, Turner said the oil barge had been lifted
off the submerged barge without any significant increase in the
amount of leaking crude.
</TEXT>
