<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LastTemptation 1stLd-Writethru a0791 08-11 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0791,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Mount Demonstration on Eve of Film Opening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, `The fundamentalists' ... with
Scorsese's defense of the film; SUBS 12th graf, `Both have .. .
with 2 grafs to ADD Wildmon's quote.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA12.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of demonstrators lugged
crosses and picket signs to the gates of Universal Studios on
Thursday to protest ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' on the eve of
the film's release.
   In Washington, the conservative religious lobby Moral Majority
condemned the Martin Scorsese-directed film as ``an utter
blasphemy'' and pledged a boycott of Universal, the movie's
distributor and related companies.
   The movie, which opens Friday in seven U.S. cities and Toronto,
stars Willem Dafoe, Barbara Hershey and Harvey Keitel. Based on the
1955 novel by Nikos Kazantzakis, it differs with the Biblical
account of Jesus' life.
   The fundamentalists' fury has focused on Scorsese's portrayal of
Jesus as an uncertain, ambivalent savior. In a hallucinatory dream
sequence while dying on the cross, Scorsese's Christ imagines
abandoning his divinity to live as an ordinary mortal, and
fantasizes about sex with Mary Magdalene.
   Scorsese has defended his film, saying it is intended as a
thought-provoking work of art derived from a novel that focuses on
the humanity of Jesus and the worldly temptations he faced.
   In London, a Roman Catholic official called Thursday for viewers
to boycott the film.
   ``People ought to show a bit of restraint and not give in to
curiosity,'' said Nicholas Coote, assistant general secretary of
the Catholic Bishops of England and Wales. ``Can we just for once
not wallow in bad taste?''
   A spokesman for the Church of England, John Miles, said the
church's Board of Social Responsibility will want to see the film,
but until it did, the church could not comment.
   Police said a crowd of 25,000 joined the Hollywood protest,
coordinated by the American Family Association, Trinity Broadcast
Network and other conservative Christians. It caused huge traffic
jams around Universal Studios.
   Joyce Walker, 34, said she came to the demonstration at the
direction of the PTL Television ministry. ``I may go see the
movie,'' Ms. Walker said. ``I'm still curious, but I don't like the
sex scenes with Jesus.''
   Among participants in the noon demonstration were Rev. Donald
Wildmon, director of the American Family Association of Tupelo,
Miss., and Bill Bright, president of the Campus Crusade for Christ
in Arrowhead Springs, Calif.
   ``We have come to tell this company that although you may not
respect our religion, you will respect us in the marketplace,''
Wildmon told the crowd.
   Bright and Wildmon have emerged as prominent critics of the
film. Bright has offered to raise $10 million to buy and burn the
film, and Wildmon has urged a nationwide boycott of MCA.
   Moral Majority president Jerry C. Nims said in a statement from
his Washington office that he was calling for a nationwide boycott
of Universal Pictures and other subsidiaries of MCA Inc.,
Universal's parent company.
   ``Regardless of what this movie claims to be, `The Last
Temptation of Christ' appears to be utter blasphemy,'' Nims said in
a letter to MCA chairman Lew Wasserman, accusing MCA and its
officials of ``privately and personally profiting from the
blaspheming of our Saviour.''
   Nims said the boycott also would apply to Xerox Corp. and Pepsi
Co. because some members of their boards of directors also serve on
MCA's board. Nims' spokesman, Jake Hansen, said the Moral Majority
leader has not seen the movie.
   Conservative Reps. William E. Dannemeyer, R-Calif., Robert K.
Dornan, R-Calif., and Clyde Holloway, R-La., added their
denunciations late Wednesday in Congress, calling the movie
``scurrilous'' and ``blasphemous.''
   While it has been difficult to assess the economic effect of the
MCA boycott, several theater chains have decided against showing
the film, including the huge General Cinema Theaters based in
Buffalo, N.Y.
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' is scheduled to open to the
public Friday in Los Angeles, Chicago, Washington, San Francisco,
Seattle, Minneapolis, New York City and Toronto.
</TEXT>
