<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDEmbezzler 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AID Embezzler, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0621,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former AID Employee Pleads Guilty To Embezzling $1.2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs:subs 9th graf pvs ``Burns admitted to CORRECT amount of taxes
owed, Pickup 10th graf pvs ``According to</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Agency for International Development
financial officer on Thursday admitted embezzling $1.2 million from
the government and agreed to forfeit the house, cars and luxury
items he bought with the money.
   William J. Burns, 48, entered guilty pleas to felony charges of
embezzlement, filing false claims and attempted tax evasion before
U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson. She set sentencing for
Oct. 11.
   Burns admitted that during a six-year period starting in 1982,
he signed false forms authorizing the Treasury Department to pay
travel reimbursement checks to a fictitious individual named
Vincent Kauffman, for whom Burns opened a bank account.
   Burns, who earned $35,108 a year as a financial manager for the
foreign aid agency, transferred the money to his own bank account
by writing checks to himself and signing Kauffman's name.
   The money was used to purchase ``a house, car, furs, trips,
jewels and other personal luxury items for Mr. Burns and his
family,'' Justice Department prosecutor James Cole said.
   The judge reminded Burns that he could receive a 20-year
sentence for the three convictions and fined up to $500,000.
   But prosecutors said that according to sentencing guidelines
implemented last year, Burns could be sentenced to a term of 2{
years to three years and one month without parole.
   According to the plea agreement, Burns or federal prosecutors
could withdraw from the deal if the probation department calculates
a different sentence under the guidelines, which take into account
a defendant's criminal background.
   Burns admitted filing two false claim forms in June for more
than $56,000. Burns also pleaded guilty to a charge that he failed
to report any of the money he embezzled as income to avoid paying
taxes of $475,685.
   According to the plea agreement, Burns agreed to surrender his
$300,000 house in Burtonsville, Md., and all the possessions and
property he bought with the money.
   Burns' wife, Kathy, will be allowed to keep a car and $10,000
and necessary household goods ``to get a start in life with her two
children,'' Cole told the judge.
   Prosecutors agreed not to bring any charges against Mrs. Burns
``if any would be appropriate,'' Cole said.
   Burns and his attorney, David Addis, left the U.S. Courthouse
without commenting on the case.
   Urging Johnson to allow Burns to remain free on $500,000 bond,
Addis argued Burns won't jump bail. ``He has a family, he has two
children, he knows he has injured them terribly. He is not going to
do anything to compound that.''
   The judge allowed Burns to remain free on bond pending
sentencing.
   As part of the plea agreement, Burns and his wife agreed to give
government investigators a full accounting of their assets. Burns
agreed to make up the difference between the money the government
collects from selling his property and the amount he stole.
   He also faces civil tax penalties, Cole said.
   Burns also agreed to cooperate with a continuing investigation,
Cole said. Investigators determined there was an unspecified amount
of additional money taken in a related embezzlement scheme, Cole
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
