<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-Reagan'sFarewell Adv14-1stLd-Writethru b0622 08-11 1053</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Reagan's Farewell, Adv 14-1st Ld-Writethru, b0622,1075</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>President's Farewell Won't Steal Bush's Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Subs 8th graf, bgng So the GOP to UPDATE with brief
Reagan-Bush airport meeting; CORRECTS next to last graf, bgng ``I'm
sure xxx to make it read xxx who now runs etc. (runs sted funds).</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With an actor's grace and a politician's
flair, President Reagan's farewell to the party he returned to the
White House is designed to avoid stealing the show from the new
standardbearer, George Bush.
   Reagan himself insisted on delivering his speech to the
Republican National Convention on Monday instead of later in the
week, where it might draw attention from Bush, officials say.
   If the two men appear together in New Orleans this week, it will
only be briefly.
   ``This is his (Reagan's) swan song. The convention will be awash
with nostalgia,'' says Rep. Guy Vander Jagt, head of the National
Republican Congressional Committee. ``But it has to end on a note
of looking to the future, sending off the man we hope will be
president for the next eight years.''
   It will be an emotional time for the man who appeared in several
motion pictures, hosted ``Death Valley Days'' and ``GE Theater''
and burst onto the national scene during the 1964 convention that
nominated Sen. Barry Goldwater of Arizona for president.
   Reagan, who led the GOP to the White House in 1980 in a bitter
defeat for President Jimmy Carter, faces a bittersweet transition
as a 77-year-old president with little beyond Bush's election on
his remaining agenda. In retirement, he plans to speak for repeal
of the 22nd Amendment limiting presidents to two terms.
   The White House gave Reagan the leading role he rarely got as a
Hollywood actor. And he's relished this attention. But a
performer's feel for stage positioning convinced Reagan that Bush
must stand without him for Thursday's climatic convention moments,
party and campaign officials say.
   So the GOP passed up the chance to have the nation see Bush
hoist his arms in a unity show with Reagan. However, presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said tentative plans call for Reagan and
Bush to meet on Tuesday at Belle Chase Naval Air Station, as Reagan
is leaving the convention city and Bush is arriving.
   Republican Party Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf, talking of Reagan's
Monday night speech, said, ``I think we're going to see a very
proud man _ proud of the accomplishments of the last seven years.''
   ``Ronald Reagan at his age looks as good if not better than he
did when he came into office,'' Fahrenkopf said. ``Ronald Reagan is
an individual who knows who he is and is comfortable with who he
is. That's why, in many ways, Ronald Reagan doesn't have an ego
problem.''
   A source who participated in talks about the presidential role
in New Orleans, discussing a conversation on grounds of anonymity,
said Reagan at one point this spring argued forcefully about which
day he would speak.
   ``Initially it was penciled in that he would do the speech on
Tuesday night,'' this source said. ``But he realizes that wherever
he goes, he's the focus of media attention. This was his decision.
He said, `I don't want to do it Tuesday. I want to do it Monday.'''
   Gov. Thomas Kean's keynote address was thus put off until
Tuesday, as party strategists sought to make Reagan's valedictory
and Bush's coming out party politically compatible and graceful.
   Mitchell Daniels, White House political adviser in earlier
Reagan years, said ``no one is more conscious of the need for this
to be a George Bush convention than Ronald Reagan.''
   ``He'll be very comfortable with the balance that has been
struck,'' said Daniels, a Hudson Institute scholar who's going to
the convention as a delegate from Indiana. ``A lesser man would
have insisted on a bigger share of the limelight.''
   Said Vander Jagt, R-Mich., ``The challenge is to make `Hello!'
to George Bush as exciting as `Goodbye!' to Ronald Reagan.''
   From a variety of Republican sources, declining to be named
publicly, the Reagan itinerary in New Orleans will go like this:
   The president and his wife Nancy will arrive on Sunday, have
dinner with several members of the family and renew some political
acquaintances. On Monday, Mrs. Reagan will be the guest of honor at
a luncheon being organized by the president's daughter, Maureen
Reagan. On Monday night, former Sen. Paul Laxalt, R-Nev., will
deliver a testimonial to his longtime friend. Mrs. Reagan will
precede her husband on the podium, speaking briefly to the 2,277
convention delegates.
   After that, there will be a film presentation on the Reagan
presidency. The president will arrive on the podium while delegates
are watching the film in darkness, to await his reception when the
lights go back on.
   He'll address a fund-raising breakfast away from the convention
hotel Tuesday morning and then head to his vacation ranch in the
Santa Ynez Mountains of California.
   Reagan, who reminded the 1984 Dallas convention it was ``the
last time'' he would address such a gathering as a candidate, has
said people should be able to elect a president as often as they
wish.
   But he also has said he was never interested in a seeking a
third term.
   James David Barber, a Duke University presidential scholar, said
the mood at the New Orleans convention will likely be cheerful, but
also nostalgic.
   ``Nancy's counsel to him (Reagan) will be that, `This is the
last major speech that he'll make in a power situation, and
therefore it should be the best,'' Barber speculated. He said that
Mrs. Reagan seems to have ``a fundamental concern'' with how
history will judge her husband.
   ``There'll be a lot of cheers, a lot of tears'' when Reagan
speaks, said Donald Devine, a former head of the Office of
Personnel Management who now runs Citizens For America, a
self-styled grass-roots Reagan organization.
   ``I'm sure what's going on in their mind is, they don't want
Ronald Reagan to steal the scene, and that's a legitimate
consideration,'' Devine said. ``I think at first the president was
a little bit hesitant (about warmly embracing Bush's candidacy),
but I have do doubt that they are working together now.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Tucker Adv14   08-11 1111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Tucker, Adv 14,1139</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Man and His Dream: An Interview With the Filmmakers of
``Tucker''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They could scarcely be more different: one
with neatly trimmed hair and beard and a boy's figure,
quiet-spoken, thoughtful; the other with the unkempt look of a
struggling artist, an impetuous man with a loud laugh and hearty
appetites, as evidenced by his belly.
   They are George Lucas and Francis Coppola, respectively. Along
with Steven Spielberg, they are the titans of American film in the
post-major studio era. Despite their outward differences, Lucas,
42, and Coppola, 49, have been friends and often partners for two
decades, after meeting in film school in the late 1960s.
   Both conduct their operations outside of Hollywood, in the San
Francisco Bay area. And both have created landmark films: Lucas
with the ``Star Wars'' trilogy; Coppola with ``The Godfather''
epics.
   Now Lucas has produced, and Coppola has directed, ``Tucker: The
Man and His Dream,'' which Paramount released this weekend. The $24
million saga, starring Jeff Bridges in the title role, is a true
story that obviously appealed to both filmmakers: A gifted
entrepreneur challenges the Establishment. He was Preston Tucker,
whose postwar attempt to market an innovative car ended in failure,
partly because of pressure from the Big Three automakers _ Ford,
General Motors and Chrysler.
   Coppola had mulled the Tucker idea over the years but always was
sidetracked with other projects. At one point he even considered
doing it as a musical.
   ``Tucker'' is not the first collaboration between Lucas and
Coppola. Lucas worked as Coppola's assistant on ``The Rain People''
in 1969, which was filmed on a five-month trip across the United
States. Coppola's Zoetrope company produced Lucas' science fiction
``THX 1138'' in 1970, which was not a success.
   Lucas was unable to find a studio for ``American Graffiti'' in
1973. Then Coppola hit big with ``The Godfather.'' Universal agree
to back ``Graffiti'' if Coppola would produce. Over the years they
have combined on other projects, including Akira Kurosawa's
``Kagemusha'' and Disneyland's ``Captain EO.''
   Coppola and Lucas recently talked about their collaboration with
The Associated Press. Here are highlights from that interview:
   Q. When did you first become intrigued with the Preston Tucker
saga?
   Coppola: It was a project I brought with me from college (UCLA).
I first learned about it by being one of the kids in those crowds
(looking at the car) depicted in the movie. My dad took me to see
it, and I was very disheartened when I heard the car wasn't going
to come out. I couldn't understand it. I said, ``It's a good car.
Why won't they let him make it?'' My father said, ``Oh, they won't
let him buy steel.''
   Lucas: Francis has talked to me about it over the years. Then
one time we were talking about movies, and I told him (``Tucker'')
could really be great. Eventually, he called and asked if I would
be interested in producing it. I said yes. Absolutely.
   We started on the screenplay with Arnold Schulman. Once we got a
script finished, I started taking it to the studios. Everybody
turned it down. It didn't fit into one of their little pigeonholes
of what they thought commercial movies were. If it doesn't fit one
of those little slots, they don't know what to do with it _ that,
combined with the expense.
   If that had been a $15 million movie, they would have said, ``We
don't understand this movie but we'll do it anyway because big
names are connected with it.'' We said we'd love to make it for $15
million but we can't. We have cars and factories and period
costumes and crowd scenes. Add that up and you have a big budget.
   Q. How many Tuckers do you own?
   Coppola: I have two, and he has two. My deal with the company
was that they could have my cars free of charge if they fixed them
up, made them beautiful _ and they did.
   Lucas: My deal was that we had all those cars there, and I was
able to buy two. I had to have as many as Francis did.
   Q. ``Tucker'' has a number of directorial touches, such as
angled shots and having both sides of a telephone conversation on
the screen at the same time. How did you arrive at the style?
   Coppola: I thought in the spirit of the car, which was a kind of
Rube Goldberg contraption, that the movie ought to have the same
flavor. Why make a movie about an innovative car unless you can do
those things in movie terms?
   Since Tucker was traveling a lot, I knew there would be a lot of
phone scenes. Normally, you shoot phone scenes separately. I
thought the actors would do better playing with each other. (Such
devices) are all in the wonderful studio tradition. As you know,
I've always been a fan of the Hollywood studio tradition and want
to see it continue. I'm always sad when I hear they have sold a
studio or dismantled a studio. They are assets that should be
preserved.
   Q. Both of you have worked outside the mainstream of the film
industry. Is there a parallel between your own careers and Tucker's?
   Lucas: I think one of the main themes of the movie is that
regardless whether a project succeeds or fails, the ideas that you
bring to it can live on. If you can keep your creative spirit
alive, that's what is really important. You must persevere over
adversity even if the projects you're working on don't work out.
You have to go on and do it again.
   That's one of the main themes in the film, and one of the main
themes for us personally. We've had to go through it time and time
again in order to get innovative ideas into movies. Every time we
get an idea like ``Tucker'' they'll say . . .
   Coppola: They'll say, ``No, it's not like anything we ever saw.
We don't want it.'' But then they'll copy it afterwards.
   Lucas: You go through that whole process every time. Whether the
project itself is successful, you have generated a lot of new
ideas. . . . It's the perseverence of the creative spirit that is
really important.
   Q. What did you learn from your first work together, ``The Rain
People''?
   Coppola: We realized you could make pictures anywhere. We
decided we were going to make films and be independent and use new
methods.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
