<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:Tucker'sFamily Adv14   08-11 1034</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Tucker's Family, Adv 14,1064</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Movie Revives Memories In Tucker Hometown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YPSILANTI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie ``Tucker: The Man and His
Dream,'' has many people looking back at the postwar years, when
industrial dreams came true in the factory town.
   Preston Tucker's biggest venture _ a sleek, ahead-of-its-time
automobile that challenged the antiquated designs of the major
automakers _ was launched in 1946. It collapsed in 1949.
   The memory is still vivid for Mary Lee McAndrew, Tucker's
daughter, who at age 20 christened the first prototype car _
informally dubbed the Tucker Torpedo _ with a splash of champagne
in a June 1947 unveiling.
   McAndrew worked with director Francis Coppola while the film was
made. She recalled the days of traveling with her father to a
whirlwind of meetings with potential investors, dealers and others
at Chicago, Washington and New York hotels.
   Her ranch-style house, shaded by trees and overlooking the
Washtenaw Country Club's rolling fairways, is a few miles west of
the white house with its wide, pillared porch where Tucker and his
wife, Vera, lived with their five children, a menagerie of pets and
the ubiquitous cars.
   A few miles in the other direction, lives 78-year-old Daniel
Leabu. He was one of a handful of machinists and mechanics who
built the first four Tucker engines in a barn behind the Tucker
house.
   Leabu recalled the rush job: ``I was out there till two or three
o'clock in the morning, getting chicken, anything, just to keep
them working.''
   But too young to remember the rise and fall of the Tucker
automobile was Preston's grandson John Tucker, a 36-year-old store
designer.
   ``I was only 4 years old when he died,'' he said. ``About the
only thing I remember is sitting on his knee the summer before he
died. And I remember the energy that always went on around that
house.''
   Tucker's project started in boom times for Ypsilanti, about 35
miles west of Detroit. Not far from Leabu's house, Bomber Street is
a reminder of the round-the-clock production of bomber planes in a
plant operated by Henry Ford. Tucker's Ypsilanti Machine & Tool
Co., also thrived.
   Born in Capac, Mich., in 1903, Tucker grew up in the Lincoln
Park area south of Detroit. He worked as a policeman, and later
sold cars in Memphis, Tenn., and Indianapolis, before moving to
Ypsilanti.
   His company made a rotating ball gun-turret, designed for a fast
combat car devised by Tucker but actually used in airplanes.
   Building autos after the war came naturally, McAndrew said of
her father: ``All of his life he was into cars, from the first time
he saw one.''
   To manufacture his car, Tucker leased a mammoth plant near
Cicero, Ill., that produced aircraft engines during the war. The
plant is now a vast shopping mall, where observances are being held
in connection with the movie.
   He bought a company that made helicopter engines that could be
adapted to power the car. That was the job of Leabu and his crew.
In the movie, he is a character named Eddie.
   Tucker's house has been converted to apartments, and there are
cars parked in back. But the barn still stands, and Leabu recently
took a visitor there.
   ``This is where we started the first engine,'' he said in the
old barn. ``We hung a fuel tank from the ceiling, and hooked up a
battery, and it started. That was the most beautiful noise I ever
heard.''
   In 1948, the Tucker cars created a stir. They were capable of
going 120 miles an hour and, driven more economically, getting 30
miles to the gallon.
   Startling at the time were the rear-engine design, aerodynamic
styling, safety features such as seat belts, padded dash and
pop-out windows, and blue, maroon, silver and other brilliant
colors.
   Only 50 cars were built before pressure from the big automakers
and money problems collapsed the enterprise. A federal
investigation ended with Tucker's acquittal of fraud charges in a
1950 trial, but word of the probe had long since dried up funds.
   Jack Miller, a dealer in antique Hudson automobiles, said Tucker
might have been brought down regardless, by the same economic
forces that swallowed up other small auto companies such as Kaiser,
Nash, Hudson, Willys, Studebaker and Packard.
   ``People thought maybe he was going a little too fast,'' the
antique car dealer said.
   Leabu said Tucker might have had an edge others lacked. ``We had
something nobody ever had before, right at a point when the others
were getting retooled,'' he said. ``We needed a little more money
to get it across.
   ``He was one of the most ingenious men I've ever met.''
   Leabu's desk is full of memorabilia _ brass badges plant
employees wore, keys to Tucker cars and copies of Tucker Topics,
house organ of the short-lived plant.
   After his empire fell, Tucker returned to Ypsilanti and
continued running the machine and tool company. By the time Tucker
died of cancer in 1956, he had made several trips to Brazil to plan
the manufacture there of a car he called the Carioca.
   While the movie was being shot, Coppola often had children and
grandchildren around the set; therefore, he could understand the
boisterous, close-knit Tucker tribe that romped through the Park
Street house.
   ``We were all happy. We were a very loving family. The house was
full of people all the time, relatives, friends. We were
teen-agers, so we had all our friends,'' McAndrew said.
   There were pets, too, at one time including two cows, a pony and
a pig that were all trooped to a nearby pond to be soaped up and
washed down. ``We'd take the pony and the pig and everything,'' she
said. ``We had a ball. Dad was the first one in and the last one
out.''
   Vera Tucker, now 86 and living in Arizona, liked the film. ``She
thought it caught the spirit of the family very well, and my
father's magnetic spirit,'' her daughter said.
   She told Coppola during filming: ``My father is looking down on
this and smiling.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
