<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:TuckerCollecting Adv14   08-11 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Tucker Collecting, Adv 14,0667</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Revolutionary, Ill-Fated Tucker Automobile a Collector's Dream</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rare Tucker automobile, featuring a
spaceship design, roaming cyclops headlamp and rear-mounted engine,
is becoming a hot item for collectors with the release of a film
about the car's creator.
   Francis Coppola's ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream,'' which
chronicles the life of rebel automaker Preston Tucker, opened over
the weekend at theaters nationwide.
   But two major collector-car auctioneers based here disagree on
the movie's impact on the car's actual value. Rick Cole says the
current $50,000 pricetag should stay the same, but Tom Barrett
insists the value will soar to $250,000.
   ``It's worth $50,000 and that won't change,'' said Cole. ``It
was the De Lorean of the '40s. It was stuck together with glue and
spit and anything else.''
   Barrett disagrees. ``They are now selling in excess of $150,000
and these cars will go up rapidly with the movie,'' insisted
Barrett. ``They will easily go to $200,000.''
   Coppola has two Tuckers and producer George Lucas bought two as
soon as he finished making the movie with Coppola.
   ``Woe be the guy who runs out and buys a Tucker because of the
movie,'' warned Cole.
   Preston Tucker, with the help of designer Alex Tremulis, built a
safety-conscious luxury car that could be affordable. Barrett said
the only difference today is its affordability.
   When first introduced, Tucker owners displayed signs in the back
window reading, ``You've just been passed by a Tucker.''
   ``They were very fast, could go more than 100 mph,'' Barrett
said. ``The torque was so tremendous the car would kick up on one
side. They would run away from anything at the time.''
   Only 50 Tuckers, with a pricetag of $2,450, were made in 1948
before the big three automakers _ Ford, General Motors and Chrysler
_ allegedly conspired to torpedo the vehicle dubbed the ``Car of
Tomorrow Today.'' There are a surprising 45 left.
   Barrett, whose collector-car auction in Scottsdale, Ariz., last
Janurary brought in a record $32 million with the sale of 1,000
cars, said the Tucker is one of the most sought-after vehicles.
He's owned and sold seven Tuckers.
   ``For an American car built after World War II, the Tucker is
the most collectible in the world,'' he said.
   The most popular car overall right now is a 1964 Ferarri GTO,
which goes for about $3 million. Next is the Tucker, followed by
the 1955 Ford Thunderbird, 1957 Cadillac Eldorado and 1957
Chevrolet, he said.
   Barrett, however, still raved about the Tucker. ``The design was
way ahead of its time. They were way ahead of themselves. It is too
bad they got shut down,'' Barrett said.
   Safety features included pop-out windshields made of safety
glass, a crash board protection cowl in case of a head-on crash and
the center-mounted cyclops headlamp that moved with the steering
wheel.
   ``That was very unusual at the time, and still is, but it was
very clever when you are going into a turn,'' said Barrett.
   ``The rear-engine allowed tremendous room inside. You could sit
four people abreast in one seat. It was a huge car, about 18 feet
bumper-to-bumper.''
   But the Tucker is a four-wheeled relic that will be quickly
forgotten once the movie-hype has passed, said Cole, whose Monterey
Sports and Racing Car Auction on Aug. 19 is one of California's
largest.
   ``I wasn't interested in Tuckers before the movie and I'm not
interested after the movie, either,'' said Cole, adding there are
no Tuckers in his lineup.
   ``A guy called me last week and offered to sell me his Tucker
for $250,000. I told him I'd pass,'' said Cole. ``I'm sure I'll get
another call. As soon as the movie comes out, the phone will ring.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
