<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APArts:TuckerCars Adv14   08-11 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AP Arts: Tucker Cars, Adv 14,0530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug 14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Tucker Collecting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several of the stars in the new movie
``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' were groomed in this southern
Kansas town where wheat is more often a conversation topic than
Hollywood.
   The stars are the 1948 Tucker automobiles.
   Stan Gilliland of the Tucker Automobile Club of America is the
owner of an antique auto restoration business, worked on virtually
all 22 cars used in the movie. In 1973, he staged an organizational
meeting for the club, which now has 210 members, most of whom don't
own Tuckers. He has owned as many as six at a time.
   Hailed as a revolutionary high-powered car, only 50 Tuckers were
made in a Chicago plant where B-29 engines once were built by
Dodge. The autos were engineering prototypes, not production cars,
and no two are alike, Gilliland said.
   In tests, a Tucker powered by its flat six-cyliner 335 cubic
inch engine reached 130 miles per hour. Preston T. Tucker
encouraged employees who test drove his cars to log as many miles
as possible at 100 mph. Gilliland and other club members have
driven them faster than that.
   Probably the most distinctive appearance feature of the car was
its hood-mounted third headlight that turned with the front wheels.
That, and its low, sleek body design captured postwar imaginations
hungry for something new.
   Tucker raised $30 million to make the auto, which he planned to
sell for around $2,500, a price competitive with cars of the day.
   That is also the price Coppola paid 18 Tucker owners to use
their cars for filming. He also utilized his two Tuckers and two
owned by producer George Lucas.
   The movie finally gives Tucker the fair treatment he didn't get
when he sought to manufacture what he called ``America's First
Completely New Car in 50 Years.''
   Coppola portrays Tucker as a hero who stood against the Big
Three automakers (Ford, General Motors and Chrysler), but went
bankrupt after a lengthy Securities Exchange Commission
investigation and a criminal trial that ended in his aquittal.
Tucker died of cancer in 1956.
   ``The automobile makers just couldn't stand for anybody to bring
out a new car,'' Gilliland said. ``I'm not saying there was for
sure a conspiracy, but there was a lot of funny stuff going on.''
   Tucker antagonists pictured him as a high-living con man who
never intended to actually manufacture cars. Supporters saw him as
visionary whose innovations such as disc brakes, padded dash, and
rear-mounted aluminum alloy engine, eventually were adopted by the
Detroit automakers.
   Walker began his fascination with the cars while still a
schoolboy. He read a December 1946 Science Illustrated magazine
article about Tucker's plans for the car.
   He finally got to see one when he sneaked under a sideshow tent
at the Kansas State Fair a few years after Tucker's bankruptcy. In
college, he wrote a freshman term paper titled ``The Startling
Story of the Tucker.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
