<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0562</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jolt applied to interest rates by the
Federal Reserve singed financial markets again, as traders from
Tokyo to Wall Street sweated over the prospects for a global
interest-rate spiral.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 44.99 points
Wednesday to close at 2,034.14.
   The Fed's half-percentage-point hike in the discount rate
Tuesday to 6.5 percent created ``worry on a worldwide basis that
everybody is competing, with interest rates as their weapon,'' said
Hugh Johnson, senior vice president at First Albany Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc. has responded cooly to a
sweetened $5 billion friendly takeover bid from Batus Inc., and
Batus has pledged to continue a hostile bid for the insurer if
management refuses to negotiate.
   Batus boosted its cash offer for a negotiated merger from $63 a
share to $72 a share on Tuesday and gave management until Aug. 19
to respond.
   Farmers announced Wednesday it would study the offer with an eye
to the best interests of shareholders, but Treasurer Jerry Faulwell
hinted the higher price was unlikely to overcome management
opposition to the Batus bid.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insilco Corp. has disclosed it received
several unsolicited buyout offers since a management-led group's
$950 million bid for the high-technology and specialty consumer
products company last week.
   Insilco did not identify the parties involved in a filing with
the Securities and Exchange Commission on Wednesday, but said it
had entered into confidentiality agreements with certain groups.
   Last Thursday, Insilco's board of directors approved a
$29-a-share management offer in what some analysts described as an
anti-takeover defense.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Printer R.R. Donnelley & Sons has fired three
more production workers it believes helped leak advance copies of
an influential Business Week column to a stockbroker, a company
official said.
   A spokesman for the printer said Wednesday that Donnelley had
exhausted all its leads but was continuing to cooperate with a
Securities and Exchange Commission investigation.
   The firings late last week of three workers at Donnelley's Old
Saybrook, Conn., plant brought to seven the number of Donnelley
employees who have been fired or have resigned in connection with
the company's investigation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says it opposes
provisions of an anti-racketeering bill that would curtail the role
of trustees appointed by courts to run corrupt labor unions.
   John C. Keeney, a deputy attorney general in the department's
Criminal Division, said Wednesday that the proposed changes ``would
be disastrous'' to government anti-racketeering suits against
unions.
   Keeney testified before a House Judiciary subcommittee that is
considering legislation to change the rules for civil actions filed
under the Racketeer-Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines has announced plans to base as
many as 700 pilots and flight attendants in South Florida, the home
of embattled Eastern Airlines.
   ``American Airlines is deeply committed to the Florida market
and believes Florida will play a critical role in our future
expansion,'' Robert W. Baker, senior vice president for operations,
said Wednesday.
   American, based in Fort Worth, Texas, also announced the
addition of a flight attendant crew base in Nashville, Tenn., one
of five American hubs.
</TEXT>
