<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0568</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has begun
moving to suspend a $3.6 billion contract awarded to International
Business Machines Corp. to build an air traffic control system,
following a government decision to review the contract award.
   ``The FAA is in the process of drafting a stop work order'' that
effectively would suspend the contract, spokesman John Laden said
Wednesday.
   Hughes Aircraft, which lost out to IBM on the contract, last
week asked the government to revoke the contract. Hughes alleged
that IBM was allowed to undercut Hughes' bid partly because in
accepting IBM's offer the government included the use of used
computers. Hughes had agreed to use new computers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than four of every five people consider
safety to be a serious problem with air travel, according to an
opinion poll published by an association of private pilots.
   The random telephone survey, released Wednesday, also showed
that people regard safety as a far greater problem with air travel
than flight delays.
   The poll was commissioned by the Aircraft Owners and Pilots
Association, which represents 270,000 people who own or fly private
aircraft.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and chief executive officer of
Sterling Drug Inc. has resigned, six months after the company was
acquired by Eastman Kodak Co., because of what one official called
a decline in his authority.
   John M. Pietruski, 55, is the fifth officer of Sterling Drug,
maker of such products as Bayer aspirin and Phillips Milk of
Magnesia, to resign since June, Sterling spokesman John H. Wood
said Wednesday.
   Wood said none of the resignations were prompted by Eastman
Kodak, which acquired Sterling Drug in March for $5.1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Postal Service says it is shelving a major
portion of a contract with Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot that
drew fire from Congress and private industry and spawned a court
test of the service's purchasing rules.
   ``This was clearly a mistake that I hope it is not too late to
rectify,'' Postmaster General Anthony Frank told a pair of Senate
subcommittees Wednesday.
   At stake is a potentially lucrative deal to design and implement
cost-saving procedures for the mail-carrying agency _ a contract
initially awarded to Perot's company without competitive bidding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's merchandise trade surplus rose in July from
a year earlier, the first rise in 15 months, the government reports.
   Economists said Wednesday it was too soon to conclude that the
steady shrinkage in Japan's surplus had come to an end, and they
noted that the surplus with the United States declined again.
   But some said Japanese companies have been raising export prices
lately, something that tends to swell the surplus.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell sharply to a 2{-month low Wednesday as the
jolt of Tuesday's increase in the discount rate kept shaking
investors. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 44.99
points to 2,034.14.
   The dollar fell in domestic trading after closing higher
overseas. Gold prices rose.
   Bond prices tumbled, catapulting interest rates to their highest
levels this year.
   Cattle futures soared their permitted daily limits; stock-index
futures plunged; precious metals advanced; grains and soybeans were
higher; and oil futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
