<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-11 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Continued uncertainty over the potential impact
of the recently announced Iran-Iraq cease fire has helped to steady
crude oil futures prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, rose 3 cents to finish Wednesday at $15.71 per barrel.
The contract had declined 19 cents on Tuesday.
   The September contract for heating oil, which fell 0.43 cent in
the previous session, finished up 0.08 cent at 44.15 cents a
gallon. Unleaded gasoline for September delivery settled down 0.58
cent at 45.57 cents on the exchange, after falling 0.50 cent on
Tuesday.
   James R. Steele, an energy analyst with Refco Inc., said
fundamental changes were starting to affect the refined-crude
products Wednesday.
   ``The driving season is basically over and industrial users are
looking more to buy heating oil than gas now,'' he said. ``From now
until September, users of heating oil will be stockpiling it for
the winter.''
   Steele said the crude market remained confused over U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's announcement that Iran
and Iraq would begin a cease-fire in their 8-year-old war on Aug.
20.
   ``One school of thought says ... this will ultimately make OPEC
more cohesive,'' he said. ``The other school says that once they
stop fighting both countries will need to pump as much oil as they
can to rebuild their economies.''
   Oil prices have been declining in recent months amid speculation
that some members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were exceeding their official production quotas and were
unlikely to soon reach an agreement to limit production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryAuction     08-11 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Auction,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on 10-Year Notes Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 10-year Treasury notes rose in the
government's latest auction to the highest level in nearly three
years.
   The average yield was 9.27 percent on Wednesday, up from 9.06
percent at the last auction on May 11.
   It was the highest rate since 10-year notes averaged 9.54
percent on Nov. 21, 1985. The notes will carry a coupon interest
rate of 9.25 percent, with each $10,000 in face value selling for
$9,987.10.
   A total of $11.0 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling
$20.4 billion.
   Wednesday's auction was the second part of the Treasury's
quarterly refunding. On Thursday, the government plans to auction
$7 billion in 248-day cash management bills in minimum
denominations of $10,000.
   On Tuesday, the Treasury sold $11.1 billion in three-year notes
at an average yield of 8.77 percent, up from 8.23 percent at the
last auction on May 10. It was the highest rate since August 1985.
</TEXT>
