<1ST_LINE>r f PM-American-Expansion     08-11 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American-Expansion,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Adds Crew Bases In Miami, Nashville</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Growing American Airlines is beefing up its
presence in South Florida, home of its shrinking,
financially-troubled rival Eastern Airlines.
   Robert W. Baker, senior vice president for operations of the
carrier, announced plans Wednesday for a crew base of up to 700
pilots and flight attendants in Miami.
   ``American Airlines is deeply committed to the Florida market
and believes Florida will play a critical role in our future
expansion,'' Baker said.
   Fort Worth, Texas-based American's expansion in South Florida is
based on long-term plans and on expectations that the Florida and
Caribbean markets will continue growing, not on the potentially
temporary problems of competitors, Baker said.
   ``...The specific and well-known problems of Eastern really had
very little to do with our decision,'' Baker said.
   But he added the expansion in Miami would ``give us some
additional flexibility'' in case of such opportunities as
availability of Latin American routes currently flown by Eastern or
Pan American World Airways, both of which are seeking labor
cutbacks to avoid service reductions.
   ``I don't think it will have any effect,'' Eastern spokeswoman
Paula Musto said of American's move. ``American is in a growing
mode, and if Miami is their choice, I say more power to the Miami
community and economy.''
   Eastern has some 850 pilots and 1,800 flight attendants based
here, she said.
   U.S. District Court Judge Barrington Parker on Tuesday extended
until Aug. 26 a restraining order prohibiting Eastern from
dismissing about 4,000 workers as part of a cost-saving measure. He
planned to hear arguments today in Washington.
   Eastern, which has lost about $1 billion over the past 10 years,
posted a second quarter net loss of $89.8 million, compared with
net income of $27.1 million a year earlier. Eastern's revenue in
the most recent quarter declined to $1 billion from $1.2 billion.
   The Eastern plan, announced July 22, also calls for elimination
of 140 of its 1,225 daily flights to help cut costs.
   The plan would end nearly all operations at Kansas City,
Eastern's principal hub for the western United States, and
dramatically reduce flights at its Philadelphia hub. Flights to 14
cities also would be dropped under the plan.
   American also announced addition of a flight attendant crew base
in Nashville, Tenn., one of its five hubs. American said it would
staff the new base with 75 flight attendants in October and perhaps
as many as 600 in the early 1990s.
   American also has hubs in Dallas-Fort Worth, Chicago,
Raleigh-Durham and San Juan.
   By January, American will base 160 flight crew members in Miami,
Fort Lauderdale and West Palm Beach, Baker said. The total will
reach 700 within a few years, he said.
   The expansion reflects a rise in flights that already was under
way, they said, and will help in expansion to the Caribbean Basin
that began with establishment of a hub in Puerto Rico about 1{
years ago.
   In two years, American had increased its daily flights in
Florida from 29 to 78 and boarded nearly 1 million passengers in
Florida in the first six months of 1988, compared to 412,000 the
first half of 1986.
</TEXT>
