<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against major currencies this
morning in nervous trading after the German finance minister said a
rise in the dollar to more than 1.90 Deutsche marks would be
``problematic.''
   Gold prices rose.
   The dollar fell to 1.8950 marks shortly after Gerhard
Stoltenberg's statement, then recovered a bit, but remained below
late Wednesday's 1.9155-mark rate.
   Traders said the market was extremely nervous, wondering whether
central banks would follow up on the statement with intervention.
   But one trader in Rome added that the market had shown quite a
bit of resilience to Stoltenberg's comments. ``The market is still
a buyer of dollars,'' he said.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7015, compared
with $1.6910 Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8975 West German marks, down from
1.9155; 1.5875 Swiss francs, down from 1.5995; 6.4260 French
francs, down from 6.4780; 2.1445 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1655;
1,406.00 Italian lire, down from 1,414.00; and 1.2218 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2273.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.85 yen to a closing 134.07 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted lower at 133.65 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.50 a troy ounce, up
from late Wednesday's $428.25. At mid-morning Wednesday, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $429.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $429, up from $427 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.77 to close at a bid $431.79.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.70 a troy
ounce, up slightly from Wednesday's $6.67.
</TEXT>
