<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-11 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices bounced back today on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange from a major drop the day before, while the U.S. dollar
declined sharply against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which plunged
615.49 points Wednesday _ the largest single-day drop in eight
months _ regained 230.11 points, or 0.83 percent, to close at
27,784.98.
   ``There is still a strong bullish sentiment in the Tokyo
market,'' said a dealer at a Tokyo brokerage, speaking anonymously.
``Investors who had been sidelined because of a lack of incentives
to participate in the market are buying depressed shares today
without hesitation.''
   Securities dealers said the stock market overcame negative signs
in New York overnight, including the 45-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average and the sudden downturn of the U.S. dollar.
   They also said activity was centered around strong buying of
large-capital shares by institutional investors who were taking
advantage of Wednesday's drop.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was 600
million shares compared to 700 million Wednesday.
   The dollar, meanwhile, opened at 133.65 yen, or 1.27 yen lower
than Wednesday's 134.92 close. It moved in a range of 133.50-134.13
yen before closing at 134.07 yen, down 0.85 yen from Wednesday's
close.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's sudden downturn to fierce
profit-taking by investment banks, which bought the dollar at the
135-yen level Wednesday in New York.
   However, they said traders began buying dollars in the afternoon
session, which slightly raised the price of the dollar toward the
end of the day's trading.
   ``The low opening is apparently a carry-over from New York, but
profit-taking is pushing the dollar higher,'' said a Tokyo-based
dealer at a U.S. investment bank, also speaking anonymously.
   ``But no major shift is likely as the market awaits next week's
U.S. trade report,'' he added.
   The Commerce Department is scheduled to release U.S. trade
figures for June on Monday in Washington.
</TEXT>
