<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Toshiba     08-11 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Toshiba,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toshiba Machine Plans To Reduce U.S. Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toshiba Machine Co., whose illegal exports to the
Soviet Union drew sharp criticism from the West last year, said
today it will cut its American operations in the face of
restrictions on its U.S. exports.
   ``We understand it is only a matter of time now that the (U.S.
trade) bill will be signed and take effect,'' said Hiroshi
Yamaguchi, the company's senior spokesman. ``So, whether we like it
or not, we will have to trim down the U.S unit sooner or later.''
   If President Reagan signs the omnibus trade bill as expected,
Toshiba Machine, which makes and sells machine tools, will be
barred from exporting to the United States for three years.
   The United States moved to penalize Toshiba Machine for selling
milling machines to the Soviet Union that could be used to build
quieter submarine propellers.
   The sophisticated machines are prohibited from sale to Soviet
bloc countries by an international agreement of the Paris-based
Coordinating Committee for Multilateral Export Controls.
   Reagan is expected to sign the bill as early as next week.
   Toshiba Machine's wholly-owned U.S. subsidiary, Toshiba Machine
Co., America, based in the Chicago suburb of Elk Grove Villege, has
sales and maintenence responsibilities in the United States. It has
85 employees, 55 of them locally hired, and offices in Los Angeles,
New York and Toronto, Canada.
   ``We will try to protect the interests of our locally hired
peple as much as possible,'' said Yamaguchi. ``But eventually, the
sales function of the U.S. unit will inevitably be removed because
we won't be able to sell in the U.S. for three years.''
   Exports to the United States accounted for 12.2 percent of
Toshiba Machine's sales in fiscal 1987. The company expects a sharp
decline in its exports to the United States for the current fiscal
year, which began in April, but its total sales will likely
increase because of brisk domestic demand, Yamaguchi said.
   The U.S. trade bill also bars Toshiba Machine's parent, the
electronic giant Toshiba Corp., from sales to the U.S. government
for three years for poor supervision of its subsidiary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
