<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FederalPay     08-11 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federal Pay,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House-Senate Conferees Agree on 4.1 Percent Raises for Federal
Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's 4.4 million civilian
and military employees would receive a 4.1 percent pay increase
starting Jan. 1 under an agreement by a House-Senate conference
committee.
   President Reagan, who had recommended a 2 percent increase for
civilian workers and a 4.3 percent hike for the military, is
expected to approve the raise after final congressional action on
the Treasury-Postal Service appropriations bill which authorizes it.
   The $4 billion total cost of the 1989 raise _ which will hike
the salary of the highest-paid career civil servant from $77,500 to
$80,775 _ is to be absorbed by agency budgets already approved or
nearing approval.
   The pay raise measure was relatively noncontroversial because
members of Congress were among 5,000 top officials excluded. Also
excluded were federal judges and Cabinet secretaries, deputy
secretaries, and directors and undersecretaries of the departments
and major agencies.
   However, the conferees decided at the last minute to give the
raise to 7,000 members of the Senior Executive Service, the
top-ranking career employees.
</TEXT>
