<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Italy-FAO-Drought     08-11 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Italy-FAO-Drought,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAO Projects Decline in World Grain Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World grain production is projected to decline for
the second consecutive year as a result of the drought in North
America, causing stocks to plunge at a record rate, the U.N. Food
and Agriculture Organization reported Thursday.
   Although widespread rain in July provided some relief, it only
averted further deterioration of the corn and spring wheat crops,
which had already suffered severe losses, the agency said in its
August issue of Food Outlook.
   The report said FAO's forecast of 1988 world grain production
has been lowered further to 1.772 billion metric tons, down 24
million tons from the previous year and 13 million tons from last
month's forecast.
   As a result of the production shortfall, world grain stocks are
projected by FAO to fall by 80 million tons in 1988-89, the biggest
annual drop on record, the report said.
   At the projected level, global stocks at the end of the 1988-89
marketing year would be at the minimum level FAO considers
necessary to safeguard food security.
   FAO has said the reduced stocks could cause food shortages in
some developing countries.
   The reduction since last month has been mostly in the production
forecast for coarse grains, which is now put at 772 million tons
against the earlier forecast of 785 million tons and last year's
harvest of 819 million tons, the report said. The forecast for
wheat has been lowered by 4 million tons to 516 millions tons, the
same as the below-trend 1987 output.
   In contrast, the production forecast for rice has been raised by
4 million tons to 484 million tons, which would be some 23 million
tons or 5 percent above the drought-reduced harvest of 1987, FAO
said.
</TEXT>
