<HEAD>Sears President To Retire In December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears Roebuck and Co., has announced that Edward
A. Brennan will become president of the giant retail, insurance and
financial services company when the current president retires at
the end of the year.
   Brennan will replace Richard M. Jones, president of Sears since
1986, who will retire on Dec. 31, the company said Wednesday.
   Brennan also will remain chairman of the Chicago-based company.
   Brennan said Jones, 61, a 38-year veteran of Sears, was ``the
primary architect'' of the company's ``dynamic, cost-effective
capital structure.''
   ``His vision has given us world-class financial management
capability and his counsel has been instrumental in enabling us to
efficiently finance the growth of Sears' diversified business,''
Brennan said.
   Jones, a native of Eldon, Mo., joined Chicago-based Sears in
1950 in Kankakee, Ill., and ascended through the corporate ranks to
become vice president of finance in 1980. He was named vice
chairman and chief financial officer before becoming president two
years ago.
