<HEAD>Finance Ministers Issues Cautions on Dollar Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg said Thursday that a further increase in the dollar's
value could lead to higher West German interest rates.
   Stoltenberg said that was only one of the possible negative
consequences of a dollar rise above the then-current level of about
1.90 marks.
   The finance minister said that a rise above 1.90 would be
``problematic.''
   At a news conference in Bonn, the West German finance minister
declined to say what actions the seven major non-communist
industrialized nations, known as the G-7, might take to prevent a
further dollar increase.
   But he said the G-7 finance ministers and central bankers were
not planning any meeting to discuss the issue in the near future.
   After Stoltenberg spoke, the dollar fell against major
currencies in nervious trading.
