midday, largely in response to drops in other markets, dealers said.
   One dealer said expectations were dampened that Wall Street
would show a significant recovery later Thursday after its rout on
Wednesday.
   The morning's brief respite from the interest rate worries that
plagued the market on Wednesday allowed individual stocks to
respond to corporate news.
   The major mover was Shell Transport and Trading Co. PLC, which
plunged 35 pence (60 cents) to 10.19 pounds ($17.32) after its
parent company, Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies, reported a 4
percent drop in its second-quarter net profit.
   Shares in British Petroleum Co PLC, due to announce its results
later Thursday, were unchanged at 256 pence ($4.35).
