<DOCNO> AP880811-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Taiwan-StockMarket 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Stock Market, 1st Ld-Writethru,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soaring Prices Have Taiwanese Stock Market Crazy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Taiwan's stock ..., with one graf to
UPDATE with market closing down. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The index
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizens from housewives to factory
workers are scraping together whatever cash they can and invading
brokerages to join in an investment craze triggered by the
spectacular boom of the local stock market.
   But while the craze has conjured up dreams of instant wealth, it
also has some experts warning of a possible nightmare when the
heated market cools down.
   Brokerage trading rooms have been crowded with office and
factory workers, retired civil servants, housewives and others
anxious to play the market despite official warnings that prices
might soon tumble.
   ``The market is real hot. Many factory owners have to come to
brokerage houses to snatch their employees back to work,'' Su
San-ho, a stock manager at the Well Phones Securities Co. in the
port city of Kaohsiung, 216 miles south of Taipei, said during a
recent interview.
   Taiwan's stock index posted seven consecutive record highs
through Tuesday, when it surpassed 7,000 points for the first time
ever. It managed another record close on Wednesday despite a
615-point plunge on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, but closed sharply
lower today on profit-taking sparked by the declines in overseas
markets.
   The index has soared more than 200 percent so far this year and
35 percent in just the past month.
   Stockbrokers on Nanking East Road, nicknamed Wall Street for its
many brokerages and business firms, have hung huge red balloons
imprinted with the latest stock index showing outside the buildings.
   ``It is unbelievable,'' said John Nelson, an analyst of Jardine
Fleming Taiwan Ltd. ``No one seems to have a good reason for this
incredible rise.''
   Share trading volume zoomed to $116 billion in the first seven
months of this year, a 214 percent increase from the same period
last year.
   The accumulated figure was the fourth-largest in the world after
the Tokyo, New York and London exchanges, according to Jardine
Fleming.
   Many Taiwan companies have set aside a fund for stock
investments, in which profits are shared with employees to prevent
them from sneaking away from work to the brokerage floors, brokers
say.
   They say some office workers even have quit their jobs, figuring
that in two weeks time playing the market they can earn more than
their annual income, which averages about $10,500.
   Several local consulting firms forecast the stock index would
hit 8,000 or 10,000 points by the end of this year.
   But Chen Pao-rei, an economist at the government Council for
Economic Planning and Development, recently warned: ``Share prices
cannot continue to surge without an end. The higher the prices
rise, the sharper the fall may be.''
   Wu Jung-yi, professor of economics of National Chunghsing
University, said the overheated market is ``an irregular
phenomenon'' that could lead to ``share prices falling like
dominoes.''
   Analysts say the latest surge began in mid-July when the ruling
Nationalist Party convened a landmark congress in which it decided
to lift import bans on major raw materials from rival mainland
China.
   The congress was quickly followed by a Cabinet overhaul in which
several aging economic officials were replaced by a younger group,
in a move seen as a precursor to reforming Taiwan's restrictive
financial system.
   This island's robust economic growth also is viewed as a key
factor behind the rising share prices. But analysts note that
Taiwan's economic performance appears to be slowing and should not
have boosted the market to such heights.
   The government projects a 7 percent economic growth for this
year, down from the 1987 rate of 11 percent.
   John Chien, president of the U.S.-based Federated International
Investment Consulting Co., believes share prices have shot up
because ``too many cash-rich people are chasing too few stocks.''
   The local exchange lists only 145 companies. The relatively
small market allows manipulation by major investors, who pushed
certain share prices up before selling for huge profits, analysts
say.
   Another factor contributing to the overheated market is the 3
percent daily gain and loss limit authorities imposed on share
prices. The limits, designed to prevent drastic price surges or
tumbles, have prompted speculation by reducing investment risk,
analysts say.
   The government in June tightened credit in an effort to dampen
rampant stock and real estate speculation, but to little effect.
``Credit is a little tighter but money is still abundant
everywhere,'' said Chien.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
