<DOCNO> AP880811-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0920EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mon-Redevelop     08-11 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mon-Redevelop,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>County Acquires Abandoned Mills For Redevelopment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two abandoned steel mills that have become
public property will be turned into industrial parks and
recreational areas in an attempt to draw employers and jobs to the
depressed Monongahela River Valley.
   ``We want to make sure all the talents we have in the Mon Valley
are fully utilized,'' said Tom Foerster, chairman of the Allegheny
County commissioners.
   The directors of the county's Industrial Development Authority
signed an agreement with USX Corp. on Wednesday to transfer the
Duquesne Works in Duquesne and National Works in McKeesport to the
authority.
   The deal culminated two years of work that began before similar
recommendations were made in March by urban planners and architects
who visited the area as part of an international Remaking Cities
Conference.
   ``The county is taking a risk. Our neck is way out on the line
because now it's up to the county to develop that property,''
Foerster said. ``We thought it's time government took a risk.''
   The private Regional Industrial Development Corp. will oversee
the mills' demolition, a task expected to take three years. As each
section is razed, it will be redeveloped as quickly as possible,
said Stephen M. Barrouk, executive director of the county authority.
   ``It's not going to happen overnight, but it's going to
happen,'' Barrouk said.
   Jim Taylor, chairman of the Mon Valley Commission, which
recommended the sales agreement in a 1987 report, said he's
received numerous inquiries from businesses interested in moving
into the planned industrial parks. He declined to elaborate but
said numerous jobs likely will be created.
   USX sold the two plants, including land, buildings and
equipment, for $3,662,800, or $10,000 an acre, to be paid by
promissory note. The county will repay to USX at least that much
per acre when parcels are sold or leased.
   The county authority and the Regional Industrial Development
Corp. will share responsibility for removing any hazardous wastes
identified by a planned environmental survey.
   Any hazardous wastes found later will be cleaned at public
expense, up to $3 million. USX would pay half of any costs above $3
million, said authority solicitor Scott Irmscher.
   Removing known deposits of asbestos and other hazardous wastes
will cost about $14 million, with the sale of scrap metal expected
to easily cover the cost, Imscher said.
   USX will reserve about 20 acres of the 380-acre sites under a
leaseback arrangement for an annual rental of $1 for 10 years. Over
the next decade, the company can repurchase all or any part of that
area for $1 plus improvement costs.
   USX will continue to make payments to the county, local
municipalities and school districts in lieu of real estate taxes
following the anticipated closing in mid-September.
   ``There's a good chance that if we do it correctly and everybody
cooperates that it will be successful,'' Taylor said.
   ``The changes that we make in these communities are for the next
century,'' Barrouk said. ``So we can't afford not to do it right.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 0935EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Wildlife-IllegalTrade     08-11 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wildlife-Illegal Trade,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade in Endangered Species Up in Holiday Season, Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal trade in endangered or protected wildlife
such as crocodiles, parrots and chimpanzees represents an estimated
$1.5 billion annually, an official responsible for enforcing an
international treaty protecting such species said Thursday.
   Illicit commerce in wildlife tends to increase during the summer
and Christmas holiday seasons because customs officials are often
overloaded and illegal shipments slip past them, Jean-Patrick Le
Duc told a news conference.
   Also, at Christmas, live animals``make good presents,'' he said.
In Europe, for example, parrots and reptiles including baby
crocodiles are increasingly popular pets, he said.
   Le Duc is an enforcement official for the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora.
The convention, in force since July 1975, has been ratified by 95
countries, including the United States, most Latin American
countries except Mexico, and many Asian, African and European
nations.
   It aims to prevent international trade from threatening species
with extinction. Signatories are to enforce bans on commercial
trade in an agreed list of currently endangered species and to
regulate trade in others that might become endangered.
   According to CITES, endangered species include: all apes; the
giant panda; many South American monkeys; the Asian elephant; all
rhinoceroses; many birds of prey and parrots; all sea turtles; some
crocodiles; great whales. No permits are issued for international
trade in these species except under unusual circumstances.
   Le Duc said total trade, legal and illegal, in wildlife amounts
to $5 billion annually. He estimated that illegal trade is ``about
30 percent'' of the total.
   The hotspots of illicit wildlife trade are Southeast Asia,
Japan, Latin America and Africa, though Africa is doing more than
any other developing country to try to control it, Le Duc said.
   To give an idea of how lucrative wildlife trade can be, Le Duc
said a trader could buy a gray parrot in Ghana for about $10 and
resell it for about $600 in North America.
   A press release from CITES headquarters in Lausanne listed 10
examples of illicit trade that have been thwarted in the past 10
weeks.
   In one, ``a notorious, convicted animal trader'' sent crates
with live animals from Equatorial Guinea destined for Honduras via
Spain, the report said.
   It said that customs agents stopped the shipment at the Madrid
airport. In the crates they found five chimpanzees, 12 crocodiles,
nine Mandrill monkeys, 11 Agama lizards, seven tortoises, 17
Saimiri monkeys and 31 gray parrots. Several of the animals were
found dead. The surviving animals were given to the Madrid Zoo, the
report said.
   In two other separate cases, a total of 8,000 baby crocodiles
were shipped from Colombia to Taiwan, it says. One shipment of
2,000 was discovered because of the stench of some 1,500 that had
died.
   And recently, a female Asian elephant arrived in the Dutch port
of Rotterdam from Vietnam ``hidden in a large crate.'' Her skin had
dried up during the one-month journey, and she was ``in a pitiful
state,'' it said. The elephant survived and now is at Rotterdam Zoo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
