<2ND_LINE>PM-US News-Editor, 1st Ld-Writethru,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rosenblatt To Become Editor of US News & World Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new to clarify timing. Picks up 3rd graf pvs,
Gergen said.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Rosenblatt will become the third editor
of U.S. News & World Report in the last four years, the weekly
magazine's owner and editor-in-chief has announced.
   Mortimer B. Zuckerman said in a statement Wednesday that he
selected Rosenblatt, a senior writer at the Washington-based
publication, to succeed David Gergen on Sept. 1. Gergen is assuming
the new position of editor-at-large.
   Gergen said the change will allow him to expand his role as
writer and be an active participant in public affairs television
programming the magazine intends to undertake.
   Rosenblatt, 47, joined U.S. News earlier this year after holding
a similar senior writing position with Time magazine since 1980. He
has been a Fulbright Scholar, director of education at the National
Endowment for the Humanities and a columnist for The Washington
Post.
   Zuckerman said he has admired Rosenblatt ``as a journalist and a
writer for many years.''
   He also praised Gergen ``for his outstanding service to the
magazine'' and said he looks forward to a ``continuing, close
relationship.''
   Gergen became editor of the magazine in 1986 and prior to that
was communications director for President Reagan.
</TEXT>
