<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FAAContract     08-11 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA Contract,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GSA Order To Slow Down Air Traffic Contract, IBM Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
stopping work on a $3.6 billion air traffic control system
following a protest by a losing contractor.
   The protest by Hughes Aircraft earlier caused the General
Services Administration's Board of Contract Appeals to suspend
procurement for the system being put together by International
Business Machines Corp. Hughes claims it should have gotten the
contract.
   The Advanced Automation System is ``a new generation of air
traffic control system ... where the computer is actually involved
in the decision making,'' said FAA spokesman John Laden. The
system, which is to be completed by the turn of the century, is
intended to improve air safety and reduce air controllers'
workloads.
   ``The FAA is in the process of drafting a stop work order,''
said Laden. ``The next step will be for the GSA to decide on the
merits of the protests.''
   Hughes last week asked the government to revoke the contract,
alleging that IBM was allowed to undercut Hughes' bid in part
because IBM's offer included the use of used computers. Hughes had
agreed to use new ones.
   ``We are pleased by the decision and are looking forward to
pleading the case on its merits,'' said Lee Pitt, a Hughes vice
president.
   The contract is the largest award in IBM's history.
   ``We maintain that the Hughes protest is without merit and
should be denied,'' said IBM spokesman Michael Dutton.
   While the contract board's action ``does not mean the contract
has been suspended'' said Dutton, ``it certainly is going to slow
down development of the system.''
   Additional hearings on the contract review are scheduled for
early next month.
</TEXT>
