<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher, Turn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher,
then turned narrowly mixed today on the Chicago Board of Trade in
light trading ahead of this afternoon's Agriculture Department crop
production report.
   The USDA is expected to reduce its crop production estimates,
especially for corn and soybeans, to reflect crop damage wrought by
the summer-long drought.
   Observers generally expect the government to predict about a 40
percent decline in corn production and a 20 percent to 25 percent
drop in soybean production from last year's levels.
   But analysts said few traders were willing to gamble on the
government's numbers or on the market's reaction to the report,
which will be released at 3 p.m. EDT in Washington.
   ``We've talked about it to death. Now everybody's just standing
around and waiting for the report,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst
in Chicago with the G.H. Miller Division of LIT America Inc., a
British-owned commodity trading company.
   Rumors that the Soviet Union had purchased 500,000 metric tons
of South American soybean meal provided some support for the
soybean complex, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
September at $3.82{ a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 1\ cents
higher with September at $3.00{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents higher with September at $2.73 a bushel; and soybeans were 1
cent lower to { cent higher with August at $8.65 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .22 cent lower with August at
69.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .45 cent lower
with August at 81.10 cents a pound; hogs were .12 cent lower to .30
cent higher with August at 45.95 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .50 cent to .83 cent higher with August at 35.50 cents
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply higher on Wednesday.
