<HEAD>Court Freezes Firm's Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court has frozen the assets of a
company charged with misrepresenting certificates for Florida
vacations, the Federal Trade Commission announced Thursday.
   The U.S. District Court for the Middle District of Florida acted
at the request of the FTC, which charged Travel World International
and its parent company, Discount Travel Services Inc., with
misrepresentation. The firms are based in North Ft. Myers.
   The commission charged the firms with falsely claiming that
certificates they sold for $69.50 to $99.50 entitled buyers to
discounts at national hotel chains. The companies also were charged
with failing to honor requests for refunds and billing consumers'
credit card accounts without their permission.
