<HEAD>Stock Prices Slip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with closing figures, comments.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices slipped Thursday on the London Stock
Exchange after an uneven session.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 4.7
points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,835.2. The closing level was between
its session peak of 1,846.2 and its low of 1,828.3.
   Trading volume was 465.4 million shares, compared with
Wednesday's 442.2 million shares.
   Several analysts said recent concerns over the impact of rising
interest rates may have been exaggerated.
   ``People are realizing that the fears that were swirling around
international markets earlier this week after the (U.S.) discount
rate hike were unjustified,'' said Ian Harwood, an economist at
Warburg Securities in London.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve raised its discount rate by half a
point to 6.5 percent on Tuesday. On Thursday, several major U.S.
banks raised their prime rates to 10 percent from 9.5 percent.
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average was off a modest
2.13 points at 2,032.01 as the London session drew to a close,
after opening higher.
   London dealers had been expecting a sharply lower start in New
York and were keeping a close eye on activity there to see if
shares would take another tumble after Wednesday's 44.99-point drop
on Wall Street.
   The London session began on a buoyant note because stock prices
had risen earlier in Tokyo where U.S. bond prices also rose.
   However, equities turned suddenly lower shortly before midday,
and dealers cited a disappointing earnings report from the Royal
Dutch-Shell Group of Companies, which said its second-quarter net
profit was off 4 percent.
   Market watchers said there was no concerted selling pressure,
however.
   The Financial Times 30-share index fell 4.5 points to 1,477.6.
The Financial Times 500-share index fell 2.8 points to 1,047.96.
</TEXT>
