<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SKFResignation     08-11 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SKF Resignation,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Research And Development Chief At Smith, Kline & French Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of research and development for
Smith, Kline & French Laboratories, the pharmaceutical division of
SmithKline Beckman Corp. has resigned.
   Stanley T. Crooke, 43, had been president of the division since
1982, after joining the pharmaceutical manufacturer in 1980. He
oversaw a budget of about $235 million, as well as the opening
several years ago of a new research facility in suburban
Philadelphia.
   The company said in a statement Wednesday that Crooke would be
replaced by George Poste, 44, a veterinarian and cancer researcher
who has been second in charge of research and development.
   SmithKline officials did not offer an explanation for Crooke's
resignation. It follows by several weeks the resignation of James
Cavanaugh, 51, former head of the company's U.S. pharmaceutical
operaions and comes at a time of financial and managerial turmoil
for the company. Crooke was unavailable for comment.
   ``Clearly, SmithKline is going to be looking at its businesses,
including research, to find ways to initiate savings and maybe cut
programs that don't make sense,'' said Joseph Ricardo, a drug
industry analyst with Bear Stearns & Co. ``A lot of people are
going to be singled out and many more heads will roll.''
   On June 16, SmithKline officials disclosed that the company
expected a sharp decline in profits for the second quarter because
of a decline in sales of its two main prescription drugs _ Tagamet,
which is used to treat ulcers and Dyazide, an anti-hypertension
drug. The two products, which are facing intense competition from
rival drugs, account for about $1.5 billion of SmithKline's $4.3
billion annual sales.
   Then, last month, the company reported that its second-quarter
profit had dropped by 25 percent from levels in the same quarter
last year.
   Company officials also disclosed that they would restructure
SmithKline's three-tiered pharmaceutical business in an effort to
gain better ccontrol over the relatively autnomous units, make
communication easier among the segments and increase the company's
ability to respond to competition.
</TEXT>
