<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 6th graf pvs, Observers were ... to
UPDATE with figures from USDA crop report; Pickup 7th graf pvs, At
the ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to forecasts for
an increasing likelihood of rain in the Midwest on Friday.
   Profit-taking ahead of the Agriculture Department's crop
production report added to drop in prices for future deliveries of
corn, wheat and soybeans, analysts said.
   Several private meteorologists said a tropical depression near
the Gulf Coast could bring more rain to the drought-stricken
Midwest, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Soybeans led the decline, with the contract for August delivery
tumbling more than 10 cents a bushel.
   The USDA crop report, scheduled for release at 3 p.m. EDT in
Washington, was expected to indicate further drought damage to the
crops during July.
   Observers were expecting the USDA to predict about a 40 percent
decline in corn production and a 20 percent to 25 percent drop in
soybean production from last year's levels.
   In its report, the USDA estimated the 1988 U.S. corn crop at
4.48 billion bushels, a 37 percent reduction from last year's
harvest of 7.06 billion. The agency estimated soybean production at
1.47 billion bushels, a 23 percent drop from last year's 1.91
billion. And the USDA estimated wheat production at 1.82 billion
bushels, a 14 percent decline from last year's harvest of 2.11
billion.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.82{ a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 3} cents lower with September at $2.97\ a bushel; oats
were 2 cents to 3 cents higher with September at $2.74{ a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents to 17 cents lower with August at $8.54 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
