<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DroughtInsurance     08-11 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Insurance,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Judge Gives Drought Lawsuits Class-Action Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has given nationwide
class-action lawsuit status to farmers who allege that the Chubb
Group of Insurance Cos. breached contracts by failing to pay
drought insurance claims.
   U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin granted the class-action status
Wednesday and confirmed Thursday that it applied to affected
farmers nationwide, not just in Ohio.
   Stanley Chesley, a Cincinnati lawyer representing the farmers,
said he believed the class action would cover an estimated 8,800
farmers in 10 states who could have claims against Chubb. Chesley
estimated it could cost $380 million to pay off all those claims at
once.
   The cases trace to so-called drought insurance offered to
farmers earlier this year. Chubb authorized issuance of up to $30
million in coverage to farmers whose crops suffered major damage
attributed to the drought, but agents sold an estimated $400
million worth of insurance.
   The suits name as defendants New Jersey-based Chubb and its
agent, California-based Good Weather Agriculture. The suits demand
full payments for farmers whose crops were damaged by the drought,
as well as unspecified punitive damages. Lawyers for the farmers
hope the case can go to trial within four months.
   Chubb officials say the company did nothing wrong. The company
recently took out full-page newspaper advertisements in numerous
cities to defend its practices.
   At least 5,000 of 8,717 applicants for drought insurance have
opted to take a double-premium refund from Chubb rather than hold
out for insurance coverage, the company said. Another 1,100 have
decided to take the insurance, valued at a total $40 million of
coverage, Chubb spokeswoman Mary Lu Korkuch said.
   The double-premium offer was made last month after agents sold
farmers more than $400 million of the drought insurance coverage. A
maximum of $30 million had been authorized by the underwriter, but
Chubb maintained that a huge volume of applications in the last
days the insurance was available caused it to be over-subscribed.
   Chubb officials said the double-premium refund will cost the
company about $20 million. Chesley said he will try to invalidate
the double-premium offer, which could have the effect of preventing
farmers from taking part in the class action.
   The nationwide class-action suit will be broken into subclasses
by state to account for the differences in state insurance laws.
   The drought insurance was structured to pay farmers for the lack
of rain between June 1 and Aug. 31, based on a sliding scale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880811-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DroughtRelief 1stLd-Writethru f0142 08-11 0930</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Relief, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0142,0954</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Drought-Relief Bill; Pays Tribute to Farmers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with USDA crop estimate. Picks
up 11th graf pvs, Earlier the ... Also moving on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commending ``the indomitable spirit'' of
drought-stricken farmers, President Reagan on Thursday signed
America's largest-ever disaster relief bill.
   ``This bill isn't as good as rain,'' Reagan said. ``But it'll
tide you over until normal weather and your own skills permit you
to return to your accustomed role.''
   The president signed the measure just hours before the
Agriculture Department issued a new crop forecast that said
production of the nation's No. 1 crop, corn, would be down more
than a third from last year. The drought will cause consumer food
prices to go up an average 3 percent to 5 percent from 1987.
   Reagan, standing before several farmers invited to the Rose
Garden signing ceremony, said the $3.9 billion aid package
``expresses a distinctly American tradition ... of lending a
helping hand when misfortune strikes.''
   Reagan praised Democratic and Republican congressional leaders
for putting aside partisan differences to speed act on the bill,
and the heads of the House and Senate agriculture committees
returned the compliment.
   One of the farmers, Herman Krone, who gave Reagan a tour of his
ravaged corn and soybean crops last month near Du Quoin, Ill.,
said: ``I think that Washington has done one of their better jobs
right here.''
   ``It's a good buffer, and it's probably enough to get most
people over the hump this year,'' said Keith Salter, who is
struggling with his drought-baked wheat, barley and oat farm near
Menoken, N.D.
   ``It won't be like a crop, but it's better than nothing,'' he
said.
   Reagan said the legislation, which also provides assistance to
dairy cattlemen and ethanol producers, ``represents the largest
disaster relief measure in history.''
   ``Congratulations to America's farmers for the indomitable
spirit with which they have been facing this crisis,'' he said.
   The USDA report estimated this year's corn harvest at 4.48
billion bushels, down 37 percent from 1987, and the soybean harvest
at 1.47 billion bushels, down 23 percent from last year.
   Production of all wheat was indicated at 1.82 billion bushels,
down 13 percent.
   Earlier, the National Weather Service said that its 10-day
outlook promised little relief from the dry spell, with the
exception of rains spawned by tropical storm Beryl in the Southeast.
   The disaster-relief measure, among other things, provides aid
for farmers suffering crop losses of more than 35 percent of their
expected harvest because of the drought or other calamities. The
payments would be equal to 65 percent of the lost income. Farmers
whose crop losses exceeded 75 percent of the expected yield would
receive payments equal to 90 percent of lost income.
   The measure also makes feed assistance available for producers
of many varieties of livestock, including cattle, sheep, goats,
pigs, poultry, horses used for food or in food production and fish
used for food.
   Money for the payments is expected to come from savings that the
government will realize as a result of the drought, since farm
income-support payments are based in part on how much individual
growers produce. With crops down because of the drought, the amount
the government-owned Commodity Credit Corp. must put out in such
payments is down also.
   Reagan noted that he was at one point concerned that the bill
would be overloaded with costly special-interest provisions, and
quoted Krone as telling him, `Let's save the Christmas trees for
the 25th of December.''
   ``Well, we've done just that,'' Reagan said.
   The Agriculture Department said farmers intending to apply for
relief under the drought bill should organize all their records and
other evidence of their crop losses. The department said, however,
that the Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation Service would
not be ready to start accepting applications for several weeks.
   Once the preliminary rule-making for the program is complete,
farmers will apply to their ASCS county agent for both the disaster
payments and livestock feed assistance. Farmers seeking government
loans also available under the program should contact their local
Farmers Home Administration offices, USDA said.
   As approved by the Senate, the measure would have allowed
ethanol manufacturers to buy as much as 2 million taxpayer-owned
bushels of corn a month each at bargain prices. Ethanol is ethyl
alcohol that is mixed with gasoline to form the fuel gasohol.
   The final version Reagan signed makes the program optional, and
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng is not expected to put it in
effect. The measure also would put the subsidy off limits to huge
corporations.
   ``It's not a perfect solution, but it is a helping hand to those
in need out there,'' said Rep. E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas,
chairman of the House Agriculture Committee. ``As I've stated all
along, hold on, help is coming. It's a compassionate, sensitive
piece of legislation that hopefully will keep most of those that
are suffering because of the drought in business.''
   ``It's safe to say, without this bill, hundreds of thousands of
farmers and ranchers would have faced bankruptcy this fall,'' said
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the Senate Agriculture
Committee.
   ``From a standpoint of proceeeding in farming, it'll make a
difference, whether the man farms after this year or not,'' Krone
said.
   Asked if he could use some of the water being generously spread
over the White House north lawn by an elaborate sprinkler system,
Krone replied: ``If I had the water, I'd be sprinkling my crops.''
</TEXT>
