<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     08-11 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Extends Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. on Thursday extended its $4.4
billion tender offer for Farmers Insurance Group Inc. in what was
described as a plan to demonstrate shareholders' support for the
proposed buyout.
   The $63-a-share cash tender offer to Farmers' shareholders, set
to expire Thursday, was extended until midnight Wednesday, the
Louisville, Ky.-based tobacco and retailing company said.
   That is two days before the deadline on a parallel offer to
management that offers $72 a share in cash if a friendly deal can
be forged.
   Farmers, which has said it would consider the higher bid, had no
comment on the extension.
   The $63-a-share offer values the company at $4.4 billion; the
$72-a-share offer for a friendly merger values it at $5 billion.
   It is customary to announce the number of shares stockholders
have tendered, or offered to sell, when an offer is extended. With
the extension of its $63-a-share offer, Batus expects to have
received offers from a significant number of shareholders before
the deadline set on the higher bid to management.
   Announcing strong shareholder support would increase pressure on
Farmers' management to negotiate a friendly buyout, said spokesman
Gene Russell.
   As of Aug. 10, owners of 17 percent of Farmers' stock had
offered to sell their shares, Batus said Thursday.
   That is considerably fewer than the approximately 30 percent
Batus reported had been tendered as of the last extension of the
offer. Russell attributed the difference to institutional traders'
practice of tendering their shares immediately before such
deadlines and then withdrawing them until the next deadline looms.
   Los Angeles-based Farmers and Batus, a subsidiary of BAT
Industries PLC of Great Britain, also are fighting the takeover
battle before insurance regulators in nine states.
</TEXT>
