<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0497</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market swung back and forth in a
narrow range Thursday, struggling to stabilize after its recent
steep decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which had fallen nearly
100 points over the five previous sessions, rose 5.16 to 2,039.30.
   But declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 4 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
666 up, 828 down and 502 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 173 million shares,
against 200.95 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 201.30 million shares.
   Analysts said the market's drop over the past week had pushed
prices down to levels where they attracted some buyers looking for
``bargains.''
   But they also said widespread concern persisted over the recent
rise in interest rates.
   Many large banks across the country raised their prime lending
rates Thursday from 9.5 percent to 10 percent, two days after the
Federal Reserve increased the rate it charges on loans to private
financial institutions.
   The timing of the Federal Reserve's increase in its discount
rate from 6 percent to 6.5 percent suggested to many Wall Streeters
that the Fed was seriously worried about inflation and was becoming
more aggressive in an attempt to stop it from heating up.
   For one thing, the rate increase came just as the Treasury was
beginning a quarterly sale of debt securities.
   Gainers among the blue chips that make up the Dow included
International Business Machines, up [ at 119; Eastman Kodak, up ~
at 43]; General Motors, up [ at 75~, and American Express, up { at
28.
   American depositary receipts of leading Japanese issues, which
have been very volatile lately, chalked up broad gains. Matsushita
jumped 11 to 217; Honda Motor 9} to 171~; TDK 4{ to 80{; Hitachi 7}
to 143; Pioneer Electronics 5{ to 58}, and Kyocera 3[ to 89].
   Iroquois Brands, an American Stock Exchange issue, climbed 2\ to
24. The company said it was considering the sale of its two main
operating subsidiaries.
   Convergent Inc. jumped 2{ to 5 15-16 in the over-the-counter
market. Unisys Corp. agreed to acquire the company for $7 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $5.38 billion, or 0.21
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .37 to 148.60.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.07 to 302.26, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up .85 at 262.75.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
.60 to 379.11. At the Amex, the market value index closed at
