<2ND_LINE>AM-Prime Rate, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0201,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Waste Little Time In Raising Prime Rate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 15th graf Economists said... to CORRECT `charge' to
`pay.' Picks up 16th graf, The trend...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lasergraphic NY37</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. banks boosted the prime lending rate
back into the double digits Thursday for the first time in three
years, reflecting the Federal Reserve's drive to push all interest
rates higher to stave off inflation.
   The half-percentage point hike in the prime _ to 10 percent _
pushed the lending rate to its highest level since the spring of
1985. It was the third increase in the rate so far this year and
the second in a month.
   Because the prime is used to calculate a wide range of fixed-and
adjustable-rate loans, the increase is likely to pinch the
pocketbooks of consumers who already have seen borrowing costs rise
in recent months.
   ``It will slow the economy, but it won't stop it in its
tracks,'' explained Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for
the investment firm Nikko Securities Co. International. ``That's a
healthy thing right now.
   ``You try to get your flu shot before you get the flu ... That's
preventative medicine. That's what the Fed is doing.''
   Economists say the rise in the prime will affect small- to
medium-sized businesses and consumers more so than large
corporations, which borrow more cheaply in the open market by
issuing commercial paper, or short-term unsecured IOUs.
   Home equity lines of credit are usually pegged to the banks'
prime rate, while many home mortgages are tied to interest rates
paid on Treasury bills.
   The financial markets took Thursday's news in stride after
weathering the storm that followed the Fed's increase in a key
lending rate earlier in the week.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed
up 5.16 to 2,039.30. Bond prices, which generally decline in the
face of rising interest rates, ended mixed.
   The dollar lost ground against all key foreign currencies,
although the prime rate hike was credited by some European traders
for preventing a free fall.
   Chase Manhattan Bank was the first to announce the prime hike
Thursday morning, with other major banks across the country quickly
following suit.
   The increase brings the closely watched rate to its highest
level since June 18, 1985, when it was lowered to 9.5 percent from
10 percent.
   At the start of the year, the prime stood at 8.5 percent. It was
raised to 9 percent on May 11 and then another half percentage
point on July 14.
   The latest move had been anticipated after the Fed signaled its
desire to tighten credit by raising its discount rate to 6.5
percent from 6 percent on Tuesday, citing inflationary pressures.
The discount rate is the interest the Fed charges on loans to
member banks.
   Economists said banks were justified in raising the prime to the
current double-digit level because their own borrowing costs had
risen. Rates banks pay on products such as certificates of deposits
or money market accounts have been forced up, although not at the
same pace as bank loans.
   The trend toward higher interest rates reflects prevailing
concerns in the credit markets that the economy might be
overheating and inflation creeping up.
   Elizabeth G. Reiners, an economist for the investment firm Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc., said the catalyst for raising the prime came
from the rising federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans
between banks. That rate, which has lingered around 7.5 percent for
most of the summer, surged above 8 percent at the start of business
Thursday.
   ``Usually there's a pretty good correlation between the spread
of fed funds and the prime rate,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
