<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Harcourt     08-11 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Harcourt,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts Narrowed Loss in 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc., the publishing,
insurance and theme park concern, said Thursday its second-quarter
loss narrowed as its sales rose 23.5 percent from a year ago.
   The company, which is based in Orlando, Fla., lost $44.6 million
in the three months ended June 30, compared with a loss of $70.8
million in the same period a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose to $447 million from $362 million a
year earlier.
   The company said it had income of $22.2 million from publishing
operations in the quarter, compared with a loss of $4.1 million a
year earlier.
   It reported income of $12.1 million from theme park operations,
down from $14.3 million a year earlier. Its income from insurance
operations fell to $9.4 million from $10.1 million a year earlier.
   The company underwent a costly restructuring last year as it
avoided a $2 billion takeover bid by British publisher Robert
Maxwell.
   Its interest expense for the latest quarter rose nearly
fivefold, to $78.7 million from $16.7 million a year earlier.
   Before recapitalization charges, the company said its operating
income rose to $38.3 million for the quarter from $13.7 million a
year earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, Harcourt lost $80.1
million, virtually the same as its loss for the first six months of
1987.
   Revenue for the first six months rose to $753 million from $647
million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
